ivier |author3=Alfonso de Mar\u00eda y Campos |author4= Alicia Mayer  |year=2010 |title=El sacrificio humano en la tradici\u00f3n religiosa mesoamericana |trans-title=Human sacrifice in the Mesoamerican religious tradition |url=http://www.historicas.unam.mx/publicaciones/catalogo/ficha.jsp?id=525 |publisher=[[Instituto Nacional de Antropolog\u00eda e Historia]] (INAH) and [[Universidad Nacional Aut\u00f3noma de M\u00e9xico]] (UNAM), Instituto de Investigaciones Hist\u00f3ricas |location=Mexico City, Mexico |isbn=978-607-484-076-6 |oclc=667990552|language=Spanish}}\n* {{cite book |author=Moser, Christopher L.   |year=1973 |series=Studies in Pre-Columbian Art and Archaeology |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=1\u201372 |title=Human Decapitation in Ancient Mesoamerica |jstor=41263421 |publisher=Trustees for Harvard University |location=Dumbarton Oaks |oclc=940436}} {{subscription required}}\n* {{cite book|author=Tiesler, Vera   |author2=Andrea Cucina |type=[[Amazon Kindle|Kindle]] |title=New Perspectives on Human Sacrifice and Ritual Body Treatments in Ancient Maya Society |series=Interdisciplinary Contributions to Archaeology |publisher=Springer |year=2007 |location=New York, US |issn=1568-2722 |oclc=755866469|doi=10.1007/978-0-387-48871-4 |isbn=978-0-387-09524-0 }}\n* {{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lkwfWWpXTxIC&pg=PA123&lpg=PA123&dq=maya+%22human+sacrifice%22+dresden+codex&source=bl&ots=HrhjtmFQR1&sig=ynJ2Kzn8YryQUQAlpIkPAXSqaXQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qppiUfaPMaX60gWYtYDABg&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=maya%20%22human%20sacrifice%22%20dresden%20codex&f=false |year=2007 |author=Vail, Gabrielle   |author2=Christine Hern\u00e1ndez |chapter=Human Sacrifice in Late Postclassic Maya Iconography and Texts |title=New Perspectives on Human Sacrifice and Ritual Body Treatment in Ancient Maya Society |editor=Vera Tiesler and Andrea Cucina |publisher=Springer |pages=120\u2013164 |isbn=9780387488714}}\n{{refend}}<!-- END biblio format style -->\n\n[[Category:Human sacrifice]]\n[[Category:Maya mythology and religion]]\n[[Category:Human trophy collecting]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_sacrifice_in_Maya_culture"}
{"title_page": "Hugh Downs", "text_new": "{{short description|American broadcaster}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name           = Hugh Downs\n|birth_name     = Hugh Malcolm Downs\n|image          = Hugh Downs 1972.JPG\n|image_size     = 225px\n|caption        = Hugh Downs in 1972\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1921|2|14}}\n|birth_place    = [[Akron, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|death_cause    = \n|resting_place  = \n|occupation     = Television broadcaster, host, producer, author\n|years_active   = 1945\u20131999\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Ruth Shaheen|1944|2017|reason=her death}}\n|children       = 2\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Malcolm Downs''' (born February 14, 1921) is a retired American [[Television presenter|broadcaster]], [[television host]], [[news anchor]], TV producer, author, game show host, and music composer. He is perhaps best known for his roles as co-host of the [[NBC News]] program ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' from 1962\u201371<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mink |first1=Eric |last2=Dolphin |first2=Laurie |last3=Brown |first3=Christian |editor1-last=Dolphin |editor1-first=Laurie |editor2-last=Brown |editor2-first=Christian |title=This is Today: A Window On Our Times |language=English |publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing |date=October 1, 2003 |isbn=0740738534 |page=xiii |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XC5oCPxkPtUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:0740738534#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>, host of the ''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]'' game show from 1958\u201369<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fiftiesweb.com/tv/concentration/ |website=fiftiesweb.com |title=Concentration |access-date=Jan 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=ryan>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=hLiAiSxao5wC&q=Hugh+Downs |last=Ryan |first=Steve |title=Classic Concentration: The Game, the Show, the Puzzles |page=13 |publisher=Sterling Publishing Company |year=1991 |isbn=9780806984681 |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>, and anchor of the [[ABC News]] [[news magazine|magazine]] ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' from 1978\u201399.<ref name=post>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1999/05/06/host-hugh-downs-to-leave-2020/ca432d48-d528-44fe-90e5-b13632e0081d/ |title=Host Hugh Downs To Leave '20/20' |author=Lisa de Moraes |date=May 6, 1999 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> He also served as announcer/sidekick for ''[[Tonight Starring Jack Paar]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atvaudio.com/ata_category_search.php?current_page=1&category=T&alpha=T |title=A Matchless Library Television Archive: 1946-1982 |website=atvaudio.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atvaudio.com/ata_category_search.php?current_page=2&category=T&alpha=T |title=A Matchless Library Television Archive: 1946-1982 |website=atvaudio.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>, host of the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] talk show ''Over Easy''<ref name=reed>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gU3uBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=pbs+show+over+easy#v=onepage&q=pbs%20show%20over%20easy&f=false |last1=Reed |first1=Robert M. |last2=Reed |first2=Maxine K. |title=The Encyclopedia of Television, Cable, and Video |page=174 |year=1992 |publisher= Springer US |isbn=978-1-4684-6523-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4684-6521-1}}</ref>, and sometime co-host of the [[television syndication|syndicated]] talk show ''[[Not for Women Only]]''.<ref name=erler>{{cite book |last1=Erler |first1=Robert J. |last2=Timberg |first2=Bernard M. |title=Television Talk: A History of the TV Talk Show |date=2010 |publisher=University of Texas Press |location=Austin, TX |isbn=9780292781764 |page=228 |oclc=355281797 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDowns was born in 1921 in [[Akron, Ohio]] to Edith (n\u00e9e Hicks) and Milton Howard Downs, who worked in business.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/85/Hugh-Downs.html#ixzz0y9EDOn00 |title=Hugh Downs Biography |website=filmreference.com |access-date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Shawnee High School (Lima, Ohio)|Lima Shawnee High School]] in [[Lima, Ohio]]; [[Bluffton College]], a [[Mennonite]] school in [[Bluffton, Ohio]]; and [[Wayne State University]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], during the period 1938\u201341.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://oira.wayne.edu/publications/pub-fact-book-1011.pdf |title=2010-2011 Fact Book |publisher=Wayne State University |page=61 |year=2010 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a radio announcer and program director at [[WIMA (AM)|WLOK]] in [[Lima, Ohio]], after his first year of college.<ref name=\"Cat\"/> In 1940 he moved on to [[WWJ (AM)|WWJ]] in [[Detroit]]. Downs served in the [[United States Army]] during [[World War II]] in 1943 and then joined the [[NBC radio network]] at [[WMAQ (AM)|WMAQ]] as an announcer in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], where he lived until 1954.<ref name=\"Cat\">{{Cite book|editor-last=Rayburn|editor-first=John|page=256|title=Cat Whiskers and Talking Furniture: Memoir of Radio and Television Broadcasting|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|url=https://books.google.com/?id=79bOhN089foC&pg=PA56&dq=freeman+gosden#v=onepage&q=wmaq&f=false|isbn=978-0-7864-3697-2|accessdate=September 15, 2010}}</ref>  While at WMAQ Downs also acted, including as the \"co-pilot\" in the \"Uncle Ned's Squadron\" program in 1951.  He married a coworker, Ruth Shaheen in 1944, three days after his 23rd birthday. He also attended [[Columbia University]] in [[New York City]] during 1955\u201356.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol22/vol22_iss10/record2210.22.html |title=Hugh Downs Hosts Appreciation for Popular Physicist Motz |author=Bob Nelson |year=1997 |website=columbia.edu |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Television career==\n[[File:Hugh Downs and daughter Deirdre 1960.JPG|thumb|right|Downs and daughter, Deirdre (1960)]]\n[[File:Jack Paar Hugh Downs Jose Melis Jack Paar Tonight Show 1960.JPG|thumb|right|[[Jack Paar]], Downs, [[Jose Melis]] on ''[[The Tonight Show]]''; Downs was host Paar's announcer.]]\n[[File:Hugh downs darren Mcgavin riverboat 1960.JPG|right|thumb|With [[Darren McGavin]] on the [[Theatrical scenery|set]] of the TV series ''[[Riverboat (TV series)|Riverboat]]'']]\nDowns made his first television news broadcast in September 1945 from the still experimental studio of [[WBBM-TV|WBKB-TV]] (now WBBM-TV), a station then owned by the Balaban and Katz theater subsidiary of [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nDowns became a television regular, announcing for ''[[Hawkins Falls]]'' in 1950, the first successful television [[soap opera]], which was sponsored by [[Lever Brothers]] ''Surf'' detergent. He also announced the [[Burr Tillstrom]] children's show ''[[Kukla, Fran and Ollie]]'' from the [[NBC]] studios at Chicago's [[Merchandise Mart]] after the network picked up the program from WBKB. In March 1954, Downs moved to [[New York City]] to accept a position as announcer for [[Pat Weaver]]'s ''[[Home (1954 TV series)|The Home Show]]'' starring [[Arlene Francis]]. That program lasted until August 1957. He was the announcer for [[Sid Caesar]]'s ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' for the 1956\u201357 season, and one of NBC Radio's ''[[Monitor (NBC Radio)|Monitor]]'' \"Communicators\" from 1955\u20131959.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monitorbeacon.net/communicators.html|title=Monitor's Communicators|publisher=MonitorBeacon.net|accessdate=August 10, 2010}}</ref> Downs became a bona fide television \"personality\" as [[Jack Paar]]'s announcer on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' from mid-1957, when he replaced [[Franklin Pangborn]], until Paar's departure in March 1962,<ref name=\"Cat\"/> and then continued to announce for ''The Tonight Show'' until the summer of 1962, when [[Ed Herlihy]] took the announcing reins. Herlihy held that post until October 1, 1962, when [[Johnny Carson]] took over the show, and brought [[Ed McMahon]] as his announcer.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Television|editor-last=Dearborn|editor-first=Fitzroy|editor2-last=Newcomb|editor2-first=Horace|publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers|year=2005|pages=2697|isbn=1-57958-411-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CFXgj7a55agC&pg=PA1288&dq=ed+herlihy#v=onepage&q=ed%20herlihy&f=false|accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn August 25, 1958, Downs concurrently began a more than ten-year run hosting the original version of the game show ''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]''.<ref name=ryan/> Also, he hosted [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'' for nine years from September 1962 to October 1971, plus co-hosting the syndicated television program ''Not for Women Only'' with [[Barbara Walters]] in 1975\u201376. Downs also appeared as a panelist on the television [[game show]] ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'' and played himself in an episode of NBC's sitcom ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/car-54-where-are-you/catch-me-on-the-paar-show-90677/ |title=Car 54, Where are You? Season 1, Episode 11, Catch Me on the Paar Show |website=tv.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns earned a postgraduate degree in [[gerontology]] from [[Hunter College]] while he was hosting ''Over Easy'', a [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] television program about aging that aired from 1977 to 1983. He was probably best known in later years as the [[Emmy Award]]-winning co-anchor \u2014 again paired with Walters \u2014 of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] news [[television|TV]] show ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', a primetime news magazine program, from the show's second episode in 1978 until his retirement in 1999.<ref name=post/>\n\nIn 1985, Downs was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1985, he was certified by the ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' as holding the record for the greatest number of hours on network commercial television (15,188 hours),<ref name=orlando>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1986-03-19-0210030148-story.html |title=Hugh Downs Logs In Most Hours On Screen |last=Holston |first=Noel |work=The Orlando Sentinel |date=March 19, 1986 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> though he lost the record for most hours on all forms of television to [[Regis Philbin]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-hours-on-us-television?fb_comment_id=885667214798114_1007455985952569 |title=Most hours on US television |website=guinnessworldrecords.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA published composer, Downs hosted the PBS showcase for [[classical music]], ''[[Live from Lincoln Center]]'' from 1990\u201396. Downs made a cameo appearance on ''[[Family Guy]]'' in addition to other TV shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/family-guy/the-kiss-seen-around-the-world-64000/ |title=Family Guy, Season 3, Episode 8, The Kiss Seen Around the World |website=tv.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns has been seen in infomercials for [[Boardroom, Inc.|Bottom Line Publications]], including their ''World's Greatest Treasury of Health Secrets'', as well as another one for a personal coach. He did an infomercial for ''Where There's a Will There's an A'' in 2003. His infomercial work since then has aroused some controversy, with many arguing the products are scams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infomercialwatch.org/reports/treasury.shtml|title=The World's Greatest Treasury of Health Secrets|quote=Comments on the 2006 Book and Infomercial |first=Timothy J.|last=Quill, MD|publisher=Infomercial Watch}}</ref>\n\nDowns has most recently appeared in regional public service announcements in Arizona, where he currently lives, for that state's Motor Vehicles Division; for Hospice of the Valley, a Phoenix-area non-profit organization specializing in [[Hospice care in the United States|hospice]] care, as well as in many public, short-form programs in which he serves as host of educational interstitials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0236180/otherworks |title=Other works}} at {{IMDb name|0236180}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2007, Downs was one of the first inductees into the [[American TV Game Show Hall of Fame]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref name=latimes1>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-oct-11-wk-quick11.s5-story.html |title=Game shows get hall of fame |author=Staff Writer |work=Los Angeles Times |date=October 11, 2007 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 1967 in the area of communications.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-49 |title=Laureates by Year - The Lincoln Academy of Illinois |website=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois |accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRuth Shaheen Downs, Hugh's wife, died on March 28, 2017 at age 95.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/ruth-downs-obituary?pid=184794130&affiliateid=45 |title=Ruth Downs Obituary |website=legacy.com |date=March 29, 2017 |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Film appearances==\n* ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964) starring [[Bob Hope]] \u2013 Hugh Downs as Himself\n* ''Survival of Spaceship Earth'' (1972) interviewed along with [[Rene Dubos]], [[Margaret Mead]], and [[John D. Rockefeller, III]] in a documentary on the Earth's environmental crisis\n* ''[[Nothing by Chance (film)|Nothing by Chance]]'' (1975) executive producer and narrator \u2013 a documentary about the [[biplane]]s that [[Barnstorming|barnstormed]] across America during the 1920s\n* ''[[Oh, God! Book II]]'' (1980) newscaster\n* ''[[Someone Like You (film)|Someone Like You]]'' (2001) as Himself\n\n==Public service and political views==\n[[File:Concentration Hugh Downs 1961.JPG|thumb|right|Hugh Downs in 1961]]\nDowns was a special consultant to the [[United Nations]] for refugee problems from 1961\u201364 and served as Chairman of the Board of the United States Committee for [[UNICEF]].\n\nDowns wrote a column for ''[[Science Digest]]'' during the 1960s. He was Science Consultant to Westinghouse Laboratories and the [[Ford Foundation]] and an elected member of the [[National Academy of Science]]. He served as chair of the Board of Governors of the [[National Space Society]] until 2019 and was a longtime president and chairman of the predecessor [[National Space Institute]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Downs |first=Hugh |date=November 1, 1994 |title=Growing to a Position of Strength |url=https://space.nss.org/the-national-space-institute/ |magazine=Ad Astra |publisher=National Space Society |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[asteroid]] [[71000 Hughdowns]] is named after him.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aeAg1X7afOoC&pg=PA1219&lpg=PA1219&dq=71000+hugh+downs#v=onepage&q=71000%20hugh%20downs&f=false |last=Schmadel |first=Lutz D. |title=Dictionary of Minor Planet Names |language=English |publisher=Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg |year=2012 |isbn=978-3-642-29717-5 |page=1219 |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-29718-2}}</ref>\n\nThe auditorium of [[Shawnee High School (Lima, Ohio)|Shawnee High School]] in [[Lima, Ohio]] and the [[Hugh Downs School of Human Communication]] at [[Arizona State University]] in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]], [[Arizona]], are named in his honor.\n\nAs part of the Centennial of the State of Arizona celebration in February 2012, Downs narrated [[Aaron Copland]]'s \"[[Lincoln Portrait]]\" on stage with the [[Phoenix Symphony]].\n\nDowns has publicly expressed support for [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] viewpoints. He opposes the U.S. \"[[war on drugs]]\". He did several pieces about the war on drugs and hemp.<ref>{{Cite book|editor1-last=Evans|editor1-first=Rod|editor2-last=Berent|editor2-first=Irwin|page=346|title=Drug Legalization: For and Against|year=1992|publisher=Open Court|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cat3z6wfYRsC&pg=PA348&lpg=PA348&dq=drug+legalization+for+and+against+hugh+downs#v=onepage&q=drug%20legalization%20for%20and%20against%20hugh%20downs&f=false|isbn=0-8126-9183-0|accessdate=October 14, 2010}}</ref> On his last ''20/20'' he was asked if he had any personal opinions he would like to express and responded that marijuana should be legalized.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.perkel.com/politics/issues/pot.htm |title=Marijuana: Telling Teenagers the Truth about Smoking Pot |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* {{Cite book |title=Yours Truly... |year=1960 |publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston}} (autobiography)\n* {{Cite book |title=A Shoal of Stars: A True-Life Account of Everyman's Dream: Sailing Across the Pacific to Exotic Lands |year=1967 |publisher=Doubleday}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Rings Around Tomorrow |year=1970 |publisher=Doubleday |quote=an anthology of Downs's science articles}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Portnoff |first1=Collice |title=Books--in the news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2354505/rings_around_tomorrow/ |newspaper=[[The Arizona Republic]] |date=March 1, 1970 |page=N-11 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n* {{Cite book |title=Potential: The Way to Emotional Maturity |year=1973 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=978-0-3850-3742-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/potentialwaytoem0000down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Thirty Dirty Lies About Old Age |year=1979 |publisher=Argus |isbn=0-89505-033-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/thirtydirtyliesa00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Best Years: How to Plan for Fulfillment, Security, and Happiness in the Retirement Years |year=1981 |publisher=Delacorte Press hardcover |isbn=0-385-28076-9}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Best Years Book |year=1982 |publisher=Dell Publishing paperback |isbn=978-0-8950-5033-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/thirtydirtyliesa00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=On Camera: My 10,000 Hours on Television |year=1986 |publisher=Putnam |isbn=978-0-3991-3203-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/oncameramy10000h00down }} \n* {{Cite book |title=Fifty to Forever |year=1994 |publisher=Thomas Nelson Inc |isbn=978-0-8407-7786-7 |quote=a collection of essays |url=https://archive.org/details/fiftytoforever00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Perspectives |year=1995 |publisher=Turner Publications |isbn=978-1-5703-6283-5 |quote=50 selections from his ten-minute radio essays}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Greater Phoenix: The Desert in Bloom |year=1999 |publisher=Towery Publications |isbn=978-1-8810-9669-6}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Pure Gold: A Lifetime of Love and Marriage |year=2001 |publisher=Arizona State University Press |isbn=978-0-9717-1600-1}}\n* {{Cite book |title=My America: What My Country Means to Me, by 150 Americans from All Walks of Life |editor=Hugh Downs |year=2002 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0-7432-3474-0}} \n* {{Cite book |title=Letter to a Great Grandson: A Message of Love, Advice, and Hopes for the Future |year=2004 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0-7432-6291-0}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Television|Journalism}}\n* [[ABC News]]\n* [[Barbara Walters]]\n* [[News anchor]]\n* [[Newsmagazine]]\n* [[Sidekick]]\n* [[Television game show]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|0236180}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030417125347/http://abcnews.go.com/onair/2020/downs_hugh_bio.html |date=April 17, 2003 |title=ABC News' bio of Hugh Downs }}\n* [http://www.museum.tv/eotv/downshugh.htm Biography] from the [[Museum of Broadcast Communications]]\n* [http://www.asu.edu/clas/communication/ Hugh Downs School of Communication] at Arizona State University, Retrieved July 5, 2015\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121210124715/http://humancommunication.clas.asu.edu/about/hugh_downs Biography] of Hugh Downs by the Hugh Downs School of Communication at Arizona State University\n* {{C-SPAN|Hugh Downs}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081021152912/http://www.theadvocates.org/downs-interview.html Interview transcript] of Downs in October 2005 on his libertarian views, [[Internet Archive]]d October 28, 2008, Retrieved July 5, 2015\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|hugh-downs|Hugh Downs}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Franklin Pangborn]]\n| after=[[Ed McMahon]]\n| title=''[[The Tonight Show]]'' announcer\n| years=1957\u20131962}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Jack Barry (game show host)|Jack Barry]]\n| after=[[Bob Clayton]]\n| title=''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]''  host\n| years=1958\u20131969}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show Host]] with [[Barbara Walters]]\n| before=[[John Chancellor]]\n| after=[[Frank McGee (journalism)|Frank McGee]]\n| years=September 17, 1962\u2013October 1, 1971}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Harold Hayes]] and [[Robert Studley Forrest Hughes|Robert Hughes]]<br /><br /><small> (first episode only)\n| after=[[Barbara Walters]]\n| title=''[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]'' Anchor<br /><small>himself June 13, 1978\u20131984,<br />with [[Barbara Walters]], 1984\u20131999</small>\n| years=1978\u20131999}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{TonightShow}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Host}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Downs, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Bluffton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Hunter College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:NBC News people]]\n[[Category:People from Lima, Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Paradise Valley, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Space advocates]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Wayne State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Akron, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American broadcaster}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name           = Hugh Downs\n|birth_name     = Hugh Malcolm Downs\n|image          = Hugh Downs 1972.JPG\n|image_size     = 225px\n|caption        = Hugh Downs in 1972\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1921|2|14}}\n|birth_place    = [[Akron, Ohio]], U.S.\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|death_cause    = \n|resting_place  = \n|occupation     = Television broadcaster, host, producer, author\n|years_active   = 1945\u20131999\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Ruth Shaheen|1944|2017|reason=her death}}\n|children       = 2\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Malcolm Downs''' (born February 14, 1921) is a retired American [[Television presenter|broadcaster]], [[television host]], [[news anchor]], TV producer, author, game show host, and music composer. He is perhaps best known for his roles as co-host of the [[NBC News]] program ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' from 1962\u201371<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mink |first1=Eric |last2=Dolphin |first2=Laurie |last3=Brown |first3=Christian |editor1-last=Dolphin |editor1-first=Laurie |editor2-last=Brown |editor2-first=Christian |title=This is Today: A Window On Our Times |language=English |publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing |date=October 1, 2003 |isbn=0740738534 |page=xiii |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XC5oCPxkPtUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:0740738534#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>, host of the ''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]'' game show from 1958\u201369<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fiftiesweb.com/tv/concentration/ |website=fiftiesweb.com |title=Concentration |access-date=Jan 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=ryan>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=hLiAiSxao5wC&q=Hugh+Downs |last=Ryan |first=Steve |title=Classic Concentration: The Game, the Show, the Puzzles |page=13 |publisher=Sterling Publishing Company |year=1991 |isbn=9780806984681 |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>, and anchor of the [[ABC News]] [[news magazine|magazine]] ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' from 1978\u201399.<ref name=post>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1999/05/06/host-hugh-downs-to-leave-2020/ca432d48-d528-44fe-90e5-b13632e0081d/ |title=Host Hugh Downs To Leave '20/20' |author=Lisa de Moraes |date=May 6, 1999 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> He also served as announcer/sidekick for ''[[Tonight Starring Jack Paar]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atvaudio.com/ata_category_search.php?current_page=1&category=T&alpha=T |title=A Matchless Library Television Archive: 1946-1982 |website=atvaudio.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atvaudio.com/ata_category_search.php?current_page=2&category=T&alpha=T |title=A Matchless Library Television Archive: 1946-1982 |website=atvaudio.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>, host of the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] talk show ''Over Easy''<ref name=reed>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gU3uBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=pbs+show+over+easy#v=onepage&q=pbs%20show%20over%20easy&f=false |last1=Reed |first1=Robert M. |last2=Reed |first2=Maxine K. |title=The Encyclopedia of Television, Cable, and Video |page=174 |year=1992 |publisher= Springer US |isbn=978-1-4684-6523-5 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4684-6521-1}}</ref>, and sometime co-host of the [[television syndication|syndicated]] talk show ''[[Not for Women Only]]''.<ref name=erler>{{cite book |last1=Erler |first1=Robert J. |last2=Timberg |first2=Bernard M. |title=Television Talk: A History of the TV Talk Show |date=2010 |publisher=University of Texas Press |location=Austin, TX |isbn=9780292781764 |page=228 |oclc=355281797 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDowns was born in 1921 in [[Akron, Ohio]] to Edith (n\u00e9e Hicks) and Milton Howard Downs, who worked in business.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/85/Hugh-Downs.html#ixzz0y9EDOn00 |title=Hugh Downs Biography |website=filmreference.com |access-date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Shawnee High School (Lima, Ohio)|Lima Shawnee High School]] in [[Lima, Ohio]]; [[Bluffton College]], a [[Mennonite]] school in [[Bluffton, Ohio]]; and [[Wayne State University]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], during the period 1938\u201341<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://oira.wayne.edu/publications/pub-fact-book-1011.pdf |title=2010-2011 Fact Book |publisher=Wayne State University |page=61 |year=2010 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>.\n\nHe worked as a radio announcer and program director at [[WIMA (AM)|WLOK]] in [[Lima, Ohio]], after his first year of college.<ref name=\"Cat\"/> In 1940 he moved on to [[WWJ (AM)|WWJ]] in [[Detroit]]. Downs served in the [[United States Army]] during [[World War II]] in 1943 and then joined the [[NBC radio network]] at [[WMAQ (AM)|WMAQ]] as an announcer in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], where he lived until 1954.<ref name=\"Cat\">{{Cite book|editor-last=Rayburn|editor-first=John|page=256|title=Cat Whiskers and Talking Furniture: Memoir of Radio and Television Broadcasting|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|url=https://books.google.com/?id=79bOhN089foC&pg=PA56&dq=freeman+gosden#v=onepage&q=wmaq&f=false|isbn=978-0-7864-3697-2|accessdate=September 15, 2010}}</ref>  While at WMAQ Downs also acted, including as the \"co-pilot\" in the \"Uncle Ned's Squadron\" program in 1951.  He married a coworker, Ruth Shaheen in 1944, three days after his 23rd birthday. He also attended [[Columbia University]] in [[New York City]] during 1955\u201356<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol22/vol22_iss10/record2210.22.html |title=Hugh Downs Hosts Appreciation for Popular Physicist Motz |author=Bob Nelson |year=1997 |website=columbia.edu |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Television career==\n[[File:Hugh Downs and daughter Deirdre 1960.JPG|thumb|right|Downs and daughter, Deirdre (1960)]]\n[[File:Jack Paar Hugh Downs Jose Melis Jack Paar Tonight Show 1960.JPG|thumb|right|[[Jack Paar]], Downs, [[Jose Melis]] on ''[[The Tonight Show]]''; Downs was host Paar's announcer.]]\n[[File:Hugh downs darren Mcgavin riverboat 1960.JPG|right|thumb|With [[Darren McGavin]] on the [[Theatrical scenery|set]] of the TV series ''[[Riverboat (TV series)|Riverboat]]'']]\nDowns made his first television news broadcast in September 1945 from the still experimental studio of [[WBBM-TV|WBKB-TV]] (now WBBM-TV), a station then owned by the Balaban and Katz theater subsidiary of [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nDowns became a television regular, announcing for ''[[Hawkins Falls]]'' in 1950, the first successful television [[soap opera]], which was sponsored by [[Lever Brothers]] ''Surf'' detergent. He also announced the [[Burr Tillstrom]] children's show ''[[Kukla, Fran and Ollie]]'' from the [[NBC]] studios at Chicago's [[Merchandise Mart]] after the network picked up the program from WBKB. In March 1954, Downs moved to [[New York City]] to accept a position as announcer for [[Pat Weaver]]'s ''[[Home (1954 TV series)|The Home Show]]'' starring [[Arlene Francis]]. That program lasted until August 1957. He was the announcer for [[Sid Caesar]]'s ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' for the 1956\u201357 season, and one of NBC Radio's ''[[Monitor (NBC Radio)|Monitor]]'' \"Communicators\" from 1955\u20131959.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monitorbeacon.net/communicators.html|title=Monitor's Communicators|publisher=MonitorBeacon.net|accessdate=August 10, 2010}}</ref> Downs became a bona fide television \"personality\" as [[Jack Paar]]'s announcer on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' from mid-1957, when he replaced [[Franklin Pangborn]], until Paar's departure in March 1962,<ref name=\"Cat\"/> and then continued to announce for ''The Tonight Show'' until the summer of 1962, when [[Ed Herlihy]] took the announcing reins. Herlihy held that post until October 1, 1962, when [[Johnny Carson]] took over the show, and brought [[Ed McMahon]] as his announcer.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Television|editor-last=Dearborn|editor-first=Fitzroy|editor2-last=Newcomb|editor2-first=Horace|publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers|year=2005|pages=2697|isbn=1-57958-411-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CFXgj7a55agC&pg=PA1288&dq=ed+herlihy#v=onepage&q=ed%20herlihy&f=false|accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn August 25, 1958, Downs concurrently began a more than ten-year run hosting the original version of the game show ''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]''.<ref name=ryan/> Also, he hosted [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'' for nine years from September 1962 to October 1971, plus co-hosting the syndicated television program ''Not for Women Only'' with [[Barbara Walters]] in 1975\u201376. Downs also appeared as a panelist on the television [[game show]] ''[[To Tell the Truth]]'' and played himself in an episode of NBC's sitcom ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/car-54-where-are-you/catch-me-on-the-paar-show-90677/ |title=Car 54, Where are You? Season 1, Episode 11, Catch Me on the Paar Show |website=tv.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns earned a postgraduate degree in [[gerontology]] from [[Hunter College]] while he was hosting ''Over Easy'', a [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] television program about aging that aired from 1977 to 1983. He was probably best known in later years as the [[Emmy Award]]-winning co-anchor \u2014 again paired with Walters \u2014 of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] news [[television|TV]] show ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', a primetime news magazine program, from the show's second episode in 1978 until his retirement in 1999.<ref name=post/>\n\nIn 1985, Downs was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1985, he was certified by the ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' as holding the record for the greatest number of hours on network commercial television (15,188 hours),<ref name=orlando>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1986-03-19-0210030148-story.html |title=Hugh Downs Logs In Most Hours On Screen |last=Holston |first=Noel |work=The Orlando Sentinel |date=March 19, 1986 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> though he lost the record for most hours on all forms of television to [[Regis Philbin]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-hours-on-us-television?fb_comment_id=885667214798114_1007455985952569 |title=Most hours on US television |website=guinnessworldrecords.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA published composer, Downs hosted the PBS showcase for [[classical music]], ''[[Live from Lincoln Center]]'' from 1990\u201396. Downs made a cameo appearance on ''[[Family Guy]]'' in addition to other TV shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/family-guy/the-kiss-seen-around-the-world-64000/ |title=Family Guy, Season 3, Episode 8, The Kiss Seen Around the World |website=tv.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns has been seen in infomercials for [[Boardroom, Inc.|Bottom Line Publications]], including their ''World's Greatest Treasury of Health Secrets'', as well as another one for a personal coach. He did an infomercial for ''Where There's a Will There's an A'' in 2003. His infomercial work since then has aroused some controversy, with many arguing the products are scams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infomercialwatch.org/reports/treasury.shtml|title=The World's Greatest Treasury of Health Secrets|quote=Comments on the 2006 Book and Infomercial |first=Timothy J.|last=Quill, MD|publisher=Infomercial Watch}}</ref>\n\nDowns has most recently appeared in regional public service announcements in Arizona, where he currently lives, for that state's Motor Vehicles Division; for Hospice of the Valley, a Phoenix-area non-profit organization specializing in [[Hospice care in the United States|hospice]] care, as well as in many public, short-form programs in which he serves as host of educational interstitials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0236180/otherworks |title=Other works}} at {{IMDb name|0236180}}</ref>\n\nOn October 13, 2007, Downs was one of the first inductees into the [[American TV Game Show Hall of Fame]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref name=latimes1>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2007-oct-11-wk-quick11.s5-story.html |title=Game shows get hall of fame |author=Staff Writer |work=Los Angeles Times |date=October 11, 2007 |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowns was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 1967 in the area of communications.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-49 |title=Laureates by Year - The Lincoln Academy of Illinois |website=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois |accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRuth Shaheen Downs, Hugh's wife, died on March 28, 2017 at age 95.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/ruth-downs-obituary?pid=184794130&affiliateid=45 |title=Ruth Downs Obituary |website=legacy.com |date=March 29, 2017 |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Film appearances==\n* ''[[A Global Affair]]'' (1964) starring [[Bob Hope]] \u2013 Hugh Downs as Himself\n* ''Survival of Spaceship Earth'' (1972) interviewed along with [[Rene Dubos]], [[Margaret Mead]], and [[John D. Rockefeller, III]] in a documentary on the Earth's environmental crisis\n* ''[[Nothing by Chance (film)|Nothing by Chance]]'' (1975) executive producer and narrator \u2013 a documentary about the [[biplane]]s that [[Barnstorming|barnstormed]] across America during the 1920s\n* ''[[Oh, God! Book II]]'' (1980) newscaster\n* ''[[Someone Like You (film)|Someone Like You]]'' (2001) as Himself\n\n==Public service and political views==\n[[File:Concentration Hugh Downs 1961.JPG|thumb|right|Hugh Downs in 1961]]\nDowns was a special consultant to the [[United Nations]] for refugee problems from 1961\u201364 and served as Chairman of the Board of the United States Committee for [[UNICEF]].\n\nDowns wrote a column for ''[[Science Digest]]'' during the 1960s. He was Science Consultant to Westinghouse Laboratories and the [[Ford Foundation]] and an elected member of the [[National Academy of Science]]. He served as chair of the Board of Governors of the [[National Space Society]] until 2019 and was a longtime president and chairman of the predecessor [[National Space Institute]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Downs |first=Hugh |date=November 1, 1994 |title=Growing to a Position of Strength |url=https://space.nss.org/the-national-space-institute/ |magazine=Ad Astra |publisher=National Space Society |access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref> The [[asteroid]] [[71000 Hughdowns]] is named after him.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aeAg1X7afOoC&pg=PA1219&lpg=PA1219&dq=71000+hugh+downs#v=onepage&q=71000%20hugh%20downs&f=false |last=Schmadel |first=Lutz D. |title=Dictionary of Minor Planet Names |language=English |publisher=Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg |year=2012 |isbn=978-3-642-29717-5 |page=1219 |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-29718-2}}</ref>\n\nThe auditorium of [[Shawnee High School (Lima, Ohio)|Shawnee High School]] in [[Lima, Ohio]] and the [[Hugh Downs School of Human Communication]] at [[Arizona State University]] in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]], [[Arizona]], are named in his honor.\n\nAs part of the Centennial of the State of Arizona celebration in February 2012, Downs narrated [[Aaron Copland]]'s \"[[Lincoln Portrait]]\" on stage with the [[Phoenix Symphony]].\n\nDowns has publicly expressed support for [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] viewpoints. He opposes the U.S. \"[[war on drugs]]\". He did several pieces about the war on drugs and hemp.<ref>{{Cite book|editor1-last=Evans|editor1-first=Rod|editor2-last=Berent|editor2-first=Irwin|page=346|title=Drug Legalization: For and Against|year=1992|publisher=Open Court|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cat3z6wfYRsC&pg=PA348&lpg=PA348&dq=drug+legalization+for+and+against+hugh+downs#v=onepage&q=drug%20legalization%20for%20and%20against%20hugh%20downs&f=false|isbn=0-8126-9183-0|accessdate=October 14, 2010}}</ref> On his last ''20/20'' he was asked if he had any personal opinions he would like to express and responded that marijuana should be legalized.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.perkel.com/politics/issues/pot.htm |title=Marijuana: Telling Teenagers the Truth about Smoking Pot |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* {{Cite book |title=Yours Truly... |year=1960 |publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston}} (autobiography)\n* {{Cite book |title=A Shoal of Stars: A True-Life Account of Everyman's Dream: Sailing Across the Pacific to Exotic Lands |year=1967 |publisher=Doubleday}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Rings Around Tomorrow |year=1970 |publisher=Doubleday |quote=an anthology of Downs's science articles}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Portnoff |first1=Collice |title=Books--in the news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2354505/rings_around_tomorrow/ |newspaper=[[The Arizona Republic]] |date=March 1, 1970 |page=N-11 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=May 5, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n* {{Cite book |title=Potential: The Way to Emotional Maturity |year=1973 |publisher=Doubleday |isbn=978-0-3850-3742-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/potentialwaytoem0000down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Thirty Dirty Lies About Old Age |year=1979 |publisher=Argus |isbn=0-89505-033-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/thirtydirtyliesa00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=The Best Years: How to Plan for Fulfillment, Security, and Happiness in the Retirement Years |year=1981 |publisher=Delacorte Press hardcover |isbn=0-385-28076-9}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Best Years Book |year=1982 |publisher=Dell Publishing paperback |isbn=978-0-8950-5033-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/thirtydirtyliesa00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=On Camera: My 10,000 Hours on Television |year=1986 |publisher=Putnam |isbn=978-0-3991-3203-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/oncameramy10000h00down }} \n* {{Cite book |title=Fifty to Forever |year=1994 |publisher=Thomas Nelson Inc |isbn=978-0-8407-7786-7 |quote=a collection of essays |url=https://archive.org/details/fiftytoforever00down }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Perspectives |year=1995 |publisher=Turner Publications |isbn=978-1-5703-6283-5 |quote=50 selections from his ten-minute radio essays}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Greater Phoenix: The Desert in Bloom |year=1999 |publisher=Towery Publications |isbn=978-1-8810-9669-6}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Pure Gold: A Lifetime of Love and Marriage |year=2001 |publisher=Arizona State University Press |isbn=978-0-9717-1600-1}}\n* {{Cite book |title=My America: What My Country Means to Me, by 150 Americans from All Walks of Life |editor=Hugh Downs |year=2002 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0-7432-3474-0}} \n* {{Cite book |title=Letter to a Great Grandson: A Message of Love, Advice, and Hopes for the Future |year=2004 |publisher=Scribner |isbn=978-0-7432-6291-0}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Television|Journalism}}\n* [[ABC News]]\n* [[Barbara Walters]]\n* [[News anchor]]\n* [[Newsmagazine]]\n* [[Sidekick]]\n* [[Television game show]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|0236180}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030417125347/http://abcnews.go.com/onair/2020/downs_hugh_bio.html |date=April 17, 2003 |title=ABC News' bio of Hugh Downs }}\n* [http://www.museum.tv/eotv/downshugh.htm Biography] from the [[Museum of Broadcast Communications]]\n* [http://www.asu.edu/clas/communication/ Hugh Downs School of Communication] at Arizona State University, Retrieved July 5, 2015\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121210124715/http://humancommunication.clas.asu.edu/about/hugh_downs Biography] of Hugh Downs by the Hugh Downs School of Communication at Arizona State University\n* {{C-SPAN|Hugh Downs}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081021152912/http://www.theadvocates.org/downs-interview.html Interview transcript] of Downs in October 2005 on his libertarian views, [[Internet Archive]]d October 28, 2008, Retrieved July 5, 2015\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|hugh-downs|Hugh Downs}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Franklin Pangborn]]\n| after=[[Ed McMahon]]\n| title=''[[The Tonight Show]]'' announcer\n| years=1957\u20131962}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Jack Barry (game show host)|Jack Barry]]\n| after=[[Bob Clayton]]\n| title=''[[Concentration (game show)|Concentration]]''  host\n| years=1958\u20131969}}\n{{Succession box\n| title=[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show Host]] with [[Barbara Walters]]\n| before=[[John Chancellor]]\n| after=[[Frank McGee (journalism)|Frank McGee]]\n| years=September 17, 1962\u2013October 1, 1971}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Harold Hayes]] and [[Robert Studley Forrest Hughes|Robert Hughes]]<br /><br /><small> (first episode only)\n| after=[[Barbara Walters]]\n| title=''[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]'' Anchor<br /><small>himself June 13, 1978\u20131984,<br />with [[Barbara Walters]], 1984\u20131999</small>\n| years=1978\u20131999}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{TonightShow}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Host}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Downs, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Bluffton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Hunter College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:NBC News people]]\n[[Category:People from Lima, Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Paradise Valley, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Space advocates]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Wayne State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Akron, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Downs"}
{"title_page": "Hubert Hurkacz", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                        = Hubert Hurkacz\n| fullname                    = \n| image                       = Hurkacz RG19 (10) (48199235282).jpg\n| caption                     = Hurkacz at the [[2019 French Open]]\n| country                     = {{POL}}\n| residence                   = [[Wroc\u0142aw]], Poland\n| birth_date                  = {{birth date and age|1997|2|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place                 = Wroc\u0142aw, Poland\n| height                      = {{height|m=1.96}}\n| coach                       = Craig Boynton\n| plays                       = Right-handed (two-handed backhand)\n| careerprizemoney            = [[US$|$]]2,155,757\n| turnedpro                   = 2015\n| singlesrecord               = {{tennis record|won=41|lost=47|details=in [[ATP Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n| singlestitles               = 1\n| highestsinglesranking       = No. 28 (3 February 2020)\n| currentsinglesranking       = No. 29 (16 March 2020)<ref>[http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/rankings/singles ATP Rankings]</ref>\n| AustralianOpenresult        = 2R ([[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2020]])\n| FrenchOpenresult            = 2R ([[2018 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| Wimbledonresult             = 3R ([[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2019]])\n| USOpenresult                = 2R ([[2018 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2018]])\n| doublesrecord               = {{tennis record|won=3|lost=16|details=in [[ATP Tour]] and [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n| doublestitles               = 0\n| highestdoublesranking       = No. 218 (17 February 2020)\n| currentdoublesranking       = No. 230 (16 March 2020)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2020]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult     = 1R ([[2019 French Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2019]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult      =\n| USOpenDoublesresult         = 1R ([[2019 US Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2019]])\n|updated = {{date|2020-03-22}}\n}}\n'''Hubert Hurkacz''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8xub\u025brt \u02c8xurkat\u0282}}; born 11 February 1997)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100166135 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611233204/http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100166135 |archive-date=2015-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Polish professional [[Tennis|tennis]] player.\nHurkacz reached a career-high singles ranking of world No. 28 on 3 February 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/hubert-hurkacz/hb71/overview|title=Hubert Hurkacz - Overview - ATP Tour - Tennis|website=ATP Tour}}</ref> and he is current Polish No. 1.\n\nAs a junior, Hurkacz reached the [[2015 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Doubles|2015 Australian Open boys' doubles final]]. In 2018, he qualified for the [[Next Generation ATP Finals|Next Gen ATP Finals]] held in [[Milan]], where he won against [[Jaume Munar]] and lost to [[Frances Tiafoe]] and [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]. In 2019, he won his first ATP title in [[2019 Winston-Salem Open|Winston-Salem]] by defeating [[Beno\u00eet Paire]] in the final. His best result in a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] has been reaching the third round, which he's achieved at [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] in 2019.\n\n==Early life and background==\nHurkacz comes from a family of athletes. His mother, Zofia Maliszewska-Hurkacz was a junior tennis champion back in Poland, both his uncles were tennis players, while his grandfather was a volleyball player at an international level. When asked whether that has shaped him to be the athlete he is today, Hurkacz replied, \u201cThe [sporting] genes, the motivation in the family, the love for the sport. I think they have helped me a lot.\u201d<ref>https://lastwordontennis.com/2020/01/18/exclusive-interview-with-hubert-hurkacz/</ref>\n\nHurkacz began playing tennis at the age of five after his mother introduced him to the sport. As Hubert's mother practiced tennis, her son was watching and also wanted to try. It was his mother and father Krzysztof who became his first teachers. Then \"Hubi\" enrolled in classes and played more and more often. He became interested in professional tennis, while watching [[Roger Federer]] on [[Television|TV]]. If tennis was not part of his future, he would have most likely chosen [[Basketball|basketball]], [[Motorsport|motor racing]] or continue his education. In 2014, Hurkacz belonged to the group of the most talented young Polish tennis players, including [[Kamil Majchrzak]] and [[Jan Zielinski]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/tenis/810216/hubert-hurkacz-ambitny-dzentelmen|title=Hubert Hurkacz: ambitny d\u017centelmen, \"s\u0142odki ch\u0142opak\" - WP SportoweFakty|first=Wirtualna Polska|last=Media|date=14 March 2019|website=sportowefakty.wp.pl}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2018: French Open second round===\n[[File:Citi Open 2018 Round of 64 (42856885685).jpg|thumb|right|Hurkacz playing at the [[2018 Citi Open|2018 Washington Open]]]]\n\nHurkacz played in the main draw at the [[2018 French Open]] and defeated [[Tennys Sandgren]] in the first round. This marked his first victory at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] and at any [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] main draw event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/5/Artykul/365885,Tennis-Poland\u2019s-Hubert-Hurkacz-into-second-round-of-French-Open|title=Tennis: Poland\u2019s Hubert Hurkacz into second round of French Open|website=Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}</ref> He lost in the second round to third seed [[Marin \u010cili\u0107]] in four sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/tennis/kyrgios-draws-istomin-for-wimbledon-opener-20180629-p4zoo3.html|title=Kyrgios draws Istomin for Wimbledon opener|first=Darren|last=Walton|date=29 June 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn August, Hurkacz made his [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] debut. He began in [[2018 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles Qualifying|the qualifying]] and was aiming to reach his third straight Grand Slam main draw as a qualifier. He did so, beating [[John-Patrick Smith]], [[Egor Gerasimov]] and [[Pedro Martinez Portero]], all in straight sets, to reach the US Open first round. There, he faced [[Stefano Travaglia]] who, like many others, fell victim to the extreme heat and retired. In the second round, Hurkacz lost to the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|2014 US Open]] champion Marin \u010cili\u0107. This was the second meeting between \u010cili\u0107 and Hurkacz. The first had come in the second round of [[French Open|Roland Garros]] earlier that year, when Hurkacz was playing at his first Grand Slam and was fresh from claiming his first Tour-level win against Tennys Sandgren.<ref name=\"realsport101.com\">{{cite web|url=https://realsport101.com/news/sports/tennis/marin-cilic-vs-hubert-hurkacz-us-open-second-round-preview-and-prediction/|title=Marin Cilic vs Hubert Hurkacz: US Open second round preview and prediction|date=30 August 2018|website=RealSport}}</ref> In 2018, Hurkacz received a nomination for the ATP Newcomer of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-awards-2018-categories-nominees |title=Nominees Revealed For 2018 ATP World Tour Awards Presented By Mo\u00ebt & Chandon |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===2019: First ATP title===\nHurkacz started his season at the [[2019 Maharashtra Open]] in [[Pune]], [[India]]. He continued at the [[Canberra Challenger]], where he won the title after defeating [[Ilya Ivashka]] in the final. Hurkacz followed that up by making his debut at the [[Australian Open]]. He faced one of the best servers on the Tour, drawing [[Ivo Karlovi\u0107]] in the opening round at [[Melbourne Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/tennis/hurkacz-wins-canberra-challenger-and-now-faces-tall-task-in-melbourne-20190112-p50qz7.html|title=Hurkacz wins Canberra Challenger and now faces tall task in Melbourne|first=Eamonn|last=Tiernan|date=12 January 2019|website=Canberra Times}}</ref> After winning the first set, Hurkacz lost the match in four sets, all of which were [[Tiebreaker|tiebreakers]]. At the [[2019 Dubai Tennis Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2019 Dubai Tennis Championships]], he defeated [[Corentin Moutet]] in the first round and then went on to win against No. 1 seeded player [[Kei Nishikori]], which marked his first ever win against a top 10 player. Hurkacz lost in the quarterfinals in three sets to the eventual runner-up of the tournament, Stefanos Tsitsipas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/monfils-tsitsipas-hurkacz-dubai-2019-thursday |title=Tsitsipas, Monfils Extend Winning Streaks, Reach Dubai Semi-finals |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Hurkacz played at the [[2019 BNP Paribas Open]], where he made it to the quarterfinals of an [[ATP Tour Masters 1000|ATP Masters 1000]] event for the first time in his career. On his way to the quarterfinals, he defeated Kei Nishikori in the third round and [[Denis Shapovalov]] in the fourth round. In the quarterfinals, he lost to Roger Federer. Following [[Indian Wells Masters|Indian Wells]], Hurkacz achieved a new career high singles ranking of world No. 54. He continued at the [[2019 Miami Open]], where he defeated [[Matteo Berrettini]] in first round. In the second round, Hurkacz took down the 2019 BNP Paribas Open champion, [[Dominic Thiem]], in straight sets before falling to [[F\u00e9lix Auger-Aliassime]] in the third round.\n\nAt the [[2019 Mutua Madrid Open]], Hurkacz defeated [[Alex de Minaur]] and [[Lucas Pouille]]. He lost to [[Alexander Zverev]] in the third round after winning the first set. He continued at the [[2019 French Open|French Open]], where he lost to world No. 1 [[Novak Djokovic]] in the first round.\n\nHurkacz later produced an upset in the first round of the [[2019 Eastbourne International]], with a victory over seventh seed [[Marco Cecchinato]] in just over an hour. He then defeated [[Steve Johnson (tennis)|Steve Johnson]] in the second round.<ref>https://www.thestatszone.com/2019-eastbourne-international-steve-johnson-vs-hubert-hurkacz-preview-prediction</ref> In the quarterfinals Hurkacz lost a tight match against the eventual champion [[Taylor Fritz]].\n\nFor the first time in his career, Hurkacz reached the third round of a Grand Slam. At [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], he defeated [[Du\u0161an Lajovi\u0107]] and [[Leonardo Mayer]] to set up a third round match with world No. 1 Novak Djokovic. For two sets, Hurkacz gave Djokovic all he could handle before eventually succumbing to the top seed in four sets.<ref>http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2019/07/novak-djokovic-survives-hurkacz-onslaught-advances-four-sets/83205/</ref> At the [[2019 Rogers Cup]], Hurkacz defeated Taylor Fritz and [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]] before losing a third round match to [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]].<ref>https://www.atptour.com/en/news/tsitsipas-hurkacz-montreal-2019-wednesday</ref> Two weeks later, Hurkacz defeated [[Beno\u00eet Paire]] to win his first ATP title in [[2019 Winston-Salem Open|Winston-Salem]]. In October Hubert Hurkacz prevailed over [[Gael Monfils]] in straight sets in the second round of the [[Shanghai Masters (tennis)]].<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/08/c_138456587.htm</ref> In the third round he lost to Stefanos Tsitsipas.\n\n===2020: Top 30 ATP ranking===\nAt the [[2020 ATP Cup]] Hurkacz defeated a trio of higher-ranked opponents: [[Dominic Thiem]], [[Diego Schwartzman]] and [[Borna Coric]]. Sixth seed Hurkacz picked up where he left off at the ATP Cup, advancing to the semifinal of the [[ATP Auckland Open]] with victories over [[Lorenzo Sonego]], [[Mikael Ymer]], and [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]].<ref>https://www.atptour.com/en/news/hurkacz-sinner-tiafoe-auckland-2020-monday</ref> Seeded at No. 31 at the [[2020 Australian Open]], Hurkacz reached the second round, defeating [[Dennis Novak]] before falling to [[John Millman]] in straight sets.\n\nPlaying at the [[Rotterdam Open]] Hurkacz lost a three set 1st round match to [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]. He continued in doubles with [[F\u00e9lix Auger-Aliassime]]. To reach the quarter final they defeated third seeds [[Nikola Mekti\u0107]] and [[Wesley Koolhof]]. At the [[2020 Dubai Tennis Championships]] Hurkacz will face [[Alexander Bublik]] in the first round.\n\n===Playing style and equipment===\nHurkacz is a big-hitter, which is no surprise given that he stands 6\u20195\u201d. He is an effective server and can hit powerfully from both his forehand and backhand. But, like many of the Tour's more powerful players, consistency is an issue.<ref name=\"realsport101.com\"/> Hurkacz plays solidly from the back of the court. He plays a low, flat and dangerous ball, while holding the ball in the court. Everyone talks about his serve and forehand, but his backhand is even better than his forehand. All in all, he is an excellent, versatile player who can attack, accelerate and defend, believes former top 10 player [[Wojciech Fibak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/tenis/809964/wojciech-fibak-pod-wrazeniem-gry-huberta-hurkacza-kroi-sie-nam-wielki-sportowiec|title=Wojciech Fibak pod wra\u017ceniem gry Huberta Hurkacza. \"Kroi si\u0119 nam wielki sportowiec\" - WP SportoweFakty|first=Wirtualna Polska|last=Media|date=13 March 2019|website=sportowefakty.wp.pl}}</ref>\n\n===Coaches===\nIn the early years (2010\u20132016), Hurkacz was coached by Filip Ka\u0144czu\u0142a. In 2017, he continued with Wroc\u0142aw coaches Alexander Charpantidis and Pawe\u0142 Stadniczenko, who shaped the tennis career of [[Micha\u0142 Przysi\u0119\u017cny]], while Przemys\u0142aw Piotrowicz was responsible for physical preparation. In 2018, \"Hubi\" decided to work with [[New Zealanders|New Zealander]] Rene Moller, who appeared at his side during the [[2018 Next Generation ATP Finals|Next Gen ATP Finals in Milan later that same year]]. Under his leadership, Hurkacz won the [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] in [[Canberra]] and strengthened himself in the top 100. At the 2019 BNP Paribas Open, Hurkacz began his coaching partnership with Craig Boynton, who worked with such players as [[Jim Courier]], [[Mardy Fish]], [[John Isner]], [[Sam Querrey]] and Steve Johnson.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==ATP Tour career finals==\n\n===Singles: 1 (1 title)===\n{|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Legend\n|- style=\"background:#f3e6d7;\"\n|Grand Slam tournaments (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc;\"\n|ATP World Tour Finals (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n|ATP World Tour Masters 1000 (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#d4f1c5;\"\n|ATP World Tour 500 Series (0\u20130)\n|-\n|ATP World Tour 250 Series (1\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Titles by surface\n|-\n|Hard (1\u20130)\n|-\n|Clay (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Titles by setting\n|-\n|Outdoor (1\u20130)\n|-\n|Indoor (0\u20130)\n|}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n!{{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n!Tournament\n!Tier\n!Surface\n!Opponent\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>1\u20130</small>\n|[[2019 Winston-Salem Open \u2013 Singles|{{dts|Aug 2019}}]]\n|[[Winston-Salem Open]], USA\n|250 Series\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Beno\u00eet Paire]]\n|6\u20133, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n==Challenger and Futures finals==\n\n===Singles: 9 (5\u20134)===\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Legend (Singles)\n|- style=\"background:moccasin;\"\n|ATP Challenger Tour (3\u20132)\n|- style=\"background:#cffcff;\"\n|I