 main draw matches, and in [[Davis Cup]]|small=yes}}\n| doublestitles               = 0\n| highestdoublesranking       = No. 218 (17 February 2020)\n| currentdoublesranking       = No. 230 (16 March 2020)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 1R ([[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2020]])\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult     = 1R ([[2019 French Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2019]])\n| WimbledonDoublesresult      =\n| USOpenDoublesresult         = 1R ([[2019 US Open \u2013 Men's Doubles|2019]])\n|updated = {{date|2020-03-22}}\n}}\n'''Hubert Hurkacz''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8xub\u025brt \u02c8xurkat\u0282}}; born 11 February 1997)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100166135 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-02-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611233204/http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?playerid=100166135 |archive-date=2015-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Polish professional [[Tennis|tennis]] player.\nHurkacz reached a career-high singles ranking of world No. 28 on 3 February 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atptour.com/en/players/hubert-hurkacz/hb71/overview|title=Hubert Hurkacz - Overview - ATP Tour - Tennis|website=ATP Tour}}</ref> and he is current Polish No. 1.\n\nAs a junior, Hurkacz reached the [[2015 Australian Open \u2013 Boys' Doubles|2015 Australian Open boys' doubles final]]. In 2018, he qualified for the [[Next Generation ATP Finals|Next Gen ATP Finals]] held in [[Milan]], where he won against [[Jaume Munar]] and lost to [[Frances Tiafoe]] and [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]. In 2019, he won his first ATP title in [[2019 Winston-Salem Open|Winston-Salem]] by defeating [[Beno\u00eet Paire]] in the final. His best result in a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] has been reaching the third round, which he's achieved at [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Wimbledon]] in 2019.\n\n==Early life and background==\nHurkacz comes from a family of athletes. His mother, Zofia Maliszewska-Hurkacz was a junior tennis champion back in Poland, both his uncles were tennis players, while his grandfather was a volleyball player at an international level. When asked whether that has shaped him to be the athlete he is today, Hurkacz replied, \u201cThe [sporting] genes, the motivation in the family, the love for the sport. I think they have helped me a lot.\u201d<ref>https://lastwordontennis.com/2020/01/18/exclusive-interview-with-hubert-hurkacz/</ref>\n\nHurkacz began playing tennis at the age of five after his mother introduced him to the sport. As Hubert's mother practiced tennis, her son was watching and also wanted to try. It was his mother and father Krzysztof who became his first teachers. Then \"Hubi\" enrolled in classes and played more and more often. He became interested in professional tennis, while watching [[Roger Federer]] on [[Television|TV]]. If tennis was not part of his future, he would have most likely chosen [[Basketball|basketball]], [[Motorsport|motor racing]] or continue his education. In 2014, Hurkacz belonged to the group of the most talented young Polish tennis players, including [[Kamil Majchrzak]] and [[Jan Zielinski]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/tenis/810216/hubert-hurkacz-ambitny-dzentelmen|title=Hubert Hurkacz: ambitny d\u017centelmen, \"s\u0142odki ch\u0142opak\" - WP SportoweFakty|first=Wirtualna Polska|last=Media|date=14 March 2019|website=sportowefakty.wp.pl}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2018: French Open second round===\n[[File:Citi Open 2018 Round of 64 (42856885685).jpg|thumb|right|Hurkacz playing at the [[2018 Citi Open|2018 Washington Open]]]]\n\nHurkacz played in the main draw at the [[2018 French Open]] and defeated [[Tennys Sandgren]] in the first round. This marked his first victory at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] and at any [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] main draw event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/5/Artykul/365885,Tennis-Poland\u2019s-Hubert-Hurkacz-into-second-round-of-French-Open|title=Tennis: Poland\u2019s Hubert Hurkacz into second round of French Open|website=Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}</ref> He lost in the second round to third seed [[Marin \u010cili\u0107]] in four sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/tennis/kyrgios-draws-istomin-for-wimbledon-opener-20180629-p4zoo3.html|title=Kyrgios draws Istomin for Wimbledon opener|first=Darren|last=Walton|date=29 June 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn August, Hurkacz made his [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] debut. He began in [[2018 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles Qualifying|the qualifying]] and was aiming to reach his third straight Grand Slam main draw as a qualifier. He did so, beating [[John-Patrick Smith]], [[Egor Gerasimov]] and [[Pedro Martinez Portero]], all in straight sets, to reach the US Open first round. There, he faced [[Stefano Travaglia]] who, like many others, fell victim to the extreme heat and retired. In the second round, Hurkacz lost to the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|2014 US Open]] champion Marin \u010cili\u0107. This was the second meeting between \u010cili\u0107 and Hurkacz. The first had come in the second round of [[French Open|Roland Garros]] earlier that year, when Hurkacz was playing at his first Grand Slam and was fresh from claiming his first Tour-level win against Tennys Sandgren.<ref name=\"realsport101.com\">{{cite web|url=https://realsport101.com/news/sports/tennis/marin-cilic-vs-hubert-hurkacz-us-open-second-round-preview-and-prediction/|title=Marin Cilic vs Hubert Hurkacz: US Open second round preview and prediction|date=30 August 2018|website=RealSport}}</ref> In 2018, Hurkacz received a nomination for the ATP Newcomer of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-awards-2018-categories-nominees |title=Nominees Revealed For 2018 ATP World Tour Awards Presented By Mo\u00ebt & Chandon |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===2019: First ATP title===\nHurkacz started his season at the [[2019 Maharashtra Open]] in [[Pune]], [[India]]. He continued at the [[Canberra Challenger]], where he won the title after defeating [[Ilya Ivashka]] in the final. Hurkacz followed that up by making his debut at the [[Australian Open]]. He faced one of the best servers on the Tour, drawing [[Ivo Karlovi\u0107]] in the opening round at [[Melbourne Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/tennis/hurkacz-wins-canberra-challenger-and-now-faces-tall-task-in-melbourne-20190112-p50qz7.html|title=Hurkacz wins Canberra Challenger and now faces tall task in Melbourne|first=Eamonn|last=Tiernan|date=12 January 2019|website=Canberra Times}}</ref> After winning the first set, Hurkacz lost the match in four sets, all of which were [[Tiebreaker|tiebreakers]]. At the [[2019 Dubai Tennis Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2019 Dubai Tennis Championships]], he defeated [[Corentin Moutet]] in the first round and then went on to win against No. 1 seeded player [[Kei Nishikori]], which marked his first ever win against a top 10 player. Hurkacz lost in the quarterfinals in three sets to the eventual runner-up of the tournament, Stefanos Tsitsipas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/monfils-tsitsipas-hurkacz-dubai-2019-thursday |title=Tsitsipas, Monfils Extend Winning Streaks, Reach Dubai Semi-finals |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Hurkacz played at the [[2019 BNP Paribas Open]], where he made it to the quarterfinals of an [[ATP Tour Masters 1000|ATP Masters 1000]] event for the first time in his career. On his way to the quarterfinals, he defeated Kei Nishikori in the third round and [[Denis Shapovalov]] in the fourth round. In the quarterfinals, he lost to Roger Federer. Following [[Indian Wells Masters|Indian Wells]], Hurkacz achieved a new career high singles ranking of world No. 54. He continued at the [[2019 Miami Open]], where he defeated [[Matteo Berrettini]] in first round. In the second round, Hurkacz took down the 2019 BNP Paribas Open champion, [[Dominic Thiem]], in straight sets before falling to [[F\u00e9lix Auger-Aliassime]] in the third round.\n\nAt the [[2019 Mutua Madrid Open]], Hurkacz defeated [[Alex de Minaur]] and [[Lucas Pouille]]. He lost to [[Alexander Zverev]] in the third round after winning the first set. He continued at the [[2019 French Open|French Open]], where he lost to world No. 1 [[Novak Djokovic]] in the first round.\n\nHurkacz later produced an upset in the first round of the [[2019 Eastbourne International]], with a victory over seventh seed [[Marco Cecchinato]] in just over an hour. He then defeated [[Steve Johnson (tennis)|Steve Johnson]] in the second round.<ref>https://www.thestatszone.com/2019-eastbourne-international-steve-johnson-vs-hubert-hurkacz-preview-prediction</ref> In the quarterfinals Hurkacz lost a tight match against the eventual champion [[Taylor Fritz]].\n\nFor the first time in his career, Hurkacz reached the third round of a Grand Slam. At [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], he defeated [[Du\u0161an Lajovi\u0107]] and [[Leonardo Mayer]] to set up a third round match with world No. 1 Novak Djokovic. For two sets, Hurkacz gave Djokovic all he could handle before eventually succumbing to the top seed in four sets<ref>http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2019/07/novak-djokovic-survives-hurkacz-onslaught-advances-four-sets/83205/</ref>.  At the [[2019 Rogers Cup]], Hurkacz defeated Taylor Fritz and [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]] before losing a third round match to [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]]<ref>https://www.atptour.com/en/news/tsitsipas-hurkacz-montreal-2019-wednesday</ref>. Two weeks later, Hurkacz defeated [[Beno\u00eet Paire]] to win his first ATP title in [[2019 Winston-Salem Open|Winston-Salem]]. In October Hubert Hurkacz prevailed over [[Gael Monfils]] in straight sets in the second round of the [[Shanghai Masters (tennis)]]<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/08/c_138456587.htm</ref>. In the third round he lost to Stefanos Tsitsipas.\n\n===2020: Top 30 ATP ranking===\nAt the [[2020 ATP Cup]] Hurkacz defeated a trio of higher-ranked opponents: [[Dominic Thiem]], [[Diego Schwartzman]] and [[Borna Coric]]. Sixth seed Hurkacz picked up where he left off at the ATP Cup, advancing to the semifinal of the [[ATP Auckland Open]] with victories over [[Lorenzo Sonego]], [[Mikael Ymer]], and [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]]<ref>https://www.atptour.com/en/news/hurkacz-sinner-tiafoe-auckland-2020-monday</ref>. Seeded at No. 31 at the [[2020 Australian Open]], Hurkacz reached the second round, defeating [[Dennis Novak]] before falling to [[John Millman]] in straight sets.\n\nPlaying at the [[Rotterdam Open]] Hurkacz lost a three set 1st round match to [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]. He continued in doubles with [[F\u00e9lix Auger-Aliassime]]. To reach the quarter final they defeated third seeds [[Nikola Mekti\u0107]] and [[Wesley Koolhof]]. At the [[2020 Dubai Tennis Championships]] Hurkacz will face [[Alexander Bublik]] in the first round.\n\n===Playing style and equipment===\nHurkacz is a big-hitter, which is no surprise given that he stands 6\u20195\u201d. He is an effective server and can hit powerfully from both his forehand and backhand. But, like many of the Tour's more powerful players, consistency is an issue.<ref name=\"realsport101.com\"/> Hurkacz plays solidly from the back of the court. He plays a low, flat and dangerous ball, while holding the ball in the court. Everyone talks about his serve and forehand, but his backhand is even better than his forehand. All in all, he is an excellent, versatile player who can attack, accelerate and defend, believes former top 10 player [[Wojciech Fibak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/tenis/809964/wojciech-fibak-pod-wrazeniem-gry-huberta-hurkacza-kroi-sie-nam-wielki-sportowiec|title=Wojciech Fibak pod wra\u017ceniem gry Huberta Hurkacza. \"Kroi si\u0119 nam wielki sportowiec\" - WP SportoweFakty|first=Wirtualna Polska|last=Media|date=13 March 2019|website=sportowefakty.wp.pl}}</ref>\n\n===Coaches===\nIn the early years (2010\u20132016), Hurkacz was coached by Filip Ka\u0144czu\u0142a. In 2017, he continued with Wroc\u0142aw coaches Alexander Charpantidis and Pawe\u0142 Stadniczenko, who shaped the tennis career of [[Micha\u0142 Przysi\u0119\u017cny]], while Przemys\u0142aw Piotrowicz was responsible for physical preparation. In 2018, \"Hubi\" decided to work with [[New Zealanders|New Zealander]] Rene Moller, who appeared at his side during the [[2018 Next Generation ATP Finals|Next Gen ATP Finals in Milan later that same year]]. Under his leadership, Hurkacz won the [[ATP Challenger Tour|Challenger]] in [[Canberra]] and strengthened himself in the top 100. At the 2019 BNP Paribas Open, Hurkacz began his coaching partnership with Craig Boynton, who worked with such players as [[Jim Courier]], [[Mardy Fish]], [[John Isner]], [[Sam Querrey]] and Steve Johnson.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==ATP Tour career finals==\n\n===Singles: 1 (1 title)===\n{|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Legend\n|- style=\"background:#f3e6d7;\"\n|Grand Slam tournaments (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#ffffcc;\"\n|ATP World Tour Finals (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#e9e9e9;\"\n|ATP World Tour Masters 1000 (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#d4f1c5;\"\n|ATP World Tour 500 Series (0\u20130)\n|-\n|ATP World Tour 250 Series (1\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Titles by surface\n|-\n|Hard (1\u20130)\n|-\n|Clay (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Titles by setting\n|-\n|Outdoor (1\u20130)\n|-\n|Indoor (0\u20130)\n|}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n!{{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n!Tournament\n!Tier\n!Surface\n!Opponent\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>1\u20130</small>\n|[[2019 Winston-Salem Open \u2013 Singles|{{dts|Aug 2019}}]]\n|[[Winston-Salem Open]], USA\n|250 Series\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Beno\u00eet Paire]]\n|6\u20133, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n==Challenger and Futures finals==\n\n===Singles: 9 (5\u20134)===\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Legend (Singles)\n|- style=\"background:moccasin;\"\n|ATP Challenger Tour (3\u20132)\n|- style=\"background:#cffcff;\"\n|ITF Futures Tour (2\u20132)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Titles by Surface\n|-\n|Hard (3\u20132)\n|-\n|Clay (2\u20132)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Carpet (0\u20130)\n|}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n!{{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n!Tournament\n!Tier\n!Surface\n!Opponent\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>1\u20130</small>\n|{{dts|Sep 2015}}\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Poland F5, [[\u015al\u0119za, Lower Silesian Voivodeship|\u015al\u0119za]]\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Futures\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} Robin Stan\u011bk\n|6\u20134, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20134)</sup>\n|-\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss\n|<small>1\u20131</small>\n|{{dts|Oct 2015}}\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Portugal F12, [[Oliveira de Azem\u00e9is]]\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Futures\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} Pablo Vivero Gonz\u00e1lez\n|6\u20133, 5\u20137, 3\u20136\n|-\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss\n|<small>1\u20132</small>\n|{{dts|May 2016}}\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Czech Republic F3, [[Jablonec nad Nisou]]\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Futures\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[Marek Michali\u010dka]]\n|6\u20133, 4\u20136, 6\u20137<sup>(5\u20137)</sup>\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>2\u20132</small>\n|{{dts|Apr 2017}}\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Portugal F4, [[Lisbon]]\n|style=\"background:#cffcff;\"|Futures\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|POR}} [[Jo\u00e3o Domingues]]\n|7\u20135, 6\u20131\n|-\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss\n|<small>2\u20133</small>\n|[[2017 Shenzhen Longhua Open \u2013 Men's Singles|{{dts|Nov 2017}}]]\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|[[Shenzhen Longhua Open|Shenzhen]], China\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|Challenger\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|MDA}} [[Radu Albot]]\n|6\u20137<sup>(6\u20138)</sup>, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20133)</sup>, 4\u20136\n|-\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss\n|<small>2\u20134</small>\n|[[2018 Zhuhai Open \u2013 Men's Singles|{{dts|Mar 2018}}]]\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|[[Zhuhai Open|Zhuhai]], China\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|Challenger\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Alex Bolt]]\n|7\u20135, 6\u20137<sup>(4\u20137)</sup>, 2\u20136\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>3\u20134</small>\n|[[2018 Pozna\u0144 Open \u2013 Singles|{{dts|Jun 2018}}]]\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|[[Pozna\u0144 Open|Pozna\u0144]], Poland\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|Challenger\n|Clay\n|{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Taro Daniel]]\n|6\u20131, 6\u20131\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>4\u20134</small>\n|[[2018 Brest Challenger \u2013 Singles|{{dts|Oct 2018}}]]\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|[[Brest Challenger|Brest]], France\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|Challenger\n|Hard (i)\n|{{flagicon|LTU}} [[Ri\u010dardas Berankis]]\n|7\u20135, 6\u20131\n|-\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win\n|<small>5\u20134</small>\n|[[2019 Canberra Challenger \u2013 Singles|{{dts|January 2019}}]]\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|[[Canberra Challenger|Canberra]], Australia\n|style=\"background:moccasin;\"|Challenger\n|Hard\n|{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Ilya Ivashka]]\n|6\u20134, 4\u20136, 6\u20132\n|}\n\n===Doubles: 7 (3\u20134)===\n{|\n|- valign=top\n|\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Legend (Doubles)\n|- style=\"background:moccasin;\"\n|ATP Challenger Tour (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#cffcff;\"\n|ITF Futures Tour (3\u20134)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:97%\n|-\n!Titles by Surface\n|-\n|Hard (2\u20130)\n|-\n|Clay (1\u20133)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Carpet (0\u20131)\n|}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|W\u2013L\n!{{ns}}Date{{ns}}\n!Tournament\n!Tier\n!Surface\n!Partner\n!Opponents\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss\n|<small>0\u20131</small>\n|{{dts|