20 ATP Cup|2020 ATP Cup]] Group Stage\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} '''[[Roger Federer]]'''\n|2019\n|1\n|0\u20131\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n|0\u20131\n| -\n| -\n| \u2013\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (4\u20136, 4\u20136) at [[2019 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2019 Indian Wells]] Quarterfinal\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|LAT}} [[Ernests Gulbis]]\n|2019\n|1\n|0\u20131\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n|0\u20131\n| - \n| - \n| \u2013\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (4\u20136, 6\u20137<sup>(5\u20137)</sup>) at [[2019 Open Sud de France \u2013 Singles|2019 Montpellier]] 1st Round\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Alexander Zverev]]\n|2019\n|1\n|0\u20131\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n| -\n| -\n|0\u20131\n| \u2013\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (6\u20133, 4\u20136, 4\u20136) at [[2019 Mutua Madrid Open \u2013 Men's Singles|2019 Madrid]] 3rd Round\n|-\n|align=left|'''{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Novak Djokovic]]'''\n|2019\n|2\n|0\u20132\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n| -\n|0-1\n|0\u20131\n| \u2013\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (5-7, 7-6<sup>(7-5)</sup>, 1\u20136, 4-6) at [[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2019 Wimbledon]] 3rd Round\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Marin \u010cili\u0107]]\n|2018\u20132019\n|3\n|0\u20133\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n|0\u20132\n| -\n|0\u20131\n| -\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (6\u20137<sup>(5-7)</sup>), 4\u20136) at [[2019 Rolex Paris Masters \u2013 Singles|2019 Paris]] 1st Round\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|GRE}} [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]\n|2018\u20132020\n|7\n|1\u20136\n|bgcolor=#98fb98|14%\n|1\u20135\n| \u2013\n|0\u20131\n| \u2013\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (7\u20136<sup>(7-2)</sup>), 3\u20136, 1-6) at [[2020 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament \u2013 Singles|2019 Rotterdam]] 1st Round\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Karen Khachanov]]\n|2019\n|1\n|0\u20131\n|bgcolor=EBC2AF|0%\n|0\u20131\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|bgcolor=eee8AA align=left|Lost (4\u20136, 6\u20137<sup>(3-7)</sup>)) at [[2019 Erste Bank Open \u2013 Singles|2019 Vienna]] 1st Round\n|-bgcolor=efefef class=\"sortbottom\"\n|Total\n|2018\u20132020\n|23\n|7\u201316\n|30%\n|6\u201311 <br><small>(35%)</small>\n|0-1   <br><small>(0%)</small>\n|1\u20134  <br><small>(20%)</small>\n| -   <br><small>(-)</small>\n|''Statistics correct {{as of|2020|02|19|lc=y}}.''\n|}\n\n==Wins over top 10 players==\nHurkacz has a 5\u20138 (.385) record against players who were, at the time the match was played, ranked in the top 10.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Season || 2015 || 2016|| 2017 || 2018 || 2019 || 2020 || '''Total'''\n|- align=center\n| Wins || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 4 || 1 || '''5'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n!#\n!width=150|Player\n!Rank\n!Event\n!Surface\n!Rd\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n!HH Rank\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center\" |'''[[2019 ATP World Tour|2019]]'''\n|-\n|1.\n|{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kei Nishikori]]\n|bgcolor=EEE8AA|No. 6\n|bgcolor=D4F1C5|[[2019 Dubai Tennis Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|Dubai Tennis Championships]], United Arab Emirates\n| style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Hard\n|bgcolor=afeeee|2R\n|7\u20135, 5\u20137, 6\u20132\n|No. 77\n|-\n|2.\n|{{flagicon|JPN}} Kei Nishikori\n|bgcolor=EEE8AA|No. 7\n|bgcolor=E9E9E9|[[2019 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Indian Wells Masters]], United States\n| style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Hard\n|bgcolor=afeeee|3R\n|4\u20136, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|No. 67\n|-\n|3.\n|{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Dominic Thiem]]\n|bgcolor=EEE8AA|No. 4\n|bgcolor=E9E9E9|[[2019 Miami Open \u2013 Men's Singles|Miami Masters]], United States\n| style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Hard\n|bgcolor=afeeee|2R\n|6\u20134, 6\u20134\n|No. 54\n|-\n|4.\n|{{flagicon|GRE}} [[Stefanos Tsitsipas]]\n|bgcolor=EEE8AA|No. 5\n|bgcolor=E9E9E9|[[2019 Rogers Cup \u2013 Men's Singles|Rogers Cup]], Canada\n| style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Hard\n|bgcolor=afeeee|2R\n|6\u20134, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|No. 48\n|-\n| colspan=8 style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[2020 ATP Tour|2020]]'''\n|-\n|5.\n|{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Dominic Thiem]]\n|bgcolor=EEE8AA|No. 4\n|bgcolor=ecf2ff|[[2020 ATP Cup|ATP Cup]], [[Sydney]], Australia\n|style=\"background:#ccccff;\"|Hard\n|bgcolor=AFEEEE|GS\n|3\u20136, 6\u20134, 7\u20136<sup>(7\u20135)</sup>\n|No. 37\n|}\n''Statistics correct {{as of|2020|02|19|lc=y}}.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{ITF}}\n\n{{Top ten Polish male singles tennis players}}\n{{Top ten Polish male doubles tennis players}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hurkacz, Hubert}}\n[[Category:Polish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Wroc\u0142aw]]\n[[Category:Lazarski University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hubert_Hurkacz"}
{"title_page": "Howie Morales", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Howie Morales\n| image         = Howie Morales.jpg\n| office        = 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]\n| governor      = [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]]\n| term_start    = January 1, 2019\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[John Sanchez]]\n| successor     = \n| state_senate1 = New Mexico\n| district1     = 28th\n| term_start1   = January 9, 2008\n| term_end1     = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor1  = [[Ben D. Altamirano]]\n| successor1    = Gabriel Ramos<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKay |first1=Dan |title=Ramos appointed to NM Senate |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1269375/ramos-appointed-to-nm-senate.html |website=www.abqjournal.com |publisher=Albuquerque Journal |date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1973|1|5}}\n| birth_place   = [[Silver City, New Mexico|Silver City]], [[New Mexico]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        = Teresa Arizaga (Divorced)\n| education     = [[Western New Mexico University|Western New Mexico<br>University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[New Mexico State University|New Mexico State University,<br>Las Cruces]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Henry C. \"Howie\" Morales''' (born January 5, 1973)<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/GovMLG/status/1081728093952237568</ref> is an American politician and member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] who currently serves as the 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico|lieutenant governor of New Mexico]], since January 1, 2019. He previously served as a member of the [[New Mexico Senate]], representing the 28th District which includes [[Catron County, New Mexico|Catron]], [[Grant County, New Mexico|Grant]], and [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro]] counties from 2008 to 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nMorales attended [[Silver High School (Silver City, NM)|Silver High]] in [[Silver City, New Mexico]] and graduated in 1991. His father, a [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]] veteran, worked in a copper mine and his mother worked multiple hourly-wage jobs. Morales began his first job as a teenager to help his parents make ends meet, and later worked as a shoe salesman and maintenance worker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmexicansformichelle.com/meet-michelle|title=Meet Howie|publisher=newmexicansformichelle.com|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> He earned a Bachelor of Science degree, and in 1998 a Master of Art degree in Bilingual Special Education from [[Western New Mexico University]].  Morales earned a PhD in Education Curriculum and Instruction with a dual emphasis in computer learning technologies and management and leadership from [[New Mexico State University]] in 2007.\n\n==Earlier career==\n\nMorales began his professional career in 1995 as a classroom teacher of special education students in the Silver Consolidated School District.  From 2001 to 2005, he also was the head baseball coach for Cobre High School.\n\nMorales is currently the longest serving volunteer member of the Big Brothers/Big Sisters of [[Grant County, New Mexico|Grant County]]. \n\n== Early political career ==\nMorales was elected [[County Clerk]] in Grant County in 2005.  As County Clerk, he oversaw the transition from over 1,000 outdated voting machines to newer Edge Touch Screen Machines.  He also created a Bureau of Elections Department within the Clerk's office.\n\n== New Mexico Senate ==\nOn December 27, 2007, New Mexico State Senator [[Ben D. Altamirano]] died of a heart attack.  On January 9, 2008, Governor [[Bill Richardson]] appointed Morales to the vacant position that Altamirano held since 1971.  According to Socorro County Commission Chairman Jay Santillanes, \"Morales was personally recommended by the Altamirano family to fill Ben Altamirano's term.  Altamirano's wife, Nina, had considered putting her name in for the position, but decided against it.\"<ref>[http://www.dchieftain.com/news/76997-01-09-08.html \"Morales a nominee to finish Altamirano's term,\" ''El Defensor Chieftain''], retrieved online on December 21, 2008</ref>\n\nMorales ran for the office that he was appointed to in the 2008 general elections and defeated Republican Joseph Gros, 9,561 to 4,019, to retain his seat.<ref>\"Democrats run the table in Grant County,\" ''[[Silver City Daily Press]]'', Online Edition, retrieved on December 21, 2008 [http://www.scdailypress.com/index.php?pSetup=silvercitydailypress&curDate=20081105&pageToLoad=showFreeArticle.php&type=art&index=01  Silver City Daily Press, \"Democrats run the table in Grant County\"].</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Morales officially announced he would run for the office of Governor of New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/elections/elections_2014/race_for_governor/morales-bases-approach-on-second-to-none-mentality/article_e9b269a6-e4b9-5f91-9ffb-e71cb668dce9.html|title=Morales bases approach on \u2018second-to-none\u2019 mentality|last=Mexican|first=Milan SimonichThe New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> \n\nAfter losing the Democratic nomination in a five-way primary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/410306/king-leads-bernalillo-county-gov-vote.html|title=Gary King wins gov primary|last=Writer|first=James Monteleone {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> in June, 2014 to state Attorney General [[Gary King (politician)|Gary King]], Morales continued to serve as a State Senator in his district.<ref>[http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?eid=1&type=SW&map=CTY]</ref> \n\nDuring his 11-year career in the New Mexico Senate, Morales held seats on the Legislative Finance Committee and the Senate Finance Committee, both dealing with state budget matters. He sponsored bills addressing public education, environment and universal health care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retakeourdemocracy.org/health-security-act-nms-single-payer-plan/|title=Health Security Act NM\u2019s Single Payer Plan|date=2017-02-05|website=Retake Our Democracy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales was an outspoken critic of the Martinez administration's education policies that emphasized standardized testing, and he opposed use of [https://parcc.pearson.com/ The Partnership for Assessment of Readiness for College and Careers] (PARCC) assessment in classrooms statewide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dchieftain.com/opinion/editorials/it-s-time-to-end-parcc-testing-of-state-students/article_4bc59446-4323-11e8-bea1-9f2ce3273322.html|title=It\u2019s time to end PARCC testing of state students|last=Morales|first=Guest Columnist Sen Howie|website=El Defensor Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> He spoke out frequently against cuts to public education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lcsun-news.com/story/opinion/2017/05/27/cuts-new-mexico-classrooms/102256886/|title=No more cuts to New Mexico classrooms|website=Las Cruces Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales criticized the introduction of a teacher evaluation system that relied heavily on student performance on the new standardized test (PARCC) in the state's public schools, and he questioned the methodology of the A-to-F school grading system instituted by the Martinez administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/305225/teachers-protest-reforms.html|title=Teachers protest reforms|last=Writer|first=T. S. Last {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  In 2018 Morales sponsored legislation to substantially increase the tax on cigarettes, vaping and tobacco products in order to generate $89 million additional for public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/local_news/lawmakers-to-consider-cigarette-tax-increase/article_fe2bd81a-d883-5607-b3ab-27c5307c7ca6.html|title=Lawmakers to consider cigarette tax increase|last=Mexican|first=Andrew Oxford {{!}} The New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Morales' 2017 [https://www.nmlegis.gov/Legislation/Legislation?Chamber=S&LegType=B&LegNo=106&year=17 Senate Bill 106] sought to create a new cabinet-level Early Childhood Services Department with oversight of already-existing programs like home visiting and pre-kindergarten that are currently scattered through various state agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmindepth.com/2017/02/23/legislator-seeks-to-consolidate-early-childhood-education-programs/|title=Legislator seeks to consolidate early childhood education programs {{!}} New Mexico In Depth|website=nmindepth.com|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  On the environmental side, Morales staunchly opposed controversial federal plans to divert the Gila River in western New Mexico, often described as the last wild river in the West, and he pushed for alternatives to wholesale diversion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmpoliticalreport.com/2018/01/31/southwest-water-bill-would-shift-funding-from-gila-river-diversion-en/|title=Southwest water bill would shift funding from Gila River diversion|last=Paskus|first=Laura|date=2018-01-31|website=The NM Political Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nSenator Morales was inducted into the New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame in December, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/2017/12/12/sen-morales-inducted-into-new-mexico-high-school-baseball-coaches-hall-fame/945644001/|title=Sen. Morales is inducted into New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>, an honor given in recognition of his successful baseball coaching career while achieving prominence in government.\u00a0 Morales was an accomplished high school baseball coach at both Silver High School and Cobre High School in Grant County, including being the youngest head coach in New Mexico to reach 200 wins. Morales retired (2009) after coaching to an impressive 203-49 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/2017/12/12/sen-morales-inducted-into-new-mexico-high-school-baseball-coaches-hall-fame/945644001/|title=Sen. Morales is inducted into New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> \n[[File:Howie_Morales_Stadium,_Bayard,_New_Mexico.jpg|thumb|Howie Morales Stadium, Bayard, New Mexico]]\nSen. Morales' team won a state title in 2008, and he coached his team as state runners-up in 2002, 2007 and 2009. He was also part of seven district championships and seven regional championships as a head coach.  Morales also enjoys the rare honor of having a baseball stadium named in his honor, in Bayard, New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/sports/high-school/baseball/2018/03/08/indian-baseball-tournament-under-way-howie-morales-stadium/408427002/|title=Indian Baseball Tournament is under way at Howie Morales Stadium|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>   \n\n== Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico ==\nIn December 2017, Morales announced his candidacy for the office of the [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/elections/2017/12/06/district-28-senator-howie-morales-run-lieutenant-governor-2018/928709001/|title=District 28 Senator Howie Morales will run for Lieutenant Governor in 2018|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dchieftain.com/news/morales-focused-on-jobs-schools-health-care/article_79877946-6446-11e8-9fd6-5b8085b5761d.html|title=Morales focused on jobs, schools, health care|last=Editor|first=Scott Turner-El Defensor Chieftain|website=El Defensor Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> During his campaign, he called for a \"New Day for New Mexico\" in which innovative and effective policies would be implemented to create more jobs and economic growth, stronger classrooms and student achievement, and strong protections of air, water and land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.demingheadlight.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/16/new-mexico-senator-howie-morales-stumps-deming-luna-county-during-race-lt-governor/611633002/|title=New Mexico Senator Howie Morales stumps in Luna County during race for Lt. Governor|last=fb@demingheadlight|website=The Deming Headlight|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/opinion/editorials/auditor-lieutenant-governor-and-land-commissioner-col-n-morales-and/article_10f138fe-1a6b-51f9-b5b8-edcde349a268.html|title=Auditor, lieutenant governor and land commissioner: Col\u00f3n, Morales and VeneKlasen|last=Mexican|first=The New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  On June 5, 2018, Morales defeated former Majority Leader of the New Mexico House of Representatives [[Rick Miera]] and [[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana County]] Commissioner [https://www.lcsun-news.com/story/news/local/2017/10/20/billy-garrett-run-lieutenant-governor-primary/783996001/ Billy Garrett] in the Democratic primary contest. Morales received 47.1% of the vote, and won all but 3 counties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?eid=112&type=SW&map=CTY|title=New Mexico Election Results|website=electionresults.sos.state.nm.us|language=en|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-mexico-primary-elections.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-mexico-primary-elections.html|title=New Mexico Primary Election Results|last=Almukhtar|first=Sarah|date=2018-06-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-19|last2=Bloch|first2=Matthew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Lee|first3=Jasmine C.}}</ref> In the November 6, 2018 general election, he was [http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?type=SW&map=CTY elected] Lt. Governor along with the Democratic candidate for Governor, Michelle Lujan [https://www.governor.state.nm.us/our-leadership/governor/ Grisham], running together.  \nAs Lieutenant Governor, Howie Morales presides in meetings of the New Mexico Senate.  \nIn January, 2019 Gov. Lujan Grisham asked Lt. Governor Morales to lead the state [https://webnew.ped.state.nm.us/ Public Education Department] (PED) for the first few weeks of the new administration until a permanent Secretary was named<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1269420/multitasking-lieutenant-governor-blazing-a-new-path.html|title='Multitasking' lieutenant governor blazing a new path|last=Chief|first=Dan Boyd {{!}} Journal Capitol Bureau|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scdailypress.com/site/2019/01/19/redefining-the-office-morales-adds-visibility-to-lieutenant-governors-role/|title=Redefining The Office: Morales adds visibility to lieutenant governor\u2019s role {{!}} Silver City Daily Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>. During that period, Gov. Lujan Grisham issued two executive orders eliminating future use of the PARCC standardized test in public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1264248/lujan-grisham-orders-end-to-parcc-testing-in-nm.html|title=Governor orders end to PARCC testing|last=Writers|first=Dan Boyd And Shelby Perea {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scdailypress.com/site/2019/01/04/gov-kills-parcc-test-morales-to-lead-public-ed/|title=Gov. kills PARCC test, Morales to lead Public Ed. {{!}} Silver City Daily Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Dr. Karen Trujillo, a former classroom teacher and specialist in educator professional development was named as Secretary at the end of January, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1272269/governor-appoints-karen-trujillo-as-new-ped-secretary.html|title=Ex-teacher, researcher to lead PED|last=Chief|first=Dan Boyd {{!}} Journal Capitol Bureau|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales said policy changes under the administration of Gov. Lujan Grisham would have positive results for students, educators and schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koat.com/article/changes-to-the-education-system-expected-to-help-keep-teachers-in-new-mexico/25984861|title=More money, less testing hopes to keep teachers in New Mexico|last=Leggett|first=Shellye|date=2019-01-22|website=KOAT|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Morales credited the energetic leadership and new priorities of Gov. Lujan Grisham for creating a needed culture shift at the state PED in support of more collaboration with schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmpoliticalreport.com/2019/02/02/change-at-ped-is-good-news-for-students-and-new-mexico/|title=Change at PED is good news for students and New Mexico|last=Morales|first=Howie|date=2019-02-02|website=The NM Political Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ltgov.state.nm.us/ New Mexico Lt. Governor]  website\n*[http://votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=102383 Project Vote Smart - Senator Howie C. Morales (NM)] profile\n*''Follow the Money'' - Howie Morales\n**[http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=101311 2008] campaign contributions\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Sanchez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current New Mexico statewide political officials}}\n{{Current U.S. Lieutenant Governors}}\n{{Current U.S. State Senate Presidents}}\n{{Lieutenant Governors of New Mexico |state=autocollapse}}\n{{New Mexico State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morales, Howie}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Democrats]]\n[[Category:New Mexico state senators]]\n[[Category:New Mexico State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Silver City, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Western New Mexico University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of New Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Howie Morales\n| image         = Howie Morales.jpg\n| office        = 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]\n| governor      = [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]]\n| term_start    = January 1, 2019\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[John Sanchez]]\n| successor     = \n| state_senate1 = New Mexico\n| district1     = 28th\n| term_start1   = January 9, 2008\n| term_end1     = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor1  = [[Ben D. Altamirano]]\n| successor1    = Gabriel Ramos<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKay |first1=Dan |title=Ramos appointed to NM Senate |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1269375/ramos-appointed-to-nm-senate.html |website=www.abqjournal.com |publisher=Albuquerque Journal |date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1973|1|5}}\n| birth_place   = [[Silver City, New Mexico|Silver City]], [[New Mexico]], U.S.\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        = Teresa Arizaga (Divorced)\n| education     = [[Western New Mexico University|Western New Mexico<br>University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[New Mexico State University|New Mexico State University,<br>Las Cruces]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n}}\n'''Henry C. \"Howie\" Morales''' (born January 5, 1973)<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/GovMLG/status/1081728093952237568</ref> is an American politician and member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] who currently serves as the 30th [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico|lieutenant governor of New Mexico]], since January 1, 2019. He previously served as a member of the [[New Mexico Senate]], representing the 28th District which includes [[Catron County, New Mexico|Catron]], [[Grant County, New Mexico|Grant]], and [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro]] counties from 2008 to 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nMorales attended [[Silver High School (Silver City, NM)|Silver High]] in [[Silver City, New Mexico]] and graduated in 1991. His father, a [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]] veteran, worked in a copper mine and his mother worked multiple hourly-wage jobs. Morales began his first job as a teenager to help his parents make ends meet, and later worked as a shoe salesman and maintenance worker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmexicansformichelle.com/meet-michelle|title=Meet Howie|publisher=newmexicansformichelle.com|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> He earned a Bachelor of Science degree, and in 1998 a Master of Art degree in Bilingual Special Education from [[Western New Mexico University]].  Morales earned a PhD in Education Curriculum and Instruction with a dual emphasis in computer learning technologies and management and leadership from [[New Mexico State University]] in 2007.\n\n==Earlier career==\n\nMorales began his professional career in 1995 as a classroom teacher of special education students in the Silver Consolidated School District.  From 2001 to 2005, he also was the head baseball coach for Cobre High School.\n\nMorales is currently the longest serving volunteer member of the Big Brothers/Big Sisters of [[Grant County, New Mexico|Grant County]]. \n\n== Early political career ==\nMorales was elected [[County Clerk]] in Grant County in 2005.  As County Clerk, he oversaw the transition from over 1,000 outdated voting machines to newer Edge Touch Screen Machines.  He also created a Bureau of Elections Department within the Clerk's office.\n\n== New Mexico Senate ==\nOn December 27, 2007, New Mexico State Senator [[Ben D. Altamirano]] died of a heart attack.  On January 9, 2008, Governor [[Bill Richardson]] appointed Morales to the vacant position that Altamirano held since 1971.  According to Socorro County Commission Chairman Jay Santillanes, \"Morales was personally recommended by the Altamirano family to fill Ben Altamirano's term.  Altamirano's wife, Nina, had considered putting her name in for the position, but decided against it.\"<ref>[http://www.dchieftain.com/news/76997-01-09-08.html \"Morales a nominee to finish Altamirano's term,\" ''El Defensor Chieftain''], retrieved online on December 21, 2008</ref>\n\nMorales ran for the office that he was appointed to in the 2008 general elections and defeated Republican Joseph Gros, 9,561 to 4,019, to retain his seat.<ref>\"Democrats run the table in Grant County,\" ''[[Silver City Daily Press]]'', Online Edition, retrieved on December 21, 2008 [http://www.scdailypress.com/index.php?pSetup=silvercitydailypress&curDate=20081105&pageToLoad=showFreeArticle.php&type=art&index=01  Silver City Daily Press, \"Democrats run the table in Grant County\"].</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Morales officially announced he would run for the office of Governor of New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/elections/elections_2014/race_for_governor/morales-bases-approach-on-second-to-none-mentality/article_e9b269a6-e4b9-5f91-9ffb-e71cb668dce9.html|title=Morales bases approach on \u2018second-to-none\u2019 mentality|last=Mexican|first=Milan SimonichThe New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> \n\nAfter losing the Democratic nomination in a five-way primary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/410306/king-leads-bernalillo-county-gov-vote.html|title=Gary King wins gov primary|last=Writer|first=James Monteleone {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> in June, 2014 to state Attorney General [[Gary King (politician)|Gary King]], Morales continued to serve as a State Senator in his district.<ref>[http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?eid=1&type=SW&map=CTY]</ref> \n\nDuring his 11-year career in the New Mexico Senate, Morales held seats on the Legislative Finance Committee and the Senate Finance Committee, both dealing with state budget matters. He sponsored bills addressing public education, environment and universal health care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retakeourdemocracy.org/health-security-act-nms-single-payer-plan/|title=Health Security Act NM\u2019s Single Payer Plan|date=2017-02-05|website=Retake Our Democracy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales was an outspoken critic of the Martinez administration's education policies that emphasized standardized testing, and he opposed use of [https://parcc.pearson.com/ The Partnership for Assessment of Readiness for College and Careers] (PARCC) assessment in classrooms statewide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dchieftain.com/opinion/editorials/it-s-time-to-end-parcc-testing-of-state-students/article_4bc59446-4323-11e8-bea1-9f2ce3273322.html|title=It\u2019s time to end PARCC testing of state students|last=Morales|first=Guest Columnist Sen Howie|website=El Defensor Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> He spoke out frequently against cuts to public education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lcsun-news.com/story/opinion/2017/05/27/cuts-new-mexico-classrooms/102256886/|title=No more cuts to New Mexico classrooms|website=Las Cruces Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales criticized the introduction of a teacher evaluation system that relied heavily on student performance on the new standardized test (PARCC) in the state's public schools, and he questioned the methodology of the A-to-F school grading system instituted by the Martinez administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/305225/teachers-protest-reforms.html|title=Teachers protest reforms|last=Writer|first=T. S. Last {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  In 2018 Morales sponsored legislation to substantially increase the tax on cigarettes, vaping and tobacco products in order to generate $89 million additional for public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/local_news/lawmakers-to-consider-cigarette-tax-increase/article_fe2bd81a-d883-5607-b3ab-27c5307c7ca6.html|title=Lawmakers to consider cigarette tax increase|last=Mexican|first=Andrew Oxford {{!}} The New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Morales' 2017 [https://www.nmlegis.gov/Legislation/Legislation?Chamber=S&LegType=B&LegNo=106&year=17 Senate Bill 106] sought to create a new cabinet-level Early Childhood Services Department with oversight of already-existing programs like home visiting and pre-kindergarten that are currently scattered through various state agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmindepth.com/2017/02/23/legislator-seeks-to-consolidate-early-childhood-education-programs/|title=Legislator seeks to consolidate early childhood education programs {{!}} New Mexico In Depth|website=nmindepth.com|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  On the environmental side, Morales staunchly opposed controversial federal plans to divert the Gila River in western New Mexico, often described as the last wild river in the West, and he pushed for alternatives to wholesale diversion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmpoliticalreport.com/2018/01/31/southwest-water-bill-would-shift-funding-from-gila-river-diversion-en/|title=Southwest water bill would shift funding from Gila River diversion|last=Paskus|first=Laura|date=2018-01-31|website=The NM Political Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\nSenator Morales was inducted into the New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame in December, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/2017/12/12/sen-morales-inducted-into-new-mexico-high-school-baseball-coaches-hall-fame/945644001/|title=Sen. Morales is inducted into New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>, an honor given in recognition of his successful baseball coaching career while achieving prominence in government.\u00a0 Morales was an accomplished high school baseball coach at both Silver High School and Cobre High School in Grant County, including being the youngest head coach in New Mexico to reach 200 wins. Morales retired (2009) after coaching to an impressive 203-49 record<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/2017/12/12/sen-morales-inducted-into-new-mexico-high-school-baseball-coaches-hall-fame/945644001/|title=Sen. Morales is inducted into New Mexico High School Baseball Coaches Hall of Fame|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>. \n[[File:Howie_Morales_Stadium,_Bayard,_New_Mexico.jpg|thumb|Howie Morales Stadium, Bayard, New Mexico]]\nSen. Morales' team won a state title in 2008, and he coached his team as state runners-up in 2002, 2007 and 2009. He was also part of seven district championships and seven regional championships as a head coach.  Morales also enjoys the rare honor of having a baseball stadium named in his honor, in Bayard, New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/sports/high-school/baseball/2018/03/08/indian-baseball-tournament-under-way-howie-morales-stadium/408427002/|title=Indian Baseball Tournament is under way at Howie Morales Stadium|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>   \n\n== Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico ==\nIn December 2017, Morales announced his candidacy for the office of the [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/politics/elections/2017/12/06/district-28-senator-howie-morales-run-lieutenant-governor-2018/928709001/|title=District 28 Senator Howie Morales will run for Lieutenant Governor in 2018|website=Silver City Sun-News|language=en|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dchieftain.com/news/morales-focused-on-jobs-schools-health-care/article_79877946-6446-11e8-9fd6-5b8085b5761d.html|title=Morales focused on jobs, schools, health care|last=Editor|first=Scott Turner-El Defensor Chieftain|website=El Defensor Chieftain|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> During his campaign, he called for a \"New Day for New Mexico\" in which innovative and effective policies would be implemented to create more jobs and economic growth, stronger classrooms and student achievement, and strong protections of air, water and land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.demingheadlight.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/16/new-mexico-senator-howie-morales-stumps-deming-luna-county-during-race-lt-governor/611633002/|title=New Mexico Senator Howie Morales stumps in Luna County during race for Lt. Governor|last=fb@demingheadlight|website=The Deming Headlight|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.santafenewmexican.com/opinion/editorials/auditor-lieutenant-governor-and-land-commissioner-col-n-morales-and/article_10f138fe-1a6b-51f9-b5b8-edcde349a268.html|title=Auditor, lieutenant governor and land commissioner: Col\u00f3n, Morales and VeneKlasen|last=Mexican|first=The New|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  On June 5, 2018, Morales defeated former Majority Leader of the New Mexico House of Representatives [[Rick Miera]] and [[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana County]] Commissioner [https://www.lcsun-news.com/story/news/local/2017/10/20/billy-garrett-run-lieutenant-governor-primary/783996001/ Billy Garrett] in the Democratic primary contest. Morales received 47.1% of the vote, and won all but 3 counties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?eid=112&type=SW&map=CTY|title=New Mexico Election Results|website=electionresults.sos.state.nm.us|language=en|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-mexico-primary-elections.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/05/us/elections/results-new-mexico-primary-elections.html|title=New Mexico Primary Election Results|last=Almukhtar|first=Sarah|date=2018-06-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-19|last2=Bloch|first2=Matthew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Lee|first3=Jasmine C.}}</ref> In the November 6, 2018 general election, he was [http://electionresults.sos.state.nm.us/resultsSW.aspx?type=SW&map=CTY elected] Lt. Governor along with the Democratic candidate for Governor, Michelle Lujan [https://www.governor.state.nm.us/our-leadership/governor/ Grisham], running together.  \nAs Lieutenant Governor, Howie Morales presides in meetings of the New Mexico Senate.  \nIn January, 2019 Gov. Lujan Grisham asked Lt. Governor Morales to lead the state [https://webnew.ped.state.nm.us/ Public Education Department] (PED) for the first few weeks of the new administration until a permanent Secretary was named<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1269420/multitasking-lieutenant-governor-blazing-a-new-path.html|title='Multitasking' lieutenant governor blazing a new path|last=Chief|first=Dan Boyd {{!}} Journal Capitol Bureau|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scdailypress.com/site/2019/01/19/redefining-the-office-morales-adds-visibility-to-lieutenant-governors-role/|title=Redefining The Office: Morales adds visibility to lieutenant governor\u2019s role {{!}} Silver City Daily Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>. During that period, Gov. Lujan Grisham issued two executive orders eliminating future use of the PARCC standardized test in public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1264248/lujan-grisham-orders-end-to-parcc-testing-in-nm.html|title=Governor orders end to PARCC testing|last=Writers|first=Dan Boyd And Shelby Perea {{!}} Journal Staff|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scdailypress.com/site/2019/01/04/gov-kills-parcc-test-morales-to-lead-public-ed/|title=Gov. kills PARCC test, Morales to lead Public Ed. {{!}} Silver City Daily Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Dr. Karen Trujillo, a former classroom teacher and specialist in educator professional development was named as Secretary at the end of January, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1272269/governor-appoints-karen-trujillo-as-new-ped-secretary.html|title=Ex-teacher, researcher to lead PED|last=Chief|first=Dan Boyd {{!}} Journal Capitol Bureau|website=www.abqjournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>  Morales said policy changes under the administration of Gov. Lujan Grisham would have positive results for students, educators and schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koat.com/article/changes-to-the-education-system-expected-to-help-keep-teachers-in-new-mexico/25984861|title=More money, less testing hopes to keep teachers in New Mexico|last=Leggett|first=Shellye|date=2019-01-22|website=KOAT|language=en|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> Morales credited the energetic leadership and new priorities of Gov. Lujan Grisham for creating a needed culture shift at the state PED in support of more collaboration with schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nmpoliticalreport.com/2019/02/02/change-at-ped-is-good-news-for-students-and-new-mexico/|title=Change at PED is good news for students and New Mexico|last=Morales|first=Howie|date=2019-02-02|website=The NM Political Report|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ltgov.state.nm.us/ New Mexico Lt. Governor]  website\n*[http://votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=102383 Project Vote Smart - Senator Howie C. Morales (NM)] profile\n*''Follow the Money'' - Howie Morales\n**[http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=101311 2008] campaign contributions\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Sanchez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current New Mexico statewide political officials}}\n{{Current U.S. Lieutenant Governors}}\n{{Current U.S. State Senate Presidents}}\n{{Lieutenant Governors of New Mexico |state=autocollapse}}\n{{New Mexico State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morales, Howie}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Democrats]]\n[[Category:New Mexico state senators]]\n[[Category:New Mexico State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Silver City, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Western New Mexico University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of New Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howie_Morales"}
{"title_page": "Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use Commonwealth English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Virus strain causing coronavirus disease 2019}}\n{{About|the virus strain that causes <!--COVID-19 and SARS should not be linked here per [[Wikipedia:Hatnote]] and [[WP:RELATED]]-->COVID-19|the strain that causes SARS<!--COVID-19 and SARS should not be linked here per [[Wikipedia:Hatnote]] and [[WP:RELATED]]-->|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus}}\n{{Virusbox\n| image          = File:Novel Coronavirus SARS-CoV-2.jpg\n| image_alt      = Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV-2 virions with visible coronae\n| image_caption  = Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV-2 [[virion]]s with visible [[Coronavirus#Etymology|coronae]]\n| image2         = 2019-nCoV-CDC-23312 without background.png\n| image2_alt     = Illustration of a SARS-CoV-2 virion\n| image2_caption = Illustration of a SARS-CoV-2 virion\n| parent         = Sarbecovirus<!--Incertae sedis/Betacoronavirus-->\n| species        = Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus\n| strain         = Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2\n| synonyms       = * 2019-nCoV<!-- Please see [[Synonym (taxonomy)]] before adding unofficial names here.-->\n}}\n\n'''Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2''' ('''SARS-CoV-2'''),<ref name=\"CoronavirusStudyGroup\" /><ref name=\"BBC-Named\" /> colloquially known as the '''coronavirus''' and previously known by the [[Novel coronavirus|provisional name]] '''2019 novel coronavirus''' ('''2019-nCoV'''),<ref name=\"WHO21Jan2020\" /><ref name=\"CDC-nCoV\" /><ref name=\"CDCAbout\" /> is a [[positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus]].<ref name=\"gisaid\" /> It causes the [[respiratory illness]] known as [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19). SARS-CoV-2 is [[Contagious disease|contagious]] in humans, and the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has designated [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the ongoing pandemic]] of COVID-19 a <!--It is both a pandemic and a PHEIC. There is no need to change this PHEIC to \"pandemic\", which is in the previous phrase.-->[[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]].<ref name=\"WHOPandemic\"/><ref name=\"NYT 20200130\" /><ref name=\"Chan24Jan2020\" /> The strain was first discovered in [[Wuhan]], China, so it is sometimes referred to as the \"Wuhan virus\"<ref name=\"CNNWuhanV\"/><ref name=\"XinhuaJanuary\" /> or \"Wuhan coronavirus\".<ref name=\"HuangNPR\" /><ref name=\"Fox2020\" /><ref name=\"NBC-GOP\" /> Because the WHO discourages the use of names based upon locations<ref name=\"WHO-SR22\" /><ref name=\"BBC-How\" /> and to avoid confusion with the disease [[SARS]],<ref name=\"QZ-Why\" /> it sometimes refers to SARS-CoV-2 as \"the COVID-19 virus\" in public health communications.<ref name=\"COVIDname\" /> The general public frequently calls both SARS-CoV-2 and the disease it causes \"coronavirus\", but scientists typically use more precise terminology.<ref name=\"NYT6\" />\n\n[[Taxonomy (biology)|Taxonomically]], SARS-CoV-2 is a [[Strain (biology)|strain]] of ''[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus]]'' (SARSr-CoV).<ref name=\"CoronavirusStudyGroup\" /> It is believed to have [[Zoonosis|zoonotic]] origins and has close [[Sequence homology|genetic similarity]] to bat [[coronavirus]]es, suggesting it emerged from a [[bat-borne virus]].<ref name=\"NatureZhou\" /><ref name=\"LancetNowcasting\" /><ref name=\"MedVirEvolution\" /> An intermediate [[Natural reservoir|animal reservoir]] such as a [[pangolin]] is also thought to be involved in its introduction to humans.<ref name=\"WHO-SR22\" /><ref name=\"DWPangolins\" /> The virus shows little genetic diversity, indicating that the [[Spillover infection|spillover event]] introducing SARS-CoV-2 to humans is likely to have occurred in late 2019.<ref name=\"early\" />\n\n[[Epidemiological]] studies estimate each infection results in 1.4 to 3.9 new ones when no members of the community are [[Immunity (medical)|immune]] and no [[Infection control|preventive measures]] taken. The virus is primarily spread between people through close contact and via [[respiratory droplets]] produced from coughs or sneezes.<ref name=\"WHO2020QA\" /><ref name=\"CDCTrans\" /> It mainly [[Viral entry|enters]] human cells by binding to [[angiotensin converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) receptors.<ref name=\"HoffmanCell\" />\n\n==Virology==\n===Infection===\nHuman-to-human [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] of SARS-CoV-2 has been confirmed during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Chan24Jan2020\"/> Transmission occurs primarily via [[Transmission (medicine)#Droplet infection|respiratory droplets]] from coughs and sneezes within a range of about {{convert|1.8|m|ft|0|adj=ri1}}.<ref name=\"CDCTrans\" /><ref name=\"NBCSpread\" /> Indirect contact via [[Fomite|contaminated surfaces]] is another possible cause of infection.<ref name=\"WHO-Workplace\" /> Preliminary research indicates that the virus may remain viable on plastic and steel for up to three days, but does not survive on cardboard for more than one day or on copper for more than four hours;<ref name=\"NEJM-Stability\" /> the virus is inactivated by soap, which destabilises its [[lipid bilayer]].<ref name=\"AtlanticSuccess\" /><ref name=\"NatGeoSoap\" /> Viral RNA has also been found in [[Stool test|stool sample]]s from infected people.<ref name=\"NEJM-FirstUS\" />\n\nThe degree to which the virus is infectious during the [[incubation period]] is uncertain, but research has indicated that the [[Pharynx|pharynx]] reaches peak [[Viral load|viral load]] approximately four days after infection.<ref name=\"NaturePeakLoad\" /><ref name=\"ScienceFlawed\" /> On 1 February 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) indicated that \"transmission from asymptomatic cases is likely not a major driver of transmission\".<ref name=\"WHO-SR12\" /> However, an epidemiological model of the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|outbreak in China]] suggested that \"pre-symptomatic shedding may be typical among documented infections\" and that [[subclinical infection]]s may have been the source of a majority of infections.<ref name=\"ScienceRapid\" />\n\n===Reservoir===\n[[File:Rhinolophus rouxii.jpg|thumb|upright|right|alt=A horseshoe bat|[[Horseshoe bat]]s are among the most likely [[natural reservoir]]s of SARS-CoV-2]]\n\nThe first known infections from the SARS-CoV-2 strain were discovered in [[Wuhan]], China.<ref name=\"NatureZhou\" /> The original source of viral transmission to humans remains unclear, as does whether the strain became [[pathogen]]ic before or after the [[spillover event]].<ref name=\"early\" /><ref name=\"PopSciJan\" /><ref name=\"Proximal\" /> Because many of the first individuals found to be infected by the virus were workers at the [[Huanan Seafood Market]],<ref name=\"LancetClinical\" /><ref name=\"LancetCharacteristics\" /> it has been suggested that the strain might have originated from the market.<ref name=\"Proximal\" /><ref name=\"nature feb2020\" /> However, other research indicates that visitors may have introduced the virus to the market, which then facilitated rapid expansion of the infections.<ref name=\"early\" /><ref name=\"XivDecoding\" />\n\nResearch into the [[natural reservoir]] of the virus strain that caused the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak]] has resulted in the discovery of many [[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1|SARS-like bat coronaviruses]], most originating in the ''Rhinolophus'' genus of [[horseshoe bats]], and two viral [[nucleic acid sequence]]s found in samples taken from ''[[Chinese rufous horseshoe bat|Rhinolophus sinicus]]'' show a resemblance of 80% to SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"MedVirEvolution\" /><ref name=\"NCBI-Bat\" /><ref name=\"NCBI-Bat2\" /> A third viral nucleic acid sequence from ''[[Intermediate horseshoe bat|Rhinolophus affinis]]'', collected in [[Yunnan|Yunnan province]] and designated RaTG13, has a 96% resemblance to SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"NatureZhou\" /><ref name=\"NCBI-Bat3\" /> Bats are considered the most likely natural reservoir of SARS-CoV-2,<ref name=\"WHOChinaJoint\" /><ref name=\"LancetBinding\" /> but differences between the bat coronavirus and SARS-CoV-2 suggest that humans were infected via an intermediate host.<ref name=\"nature feb2020\" />\n\nA [[metagenomic]] study published in 2019 previously revealed that [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]], the strain of the virus that causes [[SARS]], was the most widely distributed coronavirus among a sample of [[Sunda pangolin]]s.<ref name=\"VirusesPangolins\" /> On 7 February 2020, it was announced that researchers from [[Guangzhou]] had discovered a [[pangolin]] sample with a viral nucleic acid sequence \"99% identical\" to SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"NaturePang\" /> When released, the results clarified that \"the receptor-binding domain of the S protein of the newly discovered Pangolin-CoV is virtually identical to that of 2019-nCoV, with one [[amino acid]] difference.\"<ref name=\"Isolation\" /> Pangolins are protected under Chinese law, but their [[pangolin trade|poaching and trading]] for use in [[traditional Chinese medicine]] remains common.<ref name=\"TelegraphPangolins\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Ban\" />\n\nMicrobiologists and geneticists in [[Texas]] have independently found evidence of [[reassortment]] in coronaviruses suggesting involvement of pangolins in the origin of SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"WongRecombination\" /> However, pangolin coronaviruses found to date only share at most 92% of their whole genomes with SARS-CoV-2, making them less similar than RaTG13 to SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"CurrentOrigin\" /> This is insufficient to prove pangolins to be the intermediate host; in comparison, the SARS virus responsible for the 2002\u20132004 outbreak shared 99.8% of its genome with a known [[civet]] coronavirus.<ref name=\"nature feb2020\" />\n\n===Phylogenetics and taxonomy===\n{{Infobox genome\n| image   = File:SARS-CoV-2 genome.svg\n| caption = [[Genomic]] organisation of isolate Wuhan-Hu-1, the earliest sequenced sample of SARS-CoV-2\n| type    = nucleotide\n| taxId   = MN908947\n| size    = 29,903 bases\n| year    = 2020\n}}\n\nSARS-CoV-2 belongs to the broad family of viruses known as [[coronavirus]]es. It is a [[Positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus|positive-sense single-stranded RNA]] (+ssRNA) virus. Other coronaviruses are capable of causing illnesses ranging from the [[common cold]] to more severe diseases such as [[Middle East respiratory syndrome]] (MERS). It is the seventh known coronavirus to infect people, after [[Human coronavirus 229E|229E]], [[Human coronavirus NL63|NL63]], [[Human coronavirus OC43|OC43]], [[Human coronavirus HKU1|HKU1]], [[Middle East respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|MERS-CoV]], and the original SARS-CoV.<ref name=\"NEJM-Novel\" />\n\nLike the SARS-related coronavirus strain implicated in the 2003 SARS outbreak, SARS-CoV-2 is a member of the subgenus ''[[Sarbecovirus]]'' ([[beta-CoV]] lineage B).<ref name=\"NextstrainPhylogeny\" /><ref name=\"Wong2019\" /> Its [[RNA]] sequence is approximately 30,000 [[nucleobase|base]]s in length.<ref name=\"gisaid\"/> SARS-CoV-2 is unique among known betacoronaviruses in its incorporation of a polybasic cleavage site, a characteristic known to increase [[pathogenicity]] and [[Basic reproduction number|transmissibility]] in other viruses.<ref name=\"Proximal\" /><ref name=\"CellWalls\" /><ref name=\"AntiviralCleavage\" />\n\nWith a sufficient number of sequenced [[genome]]s, it is possible to reconstruct a [[phylogenetic tree]] of the mutation history of a family of viruses. By 12 January 2020, five genomes of SARS-CoV-2 had been isolated from Wuhan and reported by the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CCDC) and other institutions;<ref name=\"gisaid\"/><ref name=\"VirologicalInitial\" /> the number of genomes increased to 42 by 30 January 2020.<ref name=\"NextstrainJanuary\" /> A phylogenetic analysis of those samples showed they were \"highly related with at most seven mutations relative to a [[common ancestor]]\", implying that the first human infection occurred in November or December 2019.<ref name=\"NextstrainJanuary\" /> {{As of|2020|March|27|post=,}} 1,495 SARS-CoV-2 genomes sampled on six continents were publicly available.<ref name=\"NextstrainMarch\" />\n\nOn 11 February 2020, the [[International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses]] (ICTV) announced that according to existing rules that compute hierarchical relationships among coronaviruses on the basis of five [[conserved sequence]]s of [[nucleic acid]]s, the differences between what was then called 2019-nCoV and the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|virus strain from the 2003 SARS outbreak]] were insufficient to make them separate [[viral species]]. Therefore, they identified 2019-nCoV as a [[Strain (biology)|strain]] of ''[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus]]''.<ref name=\"CoronavirusStudyGroup\" />\n\n===Structural biology===\n[[File:Coronavirus virion structure.svg|alt=Figure of a spherical SARSr-CoV virion showing locations of structural proteins forming the viral envelope and the inner nucleocapsid|thumb|right|Structure of a SARSr-CoV virion]]\n\nEach SARS-CoV-2 [[virion]] is approximately 50\u2013200 [[nanometre]]s in diameter.<ref name=\"LancetCharacteristics\" /> Like other coronaviruses, SARS-CoV-2 has four structural proteins, known as the S (spike), E (envelope), M (membrane), and N ([[nucleocapsid]]) proteins; the N protein holds the RNA genome, and the S, E, and M proteins together create the [[viral envelope]].<ref name=\"WuStructure\" /> The spike protein, which has been imaged at the atomic level using [[cryogenic electron microscopy]],<ref name=\"SCI-20200219\" /><ref name=\"GZM-20200220\" /> is the protein responsible for allowing the virus to attach to and fuse with the [[cell membrane|membrane]] of a host cell.<ref name=\"WuStructure\" />\n\n[[File:6VSB spike protein SARS-CoV-2 monomer in homotrimer.png|thumb|upright|left|alt=SARS-CoV-2 spike homotrimer focusing upon one protein subunit with an ACE2 binding domain highlighted|SARS-CoV-2 spike [[homotrimer]] with one [[protein subunit]] highlighted; the ACE2 [[binding domain]] is in magenta]]\n\n[[Protein structure prediction|Protein modeling]] experiments on the spike protein of the virus soon suggested that SARS-CoV-2 has sufficient affinity to the [[angiotensin converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) receptors of human cells to use them as a mechanism of [[Viral entry|cell entry]].<ref name=\"SCLSModeling\" /> By 22 January 2020, a group in China working with the full virus genome and a group in the United States using [[reverse genetics]] methods independently and experimentally demonstrated that ACE2 could act as the receptor for SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"NatureZhou\" /><ref name=\"Letko22Jan2020\" /><ref name=\"NatMicLetko\" /><ref name=\"ElSahly\" /> Studies have shown that SARS-CoV-2 has a higher affinity to human ACE2 than the original SARS virus strain.<ref name=\"SCI-20200219\" /><ref name=\"NIH-Structure\" /> SARS-CoV-2 may also use [[basigin]] to assist in cell entry.<ref name=\"CD147\" />\n\n{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | total_width = 400 | image1 = SARS-CoV-2 49531042877.jpg | alt1 = SARS-CoV-2 emerging from a human cell | image2 = SARS-CoV-2 scanning electron microscope image.jpg | alt2 = SARS-CoV-2 virions emerging from a human cell | footer_align = center | footer = Digitally colourised [[Micrograph|electron micrographs]] of SARS-CoV-2 virions (yellow) emerging from human cells [[Cell culture|cultured]] in a laboratory}}\n\nInitial spike protein priming by [[TMPRSS2|transmembrane protease, serine 2]] (TMPRSS2) is essential for entry of SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"HoffmanCell\" /> After a SARS-CoV-2 virion attaches to a target cell, the cell's [[protease]] TMPRSS2 cuts open the spike protein of the virus, exposing a [[fusion peptide]]. The virion then releases RNA into the cell, forcing the cell to produce copies of the virus that are [[Viral shedding|disseminated]] to infect more cells.<ref name=\"econ-anatomy-killer\" />{{better source|date=March 2020}} SARS-CoV-2 produces at least three [[virulence factor]]s that promote shedding of new virions from host cells and inhibit [[immune response]].<ref name=\"WuStructure\" />\n\n==Epidemiology==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Novel Coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 (49597020718).jpg|thumb|[[Transmission electron microscopy|Micrograph]] of SARS-CoV-2 virions (red) isolated from a patient during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]|alt=Micrograph of SARS-CoV-2 virus particles isolated from a patient]]\n\n<!-- This section focuses on what the pandemic shows *about the epidemiology of the virus*, not on what we know about the pandemic. Please do not overload the section with information on the pandemic. -->Based on the low variability exhibited among known SARS-CoV-2 [[genomic]] sequences, the strain is thought to have been detected by health authorities within weeks of its emergence among the human population in late 2019.<ref name=\"early\" /><ref name=\"FromHere\" /> The earliest case of infection currently known is thought to have been found on 17 November 2019.<ref name=\"November case\" /> The virus subsequently spread to all provinces of China and to more than 150 other countries in Asia, Europe, North America, South America, Africa, and Oceania.<ref name=\"JHU_ticker\" /> Human-to-human transmission of the virus has been confirmed in all of these regions.<ref name=\"WHO-SR69\" /> On 30 January 2020, SARS-CoV-2 was designated a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] by the WHO,<ref name=\"NYT 20200130\" /><ref name=\"WHO-PHEIC\" /> and on 11 March 2020 the WHO declared it a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOPandemic\" /><ref name=\"WSJPandemic\" />\n\nThe [[basic reproduction number]] (<math>R_0</math>) of the virus has been estimated to be between 1.4 and 3.9.<ref name=\"NEJM-Dynamics\" /><ref name=\"Eurosurveillance\" /> This means that each infection from the virus is expected to result in 1.4 to 3.9 new infections when no members of the community are [[Immunity (medical)|immune]] and no [[Infection control|preventive measures]] are taken. The reproduction number may be higher in densely populated conditions such as those found on [[cruise ship]]s.<ref name=\"Rocklov\" /> Many forms of [[Coronavirus disease 2019#Prevention|preventive efforts]] may be employed in specific circumstances in order to reduce the propagation of the virus. \n\nThere have been about 82,000 confirmed cases of infection in mainland China.<ref name=\"Worldometer\" /> While the proportion of infections that result in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Cases|confirmed cases]] or progress to diagnosable disease remains unclear,<ref name=\"STAT-Severity\" /> one mathematical model estimated the number of people infected in Wuhan alone at 75,815 (as of 25{{nbsp}}January), at a time when the confirmed cases were only 1,975.<ref name=\"pmid32014114\" /><ref name=\"Worldometer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/china/|title=China Coronavirus: 81,639 Cases and 3,326 Deaths - Worldometer|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Before 24{{nbsp}}February, from the all the global fatalities 95% had occurred [[Hubei|Hubei province]], where Wuhan is located.<ref name=\"GuardianLeap\" /><ref name=\"SunChinaAfrica\" /> As of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, that number decreased to only {{Percent|3207|{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|deaths|editlink=no|ref=no}}|sigfig=2}}.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, there have been {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|confirmed|editlink=no|ref=no}} total confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infection in the ongoing pandemic.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} The total number of deaths attributed to the virus is {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|deaths|editlink=no|ref=no}}.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} There are {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recovered|editlink=no|ref=no}} people who have recovered from confirmed infections, meaning that there are {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|active|editlink=no|ref=no}} active cases.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n<!-- This section focuses on what the pandemic shows *about the epidemiology of the virus*, not on what we know about the pandemic. Please do not overload the section with information on the pandemic. -->\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AntiviralCleavage\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Coutard B, Valle C, de Lamballerie X, Canard B, Seidah NG, Decroly E | title = The spike glycoprotein of the new coronavirus 2019-nCoV contains a furin-like cleavage site absent in CoV of the same clade | journal = [[Antiviral Research]] | volume = 176 | pages = 104742 | date = February 2020 | pmid = 32057769 | doi = 10.1016/j.antiviral.2020.104742|display-authors = 6 |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AtlanticSuccess\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2020/03/biography-new-coronavirus/608338/ |title=Why the Coronavirus Has Been So Successful |vauthors=Yong E |date=20 March 2020|website=The Atlantic |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200320161836/https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2020/03/biography-new-coronavirus/608338/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BBC-How\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51371770|title=How the new coronavirus will finally get a proper name |vauthors=Taylor-Coleman J |work=BBC News |date=5 February 2020|access-date=6 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205190745/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51371770|archive-date=5 February 2020|url-status=live |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BBC-Named\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51466362 |title=Coronavirus disease named Covid-19 |date=11 February 2020 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215204154/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51466362 |archive-date=15 February 2020 |url-status=live |access-date=15 February 2020 |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CDCAbout\">{{cite web |title=About Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |website=United States [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |date=11 February 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211105920/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/index.html |archive-date=11 February 2020 |url-status=unfit |access-date=25 February 2020 |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CDC-nCoV\">{{cite web |title=Healthcare Professionals: Frequently Asked Questions and Answers |website=United States [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |date=11 February 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/faq.html |access-date=15 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214023335/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/faq.html |archive-date=14 February 2020 |url-status=unfit |name-list-format = vanc}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CDCTrans\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/transmission.html |title=How COVID-19 Spreads |date=27 January 2020|website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/202