 vanc}}\n* {{cite report | vauthors = | title = \"Laboratory testing for coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) in suspected human cases: interim guidance, 2&nbsp;March 2020\" | date = 2 March 2020 | author-link = World Health Organization | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | hdl = 10665/331329 | hdl-access = free | id = WHO/COVID-19/laboratory/2020.4. License: CC BY-NC-SA 3.0 |name-list-format = vanc}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{Wikiquote|SARS-CoV-2}}\n{{Scholia}}\n\n* {{cite web | title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) | website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=11 February 2020 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html}}\n* {{cite web | title=Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak | website=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) | url=https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019}}\n* {{cite web | title=SARS-CoV-2 (Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2) Sequences | website=[[National Center for Biotechnology Information]] (NCBI) | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/genbank/sars-cov-2-seqs/ }}\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Resource Centre | website=[[The Lancet]] | url=https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus }}\n* {{cite web | title=Coronavirus (Covid-19) | website=[[The New England Journal of Medicine]] | url=https://www.nejm.org/coronavirus }}\n* {{cite web | title=Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus Content Free to Access | website=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]] | url=https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/ }}\n* {{cite web | title=2019-nCoV Data Portal | website=[[Virus Pathogen Database and Analysis Resource]] | url=https://www.viprbrc.org/brc/home.spg?decorator=corona_ncov }}\n* {{cite web | title=SARS-CoV-2 related protein structures | website=[[Protein Data Bank]] |  url=http://www.rcsb.org/news?year=2020&article=5e3c4bcba5007a04a313edcc}}\n\n{{Medical resources| ICD10 = {{ICD10|U07.1}}}}\n{{Viral systemic diseases|state=collapsed}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Viruses}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q82069695}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:Infraspecific virus taxa]]\n[[Category:Sarbecovirus]]\n[[Category:Zoonoses]]\n", "name_user": "Dekimasu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:name update, date not applicable here", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Severe_acute_respiratory_syndrome_coronavirus_2"}
{"title_page": "Howard W. Smith", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| birth_name = Howard Worth Smith\n| image name = File:Howard Worth Smith.jpg\n| state = [[Virginia]]\n| term_start = January 3, 1955\n| term_end = January 3, 1967\n| preceded = [[Leo E. Allen]]\n| succeeded = [[William M. Colmer]]\n| office1 = Member of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Virginia]]'s [[Virginia's 8th congressional district|8th]] district\n| preceded1 = [[R. Walton Moore]]\n| succeeded1 = [[William L. Scott]]\n| term_start1 = March 4, 1931\n| term_end1 = January 3, 1967<br>[[Virginia's at-large congressional seat|At-large]]: March 4, 1933 \u2013 January 3, 1935\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|2|2|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Broad Run, Virginia]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1976|10|3|1883|2|2|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Alexandria, Virginia]]\n| restingplace = Little Georgetown Cemetery<br/>Broad Run (Fauquier County)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lillian Proctor|November 4, 1913|1919}} d.&nbsp;flu pandemic<br/>{{marriage|Ann Corcoran|1923}}\n| children = Howard Worth Smith, Jr. (d.&nbsp;2003)<br/>Violett (both by Lillian)\n| profession = [[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Virginia]] ([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])\n| footnotes = <ref>{{cite web |title=SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION NO. 186 On the death of Howard Worth Smith, Jr. |url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?041+ful+SJ186+pdf |accessdate=2011-11-28 |date=February 13, 2004 |publisher=Virginia General Assembly |authorlink1=Patsy Ticer |first1=Patsy |last1=Ticer |authorlink2=Richard L. Saslaw |first2=Richard L. |last2=Saslaw |authorlink3=Adam Ebbin |first3=Adam |last3=Ebbin |authorlink4=Brian Moran |first4=Brian |last4=Moran |authorlink5=Marian Van Landingham |first5=Marian |last5=Van Landingham}}</ref><ref name=EncylopediaVirginia>{{cite web |work=Encyclopedia Virginia |title=Smith, Howard Worth (1883&ndash;1976) |accessdate=2011-11-28 |url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Smith_Howard_Worth_1883-1976 |publisher=[[Virginia Foundation for the Humanities]] |first=Bruce |last=Dierenfield |editor=Brendan Wolfe |date=7 April 2011}}</ref>\n| office = Chair of the [[U.S. House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]]\n| 1blankname = [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]\n| 1namedata = [[Sam Rayburn]]<br>[[John W. McCormack]]\n}}\n\n'''Howard Worth Smith''' (February 2, 1883 &ndash; October 3, 1976) was an American politician. A [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Virginia]], he was a leader of the powerful but informal anti-Civil Rights coalition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Smith_Howard_Worth_1883-1976|title=Smith, Howard Worth (1883\u20131976)|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in [[Broad Run, Virginia]], on February 2, 1883, he attended public schools and graduated from [[Bethel Military Academy]], [[Warrenton, Virginia]], in 1901. He took his [[LLB]] at the law department of the [[University of Virginia]] at [[Charlottesville]] in 1903, was admitted to the bar in 1904 and practiced in [[Alexandria, Virginia]].\n\nDuring [[World War I]], he was assistant general counsel to the Federal [[Alien Property Custodian]]. From 1918 to 1922 he was [[Commonwealth's Attorney]] of Alexandria. He served as a judge 1922 to 1930 (he was often referred to as \"Judge Smith\" even while in Congress), and also engaged in [[banking]], [[farming]], and [[dairying]].\n\n==Representative==\nHe was elected in 1930 to the House of Representatives. He initially supported [[New Deal]] measures such as the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] Act and the [[National Industrial Recovery Act]]. A leader of the [[conservative coalition]], he led the opposition to the [[National Labor Relations Board]] (NLRB), established by the [[Wagner Act]] of 1935. Conservatives created a special House committee to investigate the NLRB that was headed by Smith and dominated by opponents of the New Deal. The committee conducted a sensationalist investigation that undermined public support for the NLRB and, more broadly, for the New Deal. In June 1940, amendments proposed by the Smith Committee passed by a large margin in the House, partly because Smith's new alliance with [[William Green (labor leader)|William Green]], president of the [[American Federation of Labor]]. The AFL was convinced the NLRB was controlled by leftists who supported the rival [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] in organizing drives. New Dealers stopped the Smith amendments, but Roosevelt replaced the CIO-oriented members on the NLRB with men acceptable to Smith and the AFL.<ref>Storrs, p. 212.</ref>\n\nSmith proposed the [[anticommunist]] Alien Registration Act of 1940 {{UnitedStatesCode|18|2385}}, which became known as the [[Smith Act]]. It required [[resident alien]]s to register. It also banned advocating the overthrow of the [[US government]] or its political subdivisions. [[American Communist Party]] chairman [[Gus Hall]] was one of many communists later convicted of violating its provisions. The [[US Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Yates v. United States]]'' (1957) that the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protected much radical speech, which halted Smith Act prosecutions under the Act.\n\n===Opposition to civil rights===\nAs chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Rules]] starting in 1954,<ref name=\"DesMoinesRegister\">{{cite news|title=People in the News...83, Runs Again|publisher=[[The Des Moines Register]]|date=March 3, 1966}}</ref> Smith controlled the flow of legislation in the House. An opponent of racial integration, Smith used his power as chairman of the Rules Committee to keep much civil rights legislation from coming to a vote on the House floor.\n\nHe was a signatory to the 1956 [[Southern Manifesto]] that opposed the desegregation of public schools ordered by the Supreme Court in ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''. A friend described him as someone who \"had a real feeling of kindness toward the black people he knew, but he did not respect the race.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964|title=Civil Rights Act of 1964|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>\"\n\nWhen the [[Civil Rights Act of 1957]] came before Smith's committee, Smith said, \"The Southern people have never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence and education and social attainments as the whole people of the South.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=YpFWUrynUl4C&pg=PT154&lpg=PT154&dq=%22The+Southern+people+have+never+accepted+the+colored+race+as+a+race+of+people+who+had+equal+intelligence%22&source=bl&ots=jZ3s0JLtiX&sig=ACfU3U0LBDwBbjiwzbWWaxSUOTk8vo0njQ&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxoNj52sTjAhWVD2MBHbB1BAYQ6AEwBHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Southern%20people%20have%20never%20accepted%20the%20colored%20race%20as%20a%20race%20of%20people%20who%20had%20equal%20intelligence%22&f=false|title=Nobody Turn Me Around: A People's History of the 1963 March on Washington|last=Euchner|first=Charles|date=2010-09-25|publisher=Beacon Press|isbn=9780807095522|language=en}}</ref>\" Others noted him as an apologist for slavery who used the [[Slavery in ancient Greece|Ancient Greeks]] and [[Slavery in ancient Rome|Romans]] in its defense<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nSpeaker [[Sam Rayburn]] tried to reduce his power in 1961, with only limited success.\n\nSmith delayed passage the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. One of Rayburn's reforms was the \"Twenty-One Day Rule\" that required a bill to be sent to the floor within 21 days. Under pressure, Smith released the bill.\n\nTwo days before the vote, Smith offered an amendment to insert \"sex\" after the word \"religion\" as a [[protected class]] of [[Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. The ''Congressional Record'' shows Smith made serious arguments, voicing concerns that white women would suffer greater discrimination without a protection for gender.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Liberals, who knew Smith was hostile to civil rights for blacks, assumed that he was doing so to defeat the whole bill.<ref>Clinton Jacob Woods, \"Strange Bedfellows: Congressman Howard W. Smith and the Inclusion of Sex Discrimination in the 1964 Civil Rights Act,\" ''Southern Studies,'' 16 (Spring\u2013Summer 2009), 1\u201332.</ref><ref name=Freeman/> In 1968, Leo Kanowitz wrote that, within the context of the anti-civil rights coalition making \"every effort to block\" the passage of Title VII, \"it is abundantly clear that a principal motive in introducing [\"sex\"] was to prevent passage of the basic legislation being considered by Congress, rather than solicitude for women's employment rights.\"<ref>Leo Kanowitz, ''Sex-Based Discrimination in American Law III: Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act and the Equal Pay Act of 1963'', 20 Hastings L. Rev. 305 (1968).</ref>  Kanowitz notes that Representative [[Edith Green]], who was one of the few female legislators in the House at that time, held that view that legislation against sex discrimination in employment \"would not have received one hundred votes,\" indicating that it would have been defeated handedly. \n[[File:CivilRightsAct1964-HouseRollCall-Sex-Amendment.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[House Rules Committee]] clerk's record of [[markup (legislation)|markup session]] adding \"sex\" to bill.]]  \n\nIn 1964, the burning national issue was civil rights for blacks. Liberals argued that it was \"the Negro's hour\" and that adding women's rights to the bill could hurt its chance of being passed. However, conservatives on race voted for the Smith amendment. The [[National Woman's Party]] (NWP) had used Smith to include sex as a protected category and so achieved their main goal.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/onaccountofsexpo00harr|url-access=registration|title=On Account of Sex: The Politics of Women's Issues, 1945-1968|last=Harrison|first=Cynthia|publisher=University of California Press|year=1989|isbn=|location=Los Angeles|pages=[https://archive.org/details/onaccountofsexpo00harr/page/178 178]&ndash;79|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe prohibition of sex discrimination was added on the floor by Smith. While Smith was a conservative who strongly opposed civil rights laws for blacks, he supported such laws for women. Smith's amendment passed by a vote of 168 to 133.<ref name=Freeman>{{cite journal |authorlink=Jo Freeman |last=Freeman |first=Jo |title=How 'Sex' Got Into Title VII: Persistent Opportunism as a Maker of Public Policy |work=Law and Inequality: A Journal of Theory and Practice |volume=9 |issue=2 |date=March 1991 |pages=163\u2013184 |url=http://www.jofreeman.com/lawandpolicy/titlevii.htm}} online version.</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Rosalind Rosenberg |first=Rosalind |last=Rosenberg |title=Divided Lives: American Women in the Twentieth Century |year=2008 |pages=187\u2013188}}</ref><ref name=\"'70s 245\">{{cite book|title= How We Got Here: The '70s|last= Frum|first= David|authorlink= David Frum|coauthors= |year= 2000|publisher= [[Basic Books]]|location= New York, New York|isbn= 0-465-04195-7|page= |pages= [https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/245 245\u2013246, 249]|url= https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/245|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n\nSmith expected that [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], who had included equal rights for women in their party's platform since 1940, would probably vote for the amendment. Some historians speculate that Smith in addition to helping women was trying to embarrass [[Northern Democrats]], who opposed civil rights for women since [[labor unions]] opposed the clause.<ref name=\"Gold\">{{cite news |last=Gold |first=Michael Evan |title=A Tale of Two Amendments: The Reasons Congress Added Sex to Title VII and Their Implication for the Issue of Comparable Worth |work=Faculty Publications \u2014 Collective Bargaining, Labor Law, and Labor History |publisher=[[Cornell University ILR School|Cornell]] |date=1 January 1981 |accessdate=2011-11-28 |url=http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1010&context=cbpubs}} from [[Duquesne Law Review]].</ref>\n\nSmith insisted that he sincerely supported the amendment and along with Representative [[Martha Griffiths]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Lynne |last=Olson |title=Freedom's Daughters: The Unsung Heroines of the Civil Rights Movement |year=2001 |page=360}}</ref> was the chief spokeswoman for the amendment.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> For 20 years, Smith had sponsored the Equal Rights Amendment, with no linkage to racial issues, in the House. He for decades had been close to the NWP and its leader, [[Alice Paul]], one of the leaders in winning the vote for women in 1920 and the chief supporter of equal rights proposals since then. She and other feminists had worked with Smith since 1945 to try to find a way to include sex as a protected civil rights category.<ref>Rosenberg (2008). p.187; notes that Smith had been working for years with two Virginia feminists on the issue.</ref>\n\nGriffiths argued that the new law would protect black women but not white women and so was unfair to white women. Furthermore, she argued that the laws \"protecting\" women from unpleasant jobs were actually designed to enable men to monopolize those jobs, which was unfair to women who were not allowed to try the jobs.<ref>Harrison 1989. p.179</ref> The amendment passed with the votes of Republicans and Southern Democrats. Republicans and Northern Democrats voted for the bill's final passage.\n\nSmith had a part in temporarily blocking the [[Economic Opportunity Act of 1964]] because \"[[Job Corps]] provision would allow coeducational and [[miscegenation|interracial]] job camps.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=yrLcOAKloIIC&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=%22Job+Corps+provision+would+allow+coeducational+and+interracial+job+camps.%22&source=bl&ots=SsdzzaUuAu&sig=ACfU3U0Z3ENQzm5YvDrlghVM9MiFxh8dcg&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjazdLu3MTjAhWE2uAKHX6sBCsQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Job%20Corps%20provision%20would%20allow%20coeducational%20and%20interracial%20job%20camps.%22&f=false|title=The Birth of Head Start: Preschool Education Policies in the Kennedy and Johnson Administrations|last=Vinovskis|first=Maris A.|date=2008-11-15|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=|isbn=9780226856735|location=|pages=48|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Defeat===\nAfter [[U.S. Senator]] [[Carter Glass]] died in 1946, Smith sought the nomination to succeed him. The [[Byrd Organization]], of which Smith was a member, instead nominated [[A. Willis Robertson]], who was elected to the Senate.<ref name=EncylopediaVirginia/>\n\nSmith [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1966#Virginia|was defeated in the 1966 primary]] by a considerably more liberal Democrat, [[Virginia House of Delegates|State Delegate]] [[George Rawlings]], Jr. Although Smith remained neutral in the general election, many of his supporters defected to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[William L. Scott]], who soundly defeated Rawlings in November.\n\n==Later life==\nSmith resumed the practice of law in Alexandria, where he died at 93 on October 3, 1976. He was interred in Georgetown Cemetery, Broad Run, Virginia.\n\n==Portrait controversy==\nIn January 1995, the House Rules Committee chairman, Republican Congressman [[Gerald B. H. Solomon]], had a portrait of Smith hung in the Committee hearing room. The [[Congressional Black Caucus]] requested that it be removed. [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] said:<ref>{{cite web\n|date=February 13, 1995 |author=|url= http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_n14_v87/ai_16624572 |title= CBC members get portrait removed from House Rules Committee meeting room - Congressional Black Caucus |work = [[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=jDkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16&dq=%22race+of+people+who+had+equal+intelligence%22+education&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjekv-03MTjAhVR8OAKHVC6CN0Q6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=%22race%20of%20people%20who%20had%20equal%20intelligence%22%20education&f=false|title=Jet|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|date=1995-02-13|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is an affront to all of us&nbsp;...[Smith is] perhaps best remembered for his obstruction in passing this country's civil rights laws. A man who in his own words never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence and education and social attainments as the White people of the South...}}\n\nSolomon said he displayed the portrait to acknowledge Smith's co-operative work with Republicans when he was chairman but that he was unaware of his segregationist views. The portrait was later removed.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web |date=January 25, 1995 |authorlink=David E. Rosenbaum |first=David E. |last=Rosenbaum |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60610F93F580C768EDDA80894DD494D81 |title= Offending Portrait Succumbs To Black Lawmakers' Protest |work = [[New York Times]] |accessdate=2011-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nSmith was portrayed by American actor [[Ken Jenkins]] in the 2016 [[HBO]] TV movie ''[[All the Way (film)|All the Way]]'', in which his segregationist views posed as a central and divisive opposition to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s proposal of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brauer, Carl M. \"Women Activists, Southern Conservatives, and the Prohibition of Sex Discrimination in Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act\", 49 ''Journal of Southern History'', February 1983 online via JSTOR\n* Dierenfield, Bruce J. ''Keeper of the Rules: Congressman Howard W. Smith of Virginia'' (1987)\n* Dierenfield, Bruce J. \"Conservative Outrage: the Defeat in 1966 of  Representative Howard W. Smith of Virginia.\" ''Virginia Magazine of History and Biography'' 1981 89 (2): 181-205.\n* Freeman, Jo. \"How 'Sex' Got Into Title VII: Persistent Opportunism as a Maker of Public Policy,\" ''Law and Inequality: A Journal of Theory and Practice'', Vol. 9, No. 2, March 1991, pp.&nbsp;163\u2013184. [http://www.jofreeman.com/lawandpolicy/titlevii.htm online version]\n* Gold, Michael Evan. ''A Tale of Two Amendments: The Reasons Congress Added Sex to Title VII and Their Implication for the Issue of Comparable Worth.'' Faculty Publications - Collective Bargaining, Labor Law, and Labor History. Cornell, 1981 [http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1010&context=cbpubs]\n* Jones, Charles O. \"Joseph G. Cannon and Howard W. Smith: an Essay on the Limits of Leadership in the House of Representatives\" ''[[Journal of Politics]]'' 1968 30(3): 617-646. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2128798 in JSTOR]\n* Robinson, Donald Allen. \"Two Movements in Pursuit of Equal Employment Opportunity.\" ''Signs'' 1979 4(3): 413-433. on alliance between Smith and Griffiths.\n* Storrs, Landon R. Y. ''Civilizing Capitalism: The National Consumers' League, Women's Activism, and Labor Standards in the New Deal Era'' [[University of North Carolina Press]]. 2000.\n* Woods, Clinton Jacob, \"Strange Bedfellows: Congressman Howard W. Smith and the Inclusion of Sex Discrimination in the 1964 Civil Rights Act,\" ''Southern Studies,'' 16 (Spring\u2013Summer 2009), 1\u201332.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Howard W. Smith}}\n* {{congbio|S000554}}\n* {{findagrave|7709428}}\n* {{pgbio|id=smith4.html}}\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/person.xpd?id=410036 Howard Smith,  former U.S. Representative - GovTrack.us]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= Virginia\n| district= 8\n| before= [[R. Walton Moore]]\n|after = ''District abolished''<br>Himself after district re-established in 1935\n|years = 1931&ndash;1933}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state = Virginia\n|district = AL\n|before = ''District re-established''<br>[[John Sergeant Wise|John S. Wise]] before district eliminated in 1885\n|after = ''District abolished''\n|years = 1933 &ndash; 1935}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state = Virginia\n|district = 8\n|before = ''District re-established''<br>Himself before district abolished in 1933\n| after= [[William L. Scott]]\n| years= 1935&ndash;1967}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[U.S. House Committee on Rules|Chairman of the United States House Committee on Rules]] | before=[[Leo E. Allen]] | after=[[William M. Colmer]] | years=1955&ndash;1966}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{US House Rules chairs}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives08}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Howard Worth}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:County and city Commonwealth's Attorneys in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia state court judges]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Alexandria, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Old Right (United States)]]\n[[Category:History of racism in the United States]]\n[[Category:American white supremacists]]\n[[Category:Farmers from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American proslavery activists]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| birth_name = Howard Worth Smith\n| image name = File:Howard Worth Smith.jpg\n| state = [[Virginia]]\n| term_start = January 3, 1955\n| term_end = January 3, 1967\n| preceded = [[Leo E. Allen]]\n| succeeded = [[William M. Colmer]]\n| office1 = Member of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Virginia]]'s [[Virginia's 8th congressional district|8th]] district\n| preceded1 = [[R. Walton Moore]]\n| succeeded1 = [[William L. Scott]]\n| term_start1 = March 4, 1931\n| term_end1 = January 3, 1967<br>[[Virginia's at-large congressional seat|At-large]]: March 4, 1933 \u2013 January 3, 1935\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|2|2|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Broad Run, Virginia]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1976|10|3|1883|2|2|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Alexandria, Virginia]]\n| restingplace = Little Georgetown Cemetery<br/>Broad Run (Fauquier County)\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lillian Proctor|November 4, 1913|1919}} d.&nbsp;flu pandemic<br/>{{marriage|Ann Corcoran|1923}}\n| children = Howard Worth Smith, Jr. (d.&nbsp;2003)<br/>Violett (both by Lillian)\n| profession = [[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Virginia]] ([[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]])\n| footnotes = <ref>{{cite web |title=SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION NO. 186 On the death of Howard Worth Smith, Jr. |url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?041+ful+SJ186+pdf |accessdate=2011-11-28 |date=February 13, 2004 |publisher=Virginia General Assembly |authorlink1=Patsy Ticer |first1=Patsy |last1=Ticer |authorlink2=Richard L. Saslaw |first2=Richard L. |last2=Saslaw |authorlink3=Adam Ebbin |first3=Adam |last3=Ebbin |authorlink4=Brian Moran |first4=Brian |last4=Moran |authorlink5=Marian Van Landingham |first5=Marian |last5=Van Landingham}}</ref><ref name=EncylopediaVirginia>{{cite web |work=Encyclopedia Virginia |title=Smith, Howard Worth (1883&ndash;1976) |accessdate=2011-11-28 |url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Smith_Howard_Worth_1883-1976 |publisher=[[Virginia Foundation for the Humanities]] |first=Bruce |last=Dierenfield |editor=Brendan Wolfe |date=7 April 2011}}</ref>\n| office = Chair of the [[U.S. House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]]\n| 1blankname = [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]\n| 1namedata = [[Sam Rayburn]]<br>[[John W. McCormack]]\n}}\n\n'''Howard Worth Smith''' (February 2, 1883 &ndash; October 3, 1976) was an American politician. A [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Virginia]], he was a leader of the powerful but informal anti-Civil Rights coalition<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Smith_Howard_Worth_1883-1976|title=Smith, Howard Worth (1883\u20131976)|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in [[Broad Run, Virginia]], on February 2, 1883, he attended public schools and graduated from [[Bethel Military Academy]], [[Warrenton, Virginia]], in 1901. He took his [[LLB]] at the law department of the [[University of Virginia]] at [[Charlottesville]] in 1903, was admitted to the bar in 1904 and practiced in [[Alexandria, Virginia]].\n\nDuring [[World War I]], he was assistant general counsel to the Federal [[Alien Property Custodian]]. From 1918 to 1922 he was [[Commonwealth's Attorney]] of Alexandria. He served as a judge 1922 to 1930 (he was often referred to as \"Judge Smith\" even while in Congress), and also engaged in [[banking]], [[farming]], and [[dairying]].\n\n==Representative==\nHe was elected in 1930 to the House of Representatives. He initially supported [[New Deal]] measures such as the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] Act and the [[National Industrial Recovery Act]]. A leader of the [[conservative coalition]], he led the opposition to the [[National Labor Relations Board]] (NLRB), established by the [[Wagner Act]] of 1935. Conservatives created a special House committee to investigate the NLRB that was headed by Smith and dominated by opponents of the New Deal. The committee conducted a sensationalist investigation that undermined public support for the NLRB and, more broadly, for the New Deal. In June 1940, amendments proposed by the Smith Committee passed by a large margin in the House, partly because Smith's new alliance with [[William Green (labor leader)|William Green]], president of the [[American Federation of Labor]]. The AFL was convinced the NLRB was controlled by leftists who supported the rival [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] in organizing drives. New Dealers stopped the Smith amendments, but Roosevelt replaced the CIO-oriented members on the NLRB with men acceptable to Smith and the AFL.<ref>Storrs, p. 212.</ref>\n\nSmith proposed the [[anticommunist]] Alien Registration Act of 1940 {{UnitedStatesCode|18|2385}}, which became known as the [[Smith Act]]. It required [[resident alien]]s to register. It also banned advocating the overthrow of the [[US government]] or its political subdivisions. [[American Communist Party]] chairman [[Gus Hall]] was one of many communists later convicted of violating its provisions. The [[US Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Yates v. United States]]'' (1957) that the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protected much radical speech, which halted Smith Act prosecutions under the Act.\n\n===Opposition to civil rights===\nAs chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Rules]] starting in 1954,<ref name=\"DesMoinesRegister\">{{cite news|title=People in the News...83, Runs Again|publisher=[[The Des Moines Register]]|date=March 3, 1966}}</ref> Smith controlled the flow of legislation in the House. An opponent of racial integration, Smith used his power as chairman of the Rules Committee to keep much civil rights legislation from coming to a vote on the House floor.\n\nHe was a signatory to the 1956 [[Southern Manifesto]] that opposed the desegregation of public schools ordered by the Supreme Court in ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''. A friend described him as someone who \"had a real feeling of kindness toward the black people he knew, but he did not respect the race<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964|title=Civil Rights Act of 1964|website=www.encyclopediavirginia.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref>.\"\n\nWhen the [[Civil Rights Act of 1957]] came before Smith's committee, Smith said, \"The Southern people have never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence and education and social attainments as the whole people of the South<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=YpFWUrynUl4C&pg=PT154&lpg=PT154&dq=%22The+Southern+people+have+never+accepted+the+colored+race+as+a+race+of+people+who+had+equal+intelligence%22&source=bl&ots=jZ3s0JLtiX&sig=ACfU3U0LBDwBbjiwzbWWaxSUOTk8vo0njQ&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxoNj52sTjAhWVD2MBHbB1BAYQ6AEwBHoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Southern%20people%20have%20never%20accepted%20the%20colored%20race%20as%20a%20race%20of%20people%20who%20had%20equal%20intelligence%22&f=false|title=Nobody Turn Me Around: A People's History of the 1963 March on Washington|last=Euchner|first=Charles|date=2010-09-25|publisher=Beacon Press|isbn=9780807095522|language=en}}</ref>.\" Others noted him as an apologist for slavery who used the [[Slavery in ancient Greece|Ancient Greeks]] and [[Slavery in ancient Rome|Romans]] in its defense<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nSpeaker [[Sam Rayburn]] tried to reduce his power in 1961, with only limited success.\n\nSmith delayed passage the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. One of Rayburn's reforms was the \"Twenty-One Day Rule\" that required a bill to be sent to the floor within 21 days. Under pressure, Smith released the bill.\n\nTwo days before the vote, Smith offered an amendment to insert \"sex\" after the word \"religion\" as a [[protected class]] of [[Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. The ''Congressional Record'' shows Smith made serious arguments, voicing concerns that white women would suffer greater discrimination without a protection for gender.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> Liberals, who knew Smith was hostile to civil rights for blacks, assumed that he was doing so to defeat the whole bill.<ref>Clinton Jacob Woods, \"Strange Bedfellows: Congressman Howard W. Smith and the Inclusion of Sex Discrimination in the 1964 Civil Rights Act,\" ''Southern Studies,'' 16 (Spring\u2013Summer 2009), 1\u201332.</ref><ref name=Freeman/> In 1968, Leo Kanowitz wrote that, within the context of the anti-civil rights coalition making \"every effort to block\" the passage of Title VII, \"it is abundantly clear that a principal motive in introducing [\"sex\"] was to prevent passage of the basic legislation being considered by Congress, rather than solicitude for women's employment rights.\"<ref>Leo Kanowitz, ''Sex-Based Discrimination in American Law III: Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act and the Equal Pay Act of 1963'', 20 Hastings L. Rev. 305 (1968).</ref>  Kanowitz notes that Representative [[Edith Green]], who was one of the few female legislators in the House at that time, held that view that legislation against sex discrimination in employment \"would not have received one hundred votes,\" indicating that it would have been defeated handedly. \n[[File:CivilRightsAct1964-HouseRollCall-Sex-Amendment.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[House Rules Committee]] clerk's record of [[markup (legislation)|markup session]] adding \"sex\" to bill.]]  \n\nIn 1964, the burning national issue was civil rights for blacks. Liberals argued that it was \"the Negro's hour\" and that adding women's rights to the bill could hurt its chance of being passed. However, conservatives on race voted for the Smith amendment. The [[National Woman's Party]] (NWP) had used Smith to include sex as a protected category and so achieved their main goal.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/onaccountofsexpo00harr|url-access=registration|title=On Account of Sex: The Politics of Women's Issues, 1945-1968|last=Harrison|first=Cynthia|publisher=University of California Press|year=1989|isbn=|location=Los Angeles|pages=[https://archive.org/details/onaccountofsexpo00harr/page/178 178]&ndash;79|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe prohibition of sex discrimination was added on the floor by Smith. While Smith was a conservative who strongly opposed civil rights laws for blacks, he supported such laws for women. Smith's amendment passed by a vote of 168 to 133.<ref name=Freeman>{{cite journal |authorlink=Jo Freeman |last=Freeman |first=Jo |title=How 'Sex' Got Into Title VII: Persistent Opportunism as a Maker of Public Policy |work=Law and Inequality: A Journal of Theory and Practice |volume=9 |issue=2 |date=March 1991 |pages=163\u2013184 |url=http://www.jofreeman.com/lawandpolicy/titlevii.htm}} online version.</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Rosalind Rosenberg |first=Rosalind |last=Rosenberg |title=Divided Lives: American Women in the Twentieth Century |year=2008 |pages=187\u2013188}}</ref><ref name=\"'70s 245\">{{cite book|title= How We Got Here: The '70s|last= Frum|first= David|authorlink= David Frum|coauthors= |year= 2000|publisher= [[Basic Books]]|location= New York, New York|isbn= 0-465-04195-7|page= |pages= [https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/245 245\u2013246, 249]|url= https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/245|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n\nSmith expected that [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], who had included equal rights for women in their party's platform since 1940, would probably vote for the amendment. Some historians speculate that Smith in addition to helping women was trying to embarrass [[Northern Democrats]], who opposed civil rights for women since [[labor unions]] opposed the clause.<ref name=\"Gold\">{{cite news |last=Gold |first=Michael Evan |title=A Tale of Two Amendments: The Reasons Congress Added Sex to Title VII and Their Implication for the Issue of Comparable Worth |work=Faculty Publications \u2014 Collective Bargaining, Labor Law, and Labor History |publisher=[[Cornell University ILR School|Cornell]] |date=1 January 1981 |accessdate=2011-11-28 |url=http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1010&context=cbpubs}} from [[Duquesne Law Review]].</ref>\n\nSmith insisted that he sincerely supported the amendment and along with Representative [[Martha Griffiths]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Lynne |last=Olson |title=Freedom's Daughters: The Unsung Heroines of the Civil Rights Movement |year=2001 |page=360}}</ref> was the chief spokeswoman for the amendment.<ref name=\"Gold\"/> For 20 years, Smith had sponsored the Equal Rights Amendment, with no linkage to racial issues, in the House. He for decades had been close to the NWP and its leader, [[Alice Paul]], one of the leaders in winning the vote for women in 1920 and the chief supporter of equal rights proposals since then. She and other feminists had worked with Smith since 1945 to try to find a way to include sex as a protected civil rights category.<ref>Rosenberg (2008). p.187; notes that Smith had been working for years with two Virginia feminists on the issue.</ref>\n\nGriffiths argued that the new law would protect black women but not white women and so was unfair to white women. Furthermore, she argued that the laws \"protecting\" women from unpleasant jobs were actually designed to enable men to monopolize those jobs, which was unfair to women who were not allowed to try the jobs.<ref>Harrison 1989. p.179</ref> The amendment passed with the votes of Republicans and Southern Democrats. Republicans and Northern Democrats voted for the bill's final passage.\n\nSmith had a part in temporarily blocking the [[Economic Opportunity Act of 1964]] because \"[[Job Corps]] provision would allow coeducational and [[miscegenation|interracial]] job camps.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=yrLcOAKloIIC&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=%22Job+Corps+provision+would+allow+coeducational+and+interracial+job+camps.%22&source=bl&ots=SsdzzaUuAu&sig=ACfU3U0Z3ENQzm5YvDrlghVM9MiFxh8dcg&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjazdLu3MTjAhWE2uAKHX6sBCsQ6AEwAHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Job%20Corps%20provision%20would%20allow%20coeducational%20and%20interracial%20job%20camps.%22&f=false|title=The Birth of Head Start: Preschool Education Policies in the Kennedy and Johnson Administrations|last=Vinovskis|first=Maris A.|date=2008-11-15|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=|isbn=9780226856735|location=|pages=48|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Defeat===\nAfter [[U.S. Senator]] [[Carter Glass]] died in 1946, Smith sought the nomination to succeed him. The [[Byrd Organization]], of which Smith was a member, instead nominated [[A. Willis Robertson]], who was elected to the Senate.<ref name=EncylopediaVirginia/>\n\nSmith [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1966#Virginia|was defeated in the 1966 primary]] by a considerably more liberal Democrat, [[Virginia House of Delegates|State Delegate]] [[George Rawlings]], Jr. Although Smith remained neutral in the general election, many of his supporters defected to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[William L. Scott]], who soundly defeated Rawlings in November.\n\n==Later life==\nSmith resumed the practice of law in Alexandria, where he died at 93 on October 3, 1976. He was interred in Georgetown Cemetery, Broad Run, Virginia.\n\n==Portrait controversy==\nIn January 1995, the House Rules Committee chairman, Republican Congressman [[Gerald B. H. Solomon]], had a portrait of Smith hung in the Committee hearing room. The [[Congressional Black Caucus]] requested that it be removed. [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] said:<ref>{{cite web\n|date=February 13, 1995 |author=|url= http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_n14_v87/ai_16624572 |title= CBC members get portrait removed from House Rules Committee meeting room - Congressional Black Caucus |work = [[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=jDkDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16&dq=%22race+of+people+who+had+equal+intelligence%22+education&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjekv-03MTjAhVR8OAKHVC6CN0Q6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=%22race%20of%20people%20who%20had%20equal%20intelligence%22%20education&f=false|title=Jet|last=Company|first=Johnson Publishing|date=1995-02-13|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is an affront to all of us&nbsp;...[Smith is] perhaps best remembered for his obstruction in passing this country's civil rights laws. A man who in his own words never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence and education and social attainments as the White people of the South...}}\n\nSolomon said he displayed the portrait to acknowledge Smith's co-operative work with Republicans when he was chairman but that he was unaware of his segregationist views. The portrait was later removed.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web |date=January 25, 1995 |authorlink=David E. Rosenbaum |first=David E. |last=Rosenbaum |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60610F93F580C768EDDA80894DD494D81 |title= Offending Portrait Succumbs To Black Lawmakers' Protest |work = [[New York Times]] |accessdate=2011-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nSmith was portrayed by American actor [[Ken Jenkins]] in the 2016 [[HBO]] TV movie ''[[All the Way (film)|All the Way]]'', in which his segregationist views posed as a central and divisive opposition to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]]'s proposal of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brauer, Carl M. \"Women Activists, Southern Conservatives, and the Prohibition of Sex Discrimination in Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act\", 49 ''Journal of Southern History'', February 1983 online via JSTOR\n* Dierenfield, Bruce J. ''Keeper of the Rules: Congressman Howard W. Smith of Virginia'' (1987)\n* Dierenfield, Bruce J. \"Conservative Outrage: the Defeat in 1966 of  Representative Howard W. Smith of Virginia.\" ''Virginia Magazine of History and Biography'' 1981 89 (2): 181-205.\n* Freeman, Jo. \"How 'Sex' Got Into Title VII: Persistent Opportunism as a Maker of Public Policy,\" ''Law and Inequality: A Journal of Theory and Practice'', Vol. 9, No. 2, March 1991, pp.&nbsp;163\u2013184. [http://www.jofreeman.com/lawandpolicy/titlevii.htm online version]\n* Gold, Michael Evan. ''A Tale of Two Amendments: The Reasons Congress Added Sex to Title VII and Their Implication for the Issue of Comparable Worth.'' Faculty Publications - Collective Bargaining, Labor Law, and Labor History. Cornell, 1981 [http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1010&context=cbpubs]\n* Jones, Charles O. \"Joseph G. Cannon and Howard W. Smith: an Essay on the Limits of Leadership in the House of Representatives\" ''[[Journal of Politics]]'' 1968 30(3): 617-646. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2128798 in JSTOR]\n* Robinson, Donald Allen. \"Two Movements in Pursuit of Equal Employment Opportunity.\" ''Signs'' 1979 4(3): 413-433. on alliance between Smith and Griffiths.\n* Storrs, Landon R. Y. ''Civilizing Capitalism: The National Consumers' League, Women's Activism, and Labor Standards in the New Deal Era'' [[University of North Carolina Press]]. 2000.\n* Woods, Clinton Jacob, \"Strange Bedfellows: Congressman Howard W. Smith and the Inclusion of Sex Discrimination in the 1964 Civil Rights Act,\" ''Southern Studies,'' 16 (Spring\u2013Summer 2009), 1\u201332.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Howard W. Smith}}\n* {{congbio|S000554}}\n* {{findagrave|7709428}}\n* {{pgbio|id=smith4.html}}\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/person.xpd?id=410036 Howard Smith,  former U.S. Representative - GovTrack.us]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= Virginia\n| district= 8\n| before= [[R. Walton Moore]]\n|after = 