{"title_page": "Italian Ethiopia", "text_new": "{{Infobox Former Country\n| native_name                = Etiopia italiana\n| conventional_long_name                = Italian Empire of Ethiopia\n| common_name                = \n| official_languages                = [[Italian language|Italian]]\n| common_languages                = [[Amharic]], [[Afan Oromo]], [[Somali language|Somali]], [[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]\n| status_text                = [[Colony]] of [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]\n| status                = Colonized\n| empire                = Kingdom of Ethiopia\n| era                = \n| year_start                = 1936\n| year_end                = 1944\n| life_span                = 1936-1944\n| p1                = Ethiopian Empire\n| flag_p1                = Flag of Ethiopia (1897-1936; 1941-1974).svg\n| s1                = Italian East Africa\n| flag_s1                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg\n| border_p2                = no\n| image_flag                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg\n| flag                = \n| image_coat                = Scudo Africa Orientale Italiana.svg\n| symbol_type                = Italian emperor Coat of Arms\n| symbol                = \n| image_map                = Italian East Africa (1938\u20131941).svg\n| image_map_caption                = Map of [[Italian East Africa]] after Italy's annexation of Ethiopia, as part of the [[Italian Empire]]. Italian Ethiopia was made of Harrar, Galla-Sidamo, Amhara and Scioa Governorate.\n| event1                = [[East Africa Campaign (World War II)|Allied liberation]]\n| date_event1                = 1941\n| event2                = [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|Guerrilla war]]\n| date_event2                = 1943\n| capital                = [[Addis Ababa]]\n| title_leader                = Emperor\n| leader1                = [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy]]\n| year_leader1                = 1936-41\n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2                = \n| currency                = [[Italian East African lira]]\n| stat_area1                = 1221900\n| stat_pop1                = \n| footnotes                = \n| religion                = \n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = \n}}\n'''Italian Ethiopia''' (in Italian: ''Etiopia italiana''), also known as the '''Italian Empire of Ethiopia''',<ref>[http://www.storiaxxisecolo.it/fascismo/fascismo14.htm ''La guerra di Etiopia (1935-36)'' (Italian)]</ref>, is the shorthand English name given to the Italian possession in the territory of modern-day [[Ethiopia]],<ref>Pasquale Villani, ''L'et\u00e0 contemporanea'' (Italian), il Mulino, Bologna, 1983, 1993, {{ISBN|88-15-02704-1}}, p. 446.</ref> obtained by expanding the existing [[Italian Somaliland|Somali]] and [[Italian Eritrea|Eritrean]] colonies in East Africa of the [[Kingdom of Italy]].<ref>https://razzismocolonialevenezia.wordpress.com/2017/01/08/nasce-limpero-letiopia-italiana/</ref>\n\nAfter the [[second Italo-Ethiopian War]], in which the [[Ethiopian Empire]] was occupied by the [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]] of [[Benito Mussolini]], the Ethiopian territories were proclaimed part of ''[[Italian East Africa|Africa Orientale Italiana ]]'' (AOI) in 1936, with the capital of AOI moved to [[Addis Ababa]]<ref>[https://dadfeatured.blogspot.com/2018/12/italian-addis-abeba.html Italian Addis Ababa]</ref> and [[Victor Emmanuel III]] proclaiming himself [[Emperor of Ethiopia#Italian conquest of Ethiopia|Emperor of Ethiopia]].<ref>During the Italian occupation of Ethiopia, Emperor Haile Selassie continued to reign as \"monarch in exile\".</ref>\n\nDuring the Italian rule, infrastructure to connect major cities, railways, public and private companies, and dams providing power and water were built; this along with the influx of Italian settlers and labourers, was the major cause of rapid urbanization growth. Also, the Italian government abolished [[Slavery in Ethiopia|slavery]], a practice that existed in the country for centuries.<ref name=\"Accessed 15 May 2008\">Shivley, K. \"Addis Ababa, Ethiopia\" [http://www.macalester.edu/courses/geog61/kshively/index.html Macalester.edu]. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1941, during World War II, Ethiopia was occupied by Allied forces, mainly from the British Empire, in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]], but an [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|Italian guerrilla war]] continued until 1943. Despite the return of Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] from his exile and the recognition of Ethiopian sovereignty with the signing of an Anglo-Ethiopian Treaty in December 1944, some regions still remained under British occupation for several more years.<ref name=\"Clapham\">Clapham,\"\u1e2aayl\u00e4 \u015a\ufffdllase\", ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'', p. 1063.</ref> Under the [[Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947|peace treaty of 1947]], Italy recognized the sovereignty and independence of Ethiopia and renounced all claims to special interests or influence in that country.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/us-treaties/bevans/m-ust000004-0311.pdf Treaty of Peace with Italy]</ref> Many [[Italians of Ethiopia|Italian settlers]] remained for decades after receiving full pardon by Emperor Selassie, as he saw an opportunity to continue the modernization efforts of the country.<ref>cfr. Angelo del Boca, op cit., p. 201</ref><ref>[https://www.amareonlus.com/it/rivista/numero-8/haile-selassie Hail\u00e8 Selassi\u00e8 - Amare Onlus (Italian)]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nSince May 1936 Italian Ethiopia was part of the newly created ''Africa Orientale Italiana'' (AOI), or [[Italian East Africa]], and administratively was made of four governorates: [[Amhara Governorate|Governorate of Amara]], [[Harrar Governorate|Governorate of Harrar]], [[Galla-Sidamo Governorate|Governorate of Galla-Sidamo]] and [[Scioa Governorate|Governorate of Shewa]]. Each Governorate was under the authority of an Italian governor, answerable to the [[List of viceroys of Italian East Africa|Italian viceroy]], who represented the Emperor [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy|Victor Emmanuel]].\nThe territory around the capital was renamed in 1939 ''Governorate of Scioa'': originally it was called \"Governorato di Addis Abeba\", but in 1939 the name was changed to show the region of Scioa around the area of Addis Ababa. This was done because areas of the nearby governorates of Harrar, Gallo-Sidamo and Amhara were included in it.\nItalian Ethiopia had an area of {{convert|305,000|sqmi|km2|order=flip}} and a population of 9,450,000 inhabitants, resulting in a density of {{convert|31|PD/sqmi|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Royal Institute of International Affairs|title=Italian Possessions in Africa: II. Italian East Africa|journal=Bulletin of International News|date=24 August 1940|volume=17|issue=17|pages=1065\u20131074}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Governorate!! Italian name!! Capital!! Total population!! Italians<ref>Istat Statistiche 2010</ref> !! Car Tag!! Coat of Arms\n|-\n| [[Amhara Governorate]] || Amara || [[Gondar]] || 2,000,000 || 11,103 || AM || [[File:Coat of arms of Amhara governorate-2.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Harrar Governorate]] || Harar || [[Harrar]] || 1,600,000 || 10,035 || HA || [[File:Coat of arms of harar governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Galla-Sidamo Governorate]] || Galla e Sidama || [[Jimma]]/Gimma || 4,000,000 || 11,823|| GS || [[File:Coat of arms of Galla-Sidamo governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Shewa Governorate]] || Scioa || [[Addis Ababa]] || 1,850,000 || 40,698 || SC || [[File:Coat of arms of Scioa governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\nSome territories of the defeated Kingdom of Ethiopia were added to Italian Eritrea and Italian Somalia inside the AOI. This was not just since they were mainly populated by Eritreans and Somalis respectively, but also as a reward for their colonial soldiers who fought in the Italian Army against the [[Negus]] troops).{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=September 2017}}\n\nThe currency used was the [[Italian East African lira]]: the ''Lira AOI'' were special banknotes of 50 lire and 100 lire circulating in AOI between 1938 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancaditalia.it/servizi_pubbl/museo_banconota/emissioni/emissioni_oltremare%3Binternal%26action%3D_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en |title=Bank of Italy |access-date=2020-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327062618/http://www.bancaditalia.it/servizi_pubbl/museo_banconota/emissioni/emissioni_oltremare%3Binternal%26action%3D_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en |archive-date=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and 1941:\n\n==History==\n\n===Conquest and occupation===\n{{main article|Second Italo-Abyssinian War|Italian East Africa}}\n[[File:Monument fasciste de Gorgora - c\u00f4t\u00e9 est - 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|''Mussolini\u2019s Stele'' in Gorgora]]\nEmperor Haile Selassie's reign was interrupted on 3 October 1935<ref>{{cite book |ref={{harvid|Barker|1971}} |first=A. J. |last=Barker |title=Rape of Ethiopia, 1936 |publisher=Ballantine Books |year=1971 |p=33 |location=New York |isbn=978-0-345-02462-6}}</ref> when Italian forces, under the direction of dictator [[Benito Mussolini]], [[Second Italo-Abyssinian War|invaded and occupied]] Ethiopia.\n\nThey occupied the capital, Addis Ababa, on 5 May 1936. Emperor Haile Selassie pleaded to the [[League of Nations]] for aid in resisting the Italians. Nevertheless, the country was formally occupied on 9 May 1936 and the Emperor went into exile.\n\nThe war was full of cruelty: the Ethiopians used [[Dum-dum]] bullets (prohibited by the [[Hague Conventions (1899 and 1907)|Hague Convention]] of 1899, Declaration IV, 3) and the Italians used gas (prohibited under the [[Geneva Protocol]] of 1922).<ref>Antonicelli, Franco. ''Trent'anni di storia italiana 1915 - 1945'', p. 79.</ref> Many Ethiopians died in the invasion. The [[Negus]] claimed that more than 5000 Ethiopian fighters were killed compared to only 1,537 Italians, while the Italian authorities estimated that 16,000 Ethiopians and 2,700 Italians (including Italian colonial troops) died in battle.<ref>Antonicelli, Franco. ''Trent'anni di storia italiana 1915 - 1945'', p. 133.</ref>\n\n[[File:Rodolfo Graziani 1940 (Retouched).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Marshal Graziani in 1940]]\n[[Rodolfo Graziani|Marshal Graziani]], who replaced Marshal Badoglio as viceroy of Italian East Africa in May 1936 was short-tempered and inclined to violence and atrocities multiplied under his administration. Following a failed attack against Addis Ababa by rebels on 28 July 1936, he had the archbishop of Dessie, whom he suspected of being behind the attack shot the same afternoon. All resisting Ethiopians were declared \"bandits\" and he ordered that they be shot on capture. Mussolini approved the decision but requested that the order be kept secret. Following the defeat of rebels led by Ras Desta in the western part of the country in late December 1936, he had 1600 rebel troops who surrendered summarily executed by firing squads. Villages that had been friendly to Desta were burned to the ground and women and children shot. Desta and other captured rebel leaders were executed in February 1937. The Italians undertook many other terrorist actions during this period. Following a bloody attempt on the life of Graziani and other Italian officials by two Eritreans during a ceremony to celebrate the birth of the [[Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples|Prince of Naples]] on 19 February 1937, the police and soldiers, fearing a general uprising, fired indiscriminately into the crowd. Innocent bystanders were shot. For the next three days, the Italians, led by the [[Blackshirts]], went on a rampage of murder and destruction throughout Addis Ababa. By the end of 1937 more than 5000 people had been executed for alleged crimes related to the attempt against Graziani. Among them were virtually all the young educated Ethiopians the Italians could lay their hands on and all the officiers and cadets of the Holeta Military Academy. The Italian viceroy had hermits, soothsayers and travelling minstrels rounded up and executed. Convinced that the high clergy had known about the plot, he had many executed. In May 1937, he ordered 297 monks of the monastery of [[Debre Libanos]] and 23 other individuals suspected of complicity shot. Over 100 deacons and students were also executed. Several hundred monks were sent to concentration camps. Viceroy Graziani was finally replaced in November 1938 by the more humane [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta|Duke of Aosta]], who put an end to wanton atrocities which had had the effect of increasing resistance to Italian domination.<ref>Paul B. Henze, ''Layers of Time. A History of Ethiopia'', Palgrave, New York, 2000, p. 225\u2013227.</ref>\n\nWhile some countries recognized the Italian conquest, Great Britain, France and the League of Nations refused to formally recognize it and consequently it remained illegitimate in international law.<ref>For that reason, following the collapse of Italian power in 1941, Haile Selassie reassumed power without the need of any formal recognition by the international community.</ref>\n\nThe King of Italy ([[Victor Emmanuel III]]) was crowned [[Emperor of Ethiopia]] and the Italians created an [[Italian empire]] in Africa ([[Italian East Africa]]) with Ethiopia, Eritrea and Italian Somalia. In 1937 Mussolini boasted that, with his conquest of Ethiopia, \"finally [[Battle of Adwa|Adua]] was avenged\".\n\n{{Quote|We will never be the masters if we are not conscious of our preordained superiority. We do not fraternize with the Negroes. We can not, we must not. At least not until they have been civilized.|Well-known Italian reporter [[Indro Montanelli]]}}\n\n[[File:RAS Abissini Pd-italy-005.jpg|thumb|left|Ras Sejum Mangasci\u00e0, Ras Ghetacci\u00f9 Abat\u00e9 and Ras Kebbed\u00e9 Guebret offered support to [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]] in February 1937.]]\nSome Ethiopians welcomed the Italians and collaborated with them in the government of the newly created ''Impero italiano'', like Ras [[Seyoum Mengesha|Sejum Mangasci\u00e0]], Ras Ghetacci\u00f9 Abat\u00e9 and Ras Kebbed\u00e9 Guebret. In 1937 the friendship of Sejum Mangascia with the Italian Viceroy [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]] enabled this Ras to play an influential role in securing the release of 3,000 Ethiopian POWs being held in [[Italian Somaliland]].\n\nThe Italians invested substantively in Ethiopian infrastructure development. They created the \"imperial road\" between Addis Ababa and [[Massaua]], the Addis Ababa - [[Mogadishu]] and the Addis Ababa - [[Assab]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.tecnici.it/file/novecento/autocamionale_assab_addis-abeba.pdf |accessdate=28 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329080126/http://media.tecnici.it/file/novecento/autocamionale_assab_addis-abeba.pdf |archivedate=29 March 2016 |date=1940 |title=Article on the special road Addis Abeba-Assab and map (in Italian)}}</ref> the Italians built more than 4,500&nbsp;km of roads linking the country beyond\n900&nbsp;km of railways were reconstructed or initiated (like the railway between Addis Ababa and [[Assab]]), dams and hydroelectric plants were built, and many public and private companies were established in the underdeveloped country. The most important were: \"Compagnie per il cotone d'Etiopia\" (Cotton industry); \"Cementerie d'Etiopia\" (Cement industry); \"Compagnia etiopica mineraria\" (Minerals industry); \"Imprese elettriche d'Etiopia\" (Electricity industry); \"Compagnia etiopica degli esplosivi\" (Armament industry); \"Trasporti automobilistici (Citao)\" (Mechanic & Transport industry).  \n \nItalians even created new airports and in 1936 started the worldwide famous [[Imperial Line|''Linea dell'Impero'']], a flight connecting Addis Ababa to [[Rome]]. The line was opened after the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War|Italian conquest of Ethiopia]] and was followed by the first air links with the Italian colonies in [[Italian East Africa]], which began in a pioneering way since 1934. The route was enlarged to 6,379&nbsp;km and initially joined [[Rome]] with [[Addis Ababa]] via [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Benghazi]], [[Cairo]], [[Wadi Halfa]], [[Khartoum]], [[Kassala]], [[Asmara]], [[Dire Dawa]].<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/africa_res-2a855323-8b74-11dc-8e9d-0016357eee51_%28Enciclopedia-Italiana%29/ Treccani: Via dell'Impero (in Italian)]</ref> There was a change of aircraft in [[Benghazi]] (or sometimes in [[Tripoli-Castel Benito Airport|Tripoli]]). The route was carried out in three and a half days of daytime flight and the frequency was four flights per week in both directions. Later from Addis Ababa there were three flights a week that continued to [[Mogadishu]], capital of [[Italian Somalia]].\n \nThe most important railway line in the African colonies of the Kingdom of Italy, the 784&nbsp;km long [[Ethio-Djibouti Railways|Franco-Ethiopian Railway]], was [[:File:Dire Dawa Station Blackshirts 1936.jpg|seized following the conquest of Ethiopia in 1936]]. The route was served until 1935 by steam trains that took about 36 hours to do the total trip between the capital of Ethiopia and the port of [[Djibouti]]. Following the Italian conquest was obtained in 1938 the increase of speed for the trains with the introduction of four railcars high capacity \"type 038\" derived from the model ''Fiat ALn56''.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/autorails_fiat_cfe/pages/image/imagepage15.html Fiat ALn56 \"Littorina\"]</ref>\n \nThese diesel trains were able to reach 70&nbsp;km/h and cutting time travel in half to just 18 hours: they were used until the mid 1960s.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/autorails_fiat_cfe/pages/image/imagepage30.html Image of a Fiat ALn56 in 1964 Addis Ababa station]</ref> At the main stations there were some bus connections to the other cities of Italian Ethiopia not served by the railway.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/gare_diredawa_cfe/pages/image/imagepage15.html Dire Dawa bus connection to Harrar]</ref> Additionally, near the Addis Ababa station was created a special unit against fire, that was the only one in all Africa.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.storiavvf.it/Articolo%20Addis%20Abeba.htm |title=\"Pompieri ad Addis Abeba\" (in Italian) |access-date=2015-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104191728/http://www.storiavvf.it/Articolo%20Addis%20Abeba.htm |archive-date=2016-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n \n{{Quote|In 1936, during the occupation of Ethiopia, the Italians considered the construction of new railway routes from Addis-Ababa running as follows: Addis-Ababa, Dessie, Adigrat, Massawa: covering 1000 km; Addis-Ababa, Dessie, Assab - Dessie, Gondar, Om, Ager; Addis-Ababa, Megheli, Dollo, Mogadishu. All these projects had to be abandoned due to war operations.|Jean Pierre Crozet}}\n \nProjects of connecting to the Eritrean railway network did not found practical realization in 1939. In the same year was studied the possibility of connecting the Ethiopian station of [[Dire-Dawa]] to the port of [[Assab]] in southern Eritrea, in order to bypass the [[French Somaliland]]. Until 1938 there was a protective military unit in the trains, because of the Ethiopian guerrilla in the area (that by the beginning of World War II faded away).<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/divers_cfe/pages/image/imagepage34.html Photo of Italian soldiers defending the ethiopian railway trains]</ref>\n[[File:Italian communications in Ethiopia, April 1941.jpg|thumb|right|Map showing in red the new roads (like the \"Imperial road\", and those in construction in 1941) created by the Italians in Ethiopia]]\n\nThe Italians not only made new roads & other structural improvements, but they also greatly improved the socio-economical conditions of the native population, as the same emperor Haile Selassie recognized when back in power after 1941. {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nIndeed, much of these improvements were part of a plan to bring half a million Italians to colonize the Ethiopian plateaus. In October 1939 the [[Italians of Ethiopia|Italian colonists in Ethiopia]] were 35,441, of whom 30,232 male (85.3%) and 5,209 female (14.7%), most of them living in urban areas.<ref>[http://www.ilcornodafrica.it/rds-01emigrazione.pdf Italian emigration in Etiopia (in Italian)]</ref> Only 3,200 Italian farmers moved to colonize farm areas, mostly around the capital and in the [[Scioa Governorate]], where they were under sporadic attack by pro-Haile Selassie guerrillas until 1939.\n \nHowever, the [[Shifta|Ethiopian guerrillas]] - that in late 1939 were still controlling nearly a quarter of the Ethiopian highlands (but had never been active in the areas of Ethiopia united to Eritrea and Somalia in 1936 {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} )- were present at the beginning of World War II only in the Harar and Galla-Sidamo Governorate. According to the viceroy [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]] the guerrillas were going to disappear in another two years (as had happened in [[Italian Cyrenaica|Cyrenaica]] in the early 1930s). Indeed, [[Abebe Aregai]], the last leader of the \"Arbegnocks\" (as the guerrilla fighters were called in Ethiopia) after the 1939 surrender of Ethiopian leaders Zaudi\u00e8 Asfau and Olon\u00e0 Dinkel, made a surrender proposal to the Italians in spring 1940.<ref>Bahru Zewde, \"A History of Modern Ethiopia\", second edition (Oxford: James Currey, 2001), pp. 172f</ref> \n \nIn early 1940, also as a consequence of the guerrilla nearly disappearance, Italian Ethiopia was enjoying a small \"boom\" of economic & social development with the commerce and industrial sector greatly improving in the capital and in the main cities. {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{Quote|A remarkable effort was made to improve healthcare in Ethiopia: beside the doctors belonging to the Italian Africa Health Corps, flanked by 450 military doctors, there were about 500 civilian doctors (232 specialists, among whom 30 pediatricians, and 262 general practitioners). Special maternity wards were built in the hospitals situated in the main locations. The new Italian hospital in Addis Ababa had a delivery room and a pediatric clinic, with a capacity of over 100 beds in its various sections: expectant mothers, postpartum mothers, babies\u2019 room, gynecological ward, infectious diseases, visitors\u2019 room, etc. The children\u2019s hospital was subdivided into separate wards for babies and older children, for infectious, gastro-intestinal or pulmonary diseases, etc. Moreover, a university-type faculty was founded in 1941 in Asmara to train nurses....Social life in Addis Ababa (and Asmara) was pulsating just like that of any other European town. At the heart of the city were the markets: in the capital (Addis Ababa) in 1939 over 75,000 heads of cattle had been slaughtered and thousands of tons of foodstuffs had been sold. Dozens of shops and even department stores were opened in both cities. Leisure activities also boomed: in Addis Ababa four cinemas had been built...New dancehalls, restaurants and bars were being opened everywhere. The working men\u2019s clubs and numerous sports and recreational societies, supported by local government and by the PNF, organised the colonists\u2019 (and native Etiopians) free time.|G. Podesta<ref>[https://www.cairn.info/revue-annales-de-demographie-historique-2011-2-page-205.htm Podesta: \"Family and Society in Italian Africa\"]</ref>}}\n\nDuring the five years of Italian occupation, [[Catholicism]] also grew in importance, thanks mainly to the efforts of missionaries like [[Elisa Angela Meneguzzi]]. She became known as the \"Ecumenical Fire\" due to her strong efforts at [[ecumenism]] with [[Coptic Christians]] and [[Islam|Muslims]] while also catering to relations with the Catholics of [[Dire Dawa]].<ref>[http://catholicsaints.info/blessed-liduina-meneguzzi/  Blessed Elisa Angela Meneguzzi]</ref>)\n\n[[File:Stairs of the Lion of Judea in Addis Ababa.jpg|thumb|Mussolini's ''Stairway to Nowhere'', monument at the Addis Abeba University  with a stair for every year of Mussolini's rule since 1922]]\n\n===World War II===\nDuring [[World War II]], in the summer of 1940 Italian armed forces [[Italian conquest of British Somaliland|successfully invaded all of British Somaliland]].<ref>Dickson (2001) p.103</ref> But, by spring of 1941, the British had counter-attacked and pushed deep into [[Italian East Africa]]. By 5 May, [[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia]] had returned to [[Addis Ababa]] to reclaim his throne. In November, the last organised Italian resistance in Ethiopia ended with the fall of [[Battle of Gondar|Gondar]].<ref>Jowett (2001) p.7</ref> However, following the surrender of East Africa, some Italians [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|conducted a guerrilla war]] which lasted for two more years.\n\nThis guerrilla was done primarily by military units with Italian officers (like Captain Paolo Aloisi, Captain Leopoldo Rizzo, Blackshirt officer De Varda and Major Lucchetti) but also by civilians like [[Rosa Dainelli]]. She was a doctor who in August 1942 succeeded in entering the main ammunition depot of the British army in [[Addis Ababa]], and blowing it up, miraculously survived the huge explosion. Her sabotage destroyed the ammunition for the new British [[Sten submachine gun|Sten]] sub machine gun, delaying the use of this \"state of the art\" armament for many months.<ref>Rosselli, Alberto. ''Storie Segrete. Operazioni sconosciute o dimenticate della seconda guerra mondiale''. pag. 103</ref> Her true name was Danielli Rosa and the date of attack was September 15, 1941.<ref>Di Lalla, Fabrizio, \u201cSotto due bandiere. Lotta di liberazione etiopica e resistenza italiana in Africa Orientale\u201d. p. 235</ref>\n\n===After World War II===\n[[File:Ethiopian electric power corporation Addis Abeba.jpg|thumb|Italian-era electric power corporation building in Addis Ababa]]\nThe recognition by the United Kingdom of the full sovereignty of Ethiopia occurred with the signing on 19 December 1944 of the Anglo-Ethiopian agreement which acknowledged Ethiopia to be \"a free and independent state\"<ref>Henze, p. 235.</ref> although various regions remained under British occupation for some years.<ref name=\"Clapham\"/>\n\nIn the [[Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947|peace treaty of February 1947]], Italy renounced sovereignty over its African colonies of Libya, Eritrea and Somalia (art. 23) and recognised the independence of Ethiopia (art. 33), by then a sovereign member of the United Nations. \n\nItaly further agreed to:\n* Pay [[War reparation]] of US$25,000,000 to Ethiopia\n* Accept \"Annex XI of the Treaty\", upon the recommendation of the United Nations General Assembly in Resolution 390, that indicated that [[Eritrea]] was to be federated with Ethiopia.\n\nAfter the war, the [[Italian Ethiopians]] were given a full pardon by the newly returned Emperor Haile Selassie, as he saw the opportunity to continue the modernization efforts of the country.<ref name=\"Italoethiopians\">[https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/ Photos and articles of Italoethiopians who took refuge in Italy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211022551/https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/ |date=2017-02-11 }}</ref> He declared that no reprisals would be taken against the Italians, and many remained for decades, until the overthrow of the Emperor in the [[Ethiopian Civil War]] in 1974. Nearly 22,000 Italo-Ethiopians took refuge in Italy during the 1970s.<ref name=\"Italoethiopians\"/> Their main organization in Italy is the Associazione Italiana Profughi dall'Etiopia ed Eritrea (A.I.P.E.E.).<ref>[http://www.aipee.it/home.html Associazione Italiana Profughi dall'Etiopia ed Eritrea (AIPEE)]</ref>\n\nIn recent years, some Italian companies have returned to operate in Ethiopia, and a large number of Italian technicians and managers arrived with their families, residing mainly in the metropolitan area of the capital.<ref>https://dait.interno.gov.it/servizi-demografici</ref>\n\n==Contemporary relations==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right|direction=vertical|width=190\n|image1=2 giugno 2002-Axum.JPG\n|caption1=The [[Obelisk of Axum]] in [[Rome]] before its repatriation\n|image2=G7 Taormina Paolo Gentiloni Hailemariam Desalegn handshake 2017-05-27.jpg\n|caption2=[[Paolo Gentiloni]] and [[Hailemariam Desalegn]] at the [[43rd G7 summit]]\n}}\n\nIn the mid-1990s despite a previous arrangement with the Dergue regime under [[Mengistu Haile Mariam|Menghistu]] in the 1970s to cede the [[Obelisk of Axum]] to Italy in exchange for medical facilities and forgiving an accumulated debt to the Italian government, a populist movement made up of Italians and Ethiopians (both in country and expatriates around the world) began to petition the then current Italian government to return the obelisk,<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-03-10/news/0203100403_1_obelisk-ethiopian-people-ethiopian-embassy Chicago Tribune,March 10, 2002 \"Ethiopia Again Demands Italy Return Obelisk\"]</ref> an event which eventually culminated in its [[Obelisk of Axum#Repatriation|repatriation]] in 2008 to Axum, the city of its creation.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/apr/20/italy.ethiopian The Guardian, 20 April, 2005 \"Obelisk returned to Ethiopia after 68 years\"]</ref>\n\nThe Italian firm [[Salini Impregilo|Salini Costruttori]] was chosen by the Ethiopian government to design and build the Millennium or [[Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam#Construction|Renaissance Dam]] on the [[Blue Nile|Blue Nile river]], which when completed will be the largest dam and hydroelectric plant in Africa.<ref>[http://www.salini-impregilo.com/en/projects/in-progress/dams-hydroelectric-plants-hydraulic-works/grand-ethiopian-renaissance-dam-project.html Grand Renaissance Dam Project in Ethiopia]</ref> As the Italian engineers had helped to build the first railway from Addis to Djibouti in the past, the Ethiopian government has contracted them again to expand the railroad network along with India and China.<ref>[http://www.globalconreview.com/markets/ethiopia-steams-ahead-vision-modern-n8a8t8i8o8n8al/ Global Construction View - \"Ethiopia Steams Ahead\"]</ref> For the last 20 years, Italy has continued to be among the top 5 trading partners with Ethiopia and a major investor in the Ethiopian economy.<ref>[http://atlas.media.mit.edu/profile/country/eth/ MIT Country Profile - Ethiopia: Trading Partners]</ref>\n\nEthiopian languages such as Amharic and Tigrinya have many words borrowed from the Italian language, for example \"gettone\" (token), \"bigli\" from Italian \"biglie\" (glass marbles), \"borsa\" (bag), \"mach\u00ecna\" from Italian \"macchina\" (car), \"carburatore\" (carburetor) and others.<ref name=\"Yaqob\">{{cite web|url=https://totalitarismo.altervista.org/italianismi-nel-somalo-e-nell-amarico/|title=Italianismi nel somalo e nell\u2019amarico|first=Mister|last=Totalitarismo|date=2 December 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"altervista\">''I prestiti italiani in amarico e tigrino'', Yaqob Beyene</ref> Ethiopia has the largest concentration of Italian schools and cultural institutes in Africa (such as the [[Istituto Statale Italiano Omnicomprensivo di Addis Abeba|Scuola Statale Italiana]] of Addis Ababa), which foster and promote Italian and Ethiopian culture and are free to the public.<ref>[http://www.iicaddisabeba.esteri.it/IIC_AddisAbeba/Menu/Istituto/Come_raggiungerci/ Italian Cultural Institute of Addis Ababa]</ref>\n\n==Banknotes and postage stamps==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; border-bottom:2px solid gray;\" bgcolor=\"lightsteelblue\"\n! Frontal Image\n! Back Image\n! Amount\n! Color\n! Frontal Description\n! Back Description\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP1b-50Lire-1939 f-donated.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP1b-50Lire-1939 b-donated.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |'''50 Lire'''\n| align=\"left\" |Green\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CINQVANTA - BANCA D'ITALIA</small>\n| align=\"left\" |<small>50 LIRE - Lupa romana</small>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP2b-100Lire-1938-donatedms f.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP2b-100Lire-1938-donatedms b.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |'''100 Lire'''\n| align=\"left\" |Green/gray\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CENTO - BANCA D'ITALIA - Dea Roma</small>\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CENTO - BANCA D'ITALIA - Aquila</small>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\nOn 5 May 1936 the capital Addis Ababa was captured by the Italians: on 22 May three new stamps showing the King of Italy were issued. Four further values inscribed \"ETIOPIA\" were issued on 5 December 1936. After that date, the stamps were issued with the name \"Africa Orientale Italiana\" on it.<ref>[http://www.italianstamps.co.uk/colonies/ethiopia/index.html Postage stamps of Italian Ethiopia]</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=September 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{C|Italian East Africa|Italian East Africa topics}}\n* [[Italians of Ethiopia]]\n* [[Italian Eritrea]]\n* [[Italian Somalia]]\n* [[Imperial Line|Linea dell'Impero]]\n* [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://razzismocolonialevenezia.wordpress.com/2017/01/08/nasce-limpero-letiopia-italiana/|title=Nasce l\u2019Impero: l\u2019Etiopia italiana|last=Conte|first=Alessio|date=2017-01-08|website=Ascari e Schiavoni|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Italy)]] |location=[[Rome]], Italy |url=http://www.esteri.it/mae/ministero/servizi/archiviostorico/2013/2asmai_vol.i_eritrea_etiopia_somalia.pdf |language=it |title={{lang-it|Inventario dell'Archivio Storico del Ministero Africa Italiana|translit=Index of the historical archive of the ministry of Italian Africa|link=no|nocat=true}} |volume=1: (1857-1939) |year= 1975 |access-date=2017-12-20}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bandini |first=Franco |title=Gli italiani in Africa: Storia delle guerre coloniali 1882-1943 |publisher=[[Longanesi]] |language=it |location=[[Milan]], Italy |date=1971 |oclc=1253348}}\n* {{cite book |last=Beltrami |first=Vanni |title=Italia d'Oltremare: Storie dei territori italiani dalla conquista alla caduta |language=it |publisher=Edizioni Nuova Cultura |location=[[Rome]] Italy |date=2013 |isbn=978-88-6134-702-1 |page=273 |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=TE2ldbz57eIC&lpg=PR1&hl=it&pg=PA273#v=onepage&q&f=false |access-date=2017-12-20}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Keith |title=World War II for Dummies |publisher=Wiley |location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]], US |date=2001 |isbn=9780764553523 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/worldwariifordum00dick }}\n* {{cite book |last=Jowett |first=Philip S |title=The Italian Army 1940\u201345 2: Africa 1940\u201343  |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=[[Oxford]], UK |date=2001 |isbn=9781855328655}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Sbiacchi |first=Alberto |title=Hail\u00e9 Selassi\u00e9 and the Italians, 1941-43 |work=[[African Studies Review]] |volume=XXII |issue=1 |date=April 1979 |publisher=[[African Studies Association]]}}\n\n{{Italian Ethiopia}}\n{{Italian colonial empire}}\n{{WWII_history_by_nation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Italian East Africa|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Former Italian colonies|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:History of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1930s in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1940s in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1930s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1940s in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ethiopia\u2013Italy relations]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1936]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1947]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Former Country\n| native_name                = Etiopia italiana\n| conventional_long_name                = Italian Empire of Ethiopia\n| common_name                = \n| official_languages                = [[Italian language|Italian]]\n| common_languages                = [[Amharic]], [[Afan Oromo]], [[Somali language|Somali]], [[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]\n| status_text                = [[Colony]] of [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]\n| status                = Colonized\n| empire                = Kingdom of Ethiopia\n| era                = \n| year_start                = 1936\n| year_end                = 1944\n| life_span                = 1936-1944\n| p1                = Ethiopian Empire\n| flag_p1                = Flag of Ethiopia (1897-1936; 1941-1974).svg\n| s1                = Italian East Africa\n| flag_s1                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg\n| border_p2                = no\n| image_flag                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg\n| flag                = \n| image_coat                = Scudo Africa Orientale Italiana.svg\n| symbol_type                = Italian emperor Coat of Arms\n| symbol                = \n| image_map                = Italian East Africa (1938\u20131941).svg\n| image_map_caption                = Map of [[Italian East Africa]] after Italy's annexation of Ethiopia, as part of the [[Italian Empire]]. Italian Ethiopia was made of Harrar, Galla-Sidamo, Amhara and Scioa Governorate.\n| event1                = [[East Africa Campaign (World War II)|Allied liberation]]\n| date_event1                = 1941\n| event2                = [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|Guerrilla war]]\n| date_event2                = 1943\n| capital                = [[Addis Ababa]]\n| title_leader                = Emperor\n| leader1                = [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy]]\n| year_leader1                = 1936-41\n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2                = \n| currency                = [[Italian East African lira]]\n| stat_area1                = 1221900\n| stat_pop1                = \n| footnotes                = \n| religion                = \n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| today                = \n}}\n'''Italian Ethiopia''' (in Italian: ''Etiopia italiana''), also known as the '''Italian Empire of Ethiopia''',<ref>[http://www.storiaxxisecolo.it/fascismo/fascismo14.htm ''La guerra di Etiopia (1935-36)'' (Italian)]</ref>, is the shorthand English name given to the Italian possession in the territory of modern-day [[Ethiopia]],<ref>Pasquale Villani, ''L'et\u00e0 contemporanea'' (Italian), il Mulino, Bologna, 1983, 1993, {{ISBN|88-15-02704-1}}, p. 446.</ref> obtained by expanding the existing [[Italian Somaliland|Somali]] and [[Italian Eritrea|Eritrean]] colonies in East Africa of the [[Kingdom of Italy]].<ref>https://razzismocolonialevenezia.wordpress.com/2017/01/08/nasce-limpero-letiopia-italiana/</ref>\n\nAfter the [[second Italo-Ethiopian War]], in which the [[Ethiopian Empire]] was occupied by the [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]] of [[Benito Mussolini]], the Ethiopian territories were proclaimed part of ''[[Italian East Africa|Africa Orientale Italiana ]]'' (AOI) in 1936, with the capital of AOI moved to [[Addis Ababa]]<ref>[https://dadfeatured.blogspot.com/2018/12/italian-addis-abeba.html Italian Addis Ababa]</ref> and [[Victor Emmanuel III]] proclaiming himself [[Emperor of Ethiopia#Italian conquest of Ethiopia|Emperor of Ethiopia]].<ref>During the Italian occupation of Ethiopia, Emperor Haile Selassie continued to reign as \"monarch in exile\".</ref>\n\nDuring the Italian rule, infrastructure to connect major cities, railways, public and private companies, and dams providing power and water were built; this along with the influx of Italian settlers and labourers, was the major cause of rapid urbanization growth. Also, the Italian government abolished [[Slavery in Ethiopia|slavery]], a practice that existed in the country for centuries.<ref name=\"Accessed 15 May 2008\">Shivley, K. \"Addis Ababa, Ethiopia\" [http://www.macalester.edu/courses/geog61/kshively/index.html Macalester.edu]. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1941, during World War II, Ethiopia was occupied by Allied forces, mainly from the British Empire, in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)|East African Campaign]], but an [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|Italian guerrilla war]] continued until 1943. Despite the return of Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] from his exile and the recognition of Ethiopian sovereignty with the signing of an Anglo-Ethiopian Treaty in December 1944, some regions still remained under British occupation for several more years.<ref name=\"Clapham\">Clapham,\"\u1e2aayl\u00e4 \u015a\ufffdllase\", ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'', p. 1063.</ref> Under the [[Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947|peace treaty of 1947]], Italy recognized the sovereignty and independence of Ethiopia and renounced all claims to special interests or influence in that country.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/law/help/us-treaties/bevans/m-ust000004-0311.pdf Treaty of Peace with Italy]</ref> Many [[Italians of Ethiopia|Italian settlers]] remained for decades after receiving full pardon by Emperor Selassie, as he saw an opportunity to continue the modernization efforts of the country.<ref>cfr. Angelo del Boca, op cit., p. 201</ref><ref>[https://www.amareonlus.com/it/rivista/numero-8/haile-selassie Hail\u00e8 Selassi\u00e8 - Amare Onlus (Italian)]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nSince May 1936 Italian Ethiopia was part of the newly created ''Africa Orientale Italiana'' (AOI), or [[Italian East Africa]], and administratively was made of four governorates: [[Amhara Governorate|Governorate of Amara]], [[Harrar Governorate|Governorate of Harrar]], [[Galla-Sidamo Governorate|Governorate of Galla-Sidamo]] and [[Scioa Governorate|Governorate of Shewa]]. Each Governorate was under the authority of an Italian governor, answerable to the [[List of viceroys of Italian East Africa|Italian viceroy]], who represented the Emperor [[Victor Emmanuel III of Italy|Victor Emmanuel]].\nThe territory around the capital was renamed in 1939 ''Governorate of Scioa'': originally it was called \"Governorato di Addis Abeba\", but in 1939 the name was changed to show the region of Scioa around the area of Addis Ababa. This was done because areas of the nearby governorates of Harrar, Gallo-Sidamo and Amhara were included in it.\nItalian Ethiopia had an area of {{convert|305,000|sqmi|km2|order=flip}} and a population of 9,450,000 inhabitants, resulting in a density of {{convert|31|PD/sqmi|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Royal Institute of International Affairs|title=Italian Possessions in Africa: II. Italian East Africa|journal=Bulletin of International News|date=24 August 1940|volume=17|issue=17|pages=1065\u20131074}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Governorate!! Italian name!! Capital!! Total population!! Italians<ref>Istat Statistiche 2010</ref> !! Car Tag!! Coat of Arms\n|-\n| [[Amhara Governorate]] || Amara || [[Gondar]] || 2,000,000 || 11,103 || AM || [[File:Coat of arms of Amhara governorate-2.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Harrar Governorate]] || Harar || [[Harrar]] || 1,600,000 || 10,035 || HA || [[File:Coat of arms of harar governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Galla-Sidamo Governorate]] || Galla e Sidama || [[Jimma]]/Gimma || 4,000,000 || 11,823|| GS || [[File:Coat of arms of Galla-Sidamo governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n| [[Shewa Governorate]] || Scioa || [[Addis Ababa]] || 1,850,000 || 40,698 || SC || [[File:Coat of arms of Scioa governorate.svg|30px]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\nSome territories of the defeated Kingdom of Ethiopia were added to Italian Eritrea and Italian Somalia inside the AOI. This was not just since they were mainly populated by Eritreans and Somalis respectively, but also as a reward for their colonial soldiers who fought in the Italian Army against the [[Negus]] troops).{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=September 2017}}\n\nThe currency used was the [[Italian East African lira]]: the ''Lira AOI'' were special banknotes of 50 lire and 100 lire circulating in AOI between 1938 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bancaditalia.it/servizi_pubbl/museo_banconota/emissioni/emissioni_oltremare%3Binternal%26action%3D_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en |title=Bank of Italy |access-date=2020-01-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327062618/http://www.bancaditalia.it/servizi_pubbl/museo_banconota/emissioni/emissioni_oltremare%3Binternal%26action%3D_setlanguage.action?LANGUAGE=en |archive-date=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and 1941:\n\n==History==\n\n===Conquest and occupation===\n{{main article|Second Italo-Abyssinian War|Italian East Africa}}\n[[File:Monument fasciste de Gorgora - c\u00f4t\u00e9 est - 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|''Mussolini\u2019s Stele'' in Gorgora]]\nEmperor Haile Selassie's reign was interrupted on 3 October 1935<ref>{{cite book |ref={{harvid|Barker|1971}} |first=A. J. |last=Barker |title=Rape of Ethiopia, 1936 |publisher=Ballantine Books |year=1971 |p=33 |location=New York |isbn=978-0-345-02462-6}}</ref> when Italian forces, under the direction of dictator [[Benito Mussolini]], [[Second Italo-Abyssinian War|invaded and occupied]] Ethiopia.\n\nThey occupied the capital, Addis Ababa, on 5 May 1936. Emperor Haile Selassie pleaded to the [[League of Nations]] for aid in resisting the Italians. Nevertheless, the country was formally occupied on 9 May 1936 and the Emperor went into exile.\n\nThe war was full of cruelty: the Ethiopians used [[Dum-dum]] bullets (prohibited by the [[Hague Conventions (1899 and 1907)|Hague Convention]] of 1899, Declaration IV, 3) and the Italians used gas (prohibited under the [[Geneva Protocol]] of 1922).<ref>Antonicelli, Franco. ''Trent'anni di storia italiana 1915 - 1945'', p. 79.</ref> Many Ethiopians died in the invasion. The [[Negus]] claimed that more than 5000 Ethiopian fighters were killed compared to only 1,537 Italians, while the Italian authorities estimated that 16,000 Ethiopians and 2,700 Italians (including Italian colonial troops) died in battle.<ref>Antonicelli, Franco. ''Trent'anni di storia italiana 1915 - 1945'', p. 133.</ref>\n\n[[File:Rodolfo Graziani 1940 (Retouched).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Marshal Graziani in 1940]]\n[[Rodolfo Graziani|Marshal Graziani]], who replaced Marshal Badoglio as viceroy of Italian East Africa in May 1936 was short-tempered and inclined to violence and atrocities multiplied under his administration. Following a failed attack against Addis Ababa by rebels on 28 July 1936, he had the archbishop of Dessie, whom he suspected of being behind the attack shot the same afternoon. All resisting Ethiopians were declared \"bandits\" and he ordered that they be shot on capture. Mussolini approved the decision but requested that the order be kept secret. Following the defeat of rebels led by Ras Desta in the western part of the country in late December 1936, he had 1600 rebel troops who surrendered summarily executed by firing squads. Villages that had been friendly to Desta were burned to the ground and women and children shot. Desta and other captured rebel leaders were executed in February 1937. The Italians undertook many other terrorist actions during this period. Following a bloody attempt on the life of Graziani and other Italian officials by two Eritreans during a ceremony to celebrate the birth of the [[Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples|Prince of Naples]] on 19 February 1937, the police and soldiers, fearing a general uprising, fired indiscriminately into the crowd. Innocent bystanders were shot. For the next three days, the Italians, led by the [[Blackshirts]], went on a rampage of murder and destruction throughout Addis Ababa. By the end of 1937 more than 5000 people had been executed for alleged crimes related to the attempt against Graziani. Among them were virtually all the young educated Ethiopians the Italians could lay their hands on and all the officiers and cadets of the Holeta Military Academy. The Italian viceroy had hermits, soothsayers and travelling minstrels rounded up and executed. Convinced that the high clergy had known about the plot, he had many executed. In May 1937, he ordered 297 monks of the monastery of [[Debre Libanos]] and 23 other individuals suspected of complicity shot. Over 100 deacons and students were also executed. Several hundred monks were sent to concentration camps. Viceroy Graziani was finally replaced in November 1938 by the more humane [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta|Duke of Aosta]], who put an end to wanton atrocities which had had the effect of increasing resistance to Italian domination.<ref>Paul B. Henze, ''Layers of Time. A History of Ethiopia'', Palgrave, New York, 2000, p. 225\u2013227.</ref>\n\nWhile some countries recognized the Italian conquest, Great Britain, France and the League of Nations refused to formally recognize it and consequently it remained illegitimate in international law.<ref>For that reason, following the collapse of Italian power in 1941, Haile Selassie reassumed power without the need of any formal recognition by the international community.</ref>\n\nThe King of Italy ([[Victor Emmanuel III]]) was crowned [[Emperor of Ethiopia]] and the Italians created an [[Italian empire]] in Africa ([[Italian East Africa]]) with Ethiopia, Eritrea and Italian Somalia. In 1937 Mussolini boasted that, with his conquest of Ethiopia, \"finally [[Battle of Adwa|Adua]] was avenged\".\n\n{{Quote|We will never be the masters if we are not conscious of our preordained superiority. We do not fraternize with the Negroes. We can not, we must not. At least not until they have been civilized.|Well-known Italian reporter [[Indro Montanelli]]}}\n\n[[File:RAS Abissini Pd-italy-005.jpg|thumb|left|Ras Sejum Mangasci\u00e0, Ras Ghetacci\u00f9 Abat\u00e9 and Ras Kebbed\u00e9 Guebret offered support to [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]] in February 1937.]]\nSome Ethiopians welcomed the Italians and collaborated with them in the government of the newly created ''Impero italiano'', like Ras [[Seyoum Mengesha|Sejum Mangasci\u00e0]], Ras Ghetacci\u00f9 Abat\u00e9 and Ras Kebbed\u00e9 Guebret. In 1937 the friendship of Sejum Mangascia with the Italian Viceroy [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]] enabled this Ras to play an influential role in securing the release of 3,000 Ethiopian POWs being held in [[Italian Somaliland]].\n\nThe Italians invested substantively in Ethiopian infrastructure development. They created the \"imperial road\" between Addis Ababa and [[Massaua]], the Addis Ababa - [[Mogadishu]] and the Addis Ababa - [[Assab]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.tecnici.it/file/novecento/autocamionale_assab_addis-abeba.pdf |accessdate=28 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329080126/http://media.tecnici.it/file/novecento/autocamionale_assab_addis-abeba.pdf |archivedate=29 March 2016 |date=1940 |title=Article on the special road Addis Abeba-Assab and map (in Italian)}}</ref> the Italians built more than 4,500&nbsp;km of roads linking the country beyond\n900&nbsp;km of railways were reconstructed or initiated (like the railway between Addis Ababa and [[Assab]]), dams and hydroelectric plants were built, and many public and private companies were established in the underdeveloped country. The most important were: \"Compagnie per il cotone d'Etiopia\" (Cotton industry); \"Cementerie d'Etiopia\" (Cement industry); \"Compagnia etiopica mineraria\" (Minerals industry); \"Imprese elettriche d'Etiopia\" (Electricity industry); \"Compagnia etiopica degli esplosivi\" (Armament industry); \"Trasporti automobilistici (Citao)\" (Mechanic & Transport industry).  \n \nItalians even created new airports and in 1936 started the worldwide famous [[Imperial Line|''Linea dell'Impero'']], a flight connecting Addis Ababa to [[Rome]]. The line was opened after the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War|Italian conquest of Ethiopia]] and was followed by the first air links with the Italian colonies in [[Italian East Africa]], which began in a pioneering way since 1934. The route was enlarged to 6,379&nbsp;km and initially joined [[Rome]] with [[Addis Ababa]] via [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Benghazi]], [[Cairo]], [[Wadi Halfa]], [[Khartoum]], [[Kassala]], [[Asmara]], [[Dire Dawa]].<ref>[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/africa_res-2a855323-8b74-11dc-8e9d-0016357eee51_%28Enciclopedia-Italiana%29/ Treccani: Via dell'Impero (in Italian)]</ref> There was a change of aircraft in [[Benghazi]] (or sometimes in [[Tripoli-Castel Benito Airport|Tripoli]]). The route was carried out in three and a half days of daytime flight and the frequency was four flights per week in both directions. Later from Addis Ababa there were three flights a week that continued to [[Mogadishu]], capital of [[Italian Somalia]].\n \nThe most important railway line in the African colonies of the Kingdom of Italy, the 784&nbsp;km long [[Ethio-Djibouti Railways|Franco-Ethiopian Railway]], was [[:File:Dire Dawa Station Blackshirts 1936.jpg|seized following the conquest of Ethiopia in 1936]]. The route was served until 1935 by steam trains that took about 36 hours to do the total trip between the capital of Ethiopia and the port of [[Djibouti]]. Following the Italian conquest was obtained in 1938 the increase of speed for the trains with the introduction of four railcars high capacity \"type 038\" derived from the model ''Fiat ALn56''.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/autorails_fiat_cfe/pages/image/imagepage15.html Fiat ALn56 \"Littorina\"]</ref>\n \nThese diesel trains were able to reach 70&nbsp;km/h and cutting time travel in half to just 18 hours: they were used until the mid 1960s.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/autorails_fiat_cfe/pages/image/imagepage30.html Image of a Fiat ALn56 in 1964 Addis Ababa station]</ref> At the main stations there were some bus connections to the other cities of Italian Ethiopia not served by the railway.<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/gare_diredawa_cfe/pages/image/imagepage15.html Dire Dawa bus connection to Harrar]</ref> Additionally, near the Addis Ababa station was created a special unit against fire, that was the only one in all Africa.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.storiavvf.it/Articolo%20Addis%20Abeba.htm |title=\"Pompieri ad Addis Abeba\" (in Italian) |access-date=2015-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104191728/http://www.storiavvf.it/Articolo%20Addis%20Abeba.htm |archive-date=2016-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n \n{{Quote|In 1936, during the occupation of Ethiopia, the Italians considered the construction of new railway routes from Addis-Ababa running as follows: Addis-Ababa, Dessie, Adigrat, Massawa: covering 1000 km; Addis-Ababa, Dessie, Assab - Dessie, Gondar, Om, Ager; Addis-Ababa, Megheli, Dollo, Mogadishu. All these projects had to be abandoned due to war operations.|Jean Pierre Crozet}}\n \nProjects of connecting to the Eritrean railway network did not found practical realization in 1939. In the same year was studied the possibility of connecting the Ethiopian station of [[Dire-Dawa]] to the port of [[Assab]] in southern Eritrea, in order to bypass the [[French Somaliland]]. Until 1938 there was a protective military unit in the trains, because of the Ethiopian guerrilla in the area (that by the beginning of World War II faded away).<ref>[http://www.train-franco-ethiopien.com/photos_cfe/divers_cfe/pages/image/imagepage34.html Photo of Italian soldiers defending the ethiopian railway trains]</ref>\n[[File:Italian communications in Ethiopia, April 1941.jpg|thumb|right|Map showing in red the new roads (like the \"Imperial road\", and those in construction in 1941) created by the Italians in Ethiopia]]\n\nThe Italians not only made new roads & other structural improvements, but they also greatly improved the socio-economical conditions of the native population, as the same emperor Haile Selassie recognized when back in power after 1941. {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} \n\nIndeed, much of these improvements were part of a plan to bring half a million Italians to colonize the Ethiopian plateaus. In October 1939 the [[Italians of Ethiopia|Italian colonists in Ethiopia]] were 35,441, of whom 30,232 male (85.3%) and 5,209 female (14.7%), most of them living in urban areas.<ref>[http://www.ilcornodafrica.it/rds-01emigrazione.pdf Italian emigration in Etiopia (in Italian)]</ref> Only 3,200 Italian farmers moved to colonize farm areas, mostly around the capital and in the [[Scioa Governorate]], where they were under sporadic attack by pro-Haile Selassie guerrillas until 1939.\n \nHowever, the [[Shifta|Ethiopian guerrillas]] - that in late 1939 were still controlling nearly a quarter of the Ethiopian highlands (but had never been active in the areas of Ethiopia united to Eritrea and Somalia in 1936 {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} )- were present at the beginning of World War II only in the Harar and Galla-Sidamo Governorate. According to the viceroy [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]] the guerrillas were going to disappear in another two years (as had happened in [[Italian Cyrenaica|Cyrenaica]] in the early 1930s). Indeed, [[Abebe Aregai]], the last leader of the \"Arbegnocks\" (as the guerrilla fighters were called in Ethiopia) after the 1939 surrender of Ethiopian leaders Zaudi\u00e8 Asfau and Olon\u00e0 Dinkel, made a surrender proposal to the Italians in spring 1940<ref>Bahru Zewde, \"A History of Modern Ethiopia\", second edition (Oxford: James Currey, 2001), pp. 172f</ref>. \n \nIn early 1940, also as a consequence of the guerrilla nearly disappearance, Italian Ethiopia was enjoying a small \"boom\" of economic & social development with the commerce and industrial sector greatly improving in the capital and in the main cities. {{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{Quote|A remarkable effort was made to improve healthcare in Ethiopia: beside the doctors belonging to the Italian Africa Health Corps, flanked by 450 military doctors, there were about 500 civilian doctors (232 specialists, among whom 30 pediatricians, and 262 general practitioners). Special maternity wards were built in the hospitals situated in the main locations. The new Italian hospital in Addis Ababa had a delivery room and a pediatric clinic, with a capacity of over 100 beds in its various sections: expectant mothers, postpartum mothers, babies\u2019 room, gynecological ward, infectious diseases, visitors\u2019 room, etc. The children\u2019s hospital was subdivided into separate wards for babies and older children, for infectious, gastro-intestinal or pulmonary diseases, etc. Moreover, a university-type faculty was founded in 1941 in Asmara to train nurses....Social life in Addis Ababa (and Asmara) was pulsating just like that of any other European town. At the heart of the city were the markets: in the capital (Addis Ababa) in 1939 over 75,000 heads of cattle had been slaughtered and thousands of tons of foodstuffs had been sold. Dozens of shops and even department stores were opened in both cities. Leisure activities also boomed: in Addis Ababa four cinemas had been built...New dancehalls, restaurants and bars were being opened everywhere. The working men\u2019s clubs and numerous sports and recreational societies, supported by local government and by the PNF, organised the colonists\u2019 (and native Etiopians) free time.|G. Podesta<ref>[https://www.cairn.info/revue-annales-de-demographie-historique-2011-2-page-205.htm Podesta: \"Family and Society in Italian Africa\"]</ref>}}\n\nDuring the five years of Italian occupation, [[Catholicism]] also grew in importance, thanks mainly to the efforts of missionaries like [[Elisa Angela Meneguzzi]]. She became known as the \"Ecumenical Fire\" due to her strong efforts at [[ecumenism]] with [[Coptic Christians]] and [[Islam|Muslims]] while also catering to relations with the Catholics of [[Dire Dawa]].<ref>[http://catholicsaints.info/blessed-liduina-meneguzzi/  Blessed Elisa Angela Meneguzzi]</ref>)\n\n[[File:Stairs of the Lion of Judea in Addis Ababa.jpg|thumb|Mussolini's ''Stairway to Nowhere'', monument at the Addis Abeba University  with a stair for every year of Mussolini's rule since 1922]]\n\n===World War II===\nDuring [[World War II]], in the summer of 1940 Italian armed forces [[Italian conquest of British Somaliland|successfully invaded all of British Somaliland]].<ref>Dickson (2001) p.103</ref> But, by spring of 1941, the British had counter-attacked and pushed deep into [[Italian East Africa]]. By 5 May, [[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia]] had returned to [[Addis Ababa]] to reclaim his throne. In November, the last organised Italian resistance in Ethiopia ended with the fall of [[Battle of Gondar|Gondar]].<ref>Jowett (2001) p.7</ref> However, following the surrender of East Africa, some Italians [[Italian guerrilla war in Ethiopia|conducted a guerrilla war]] which lasted for two more years.\n\nThis guerrilla was done primarily by military units with Italian officers (like Captain Paolo Aloisi, Captain Leopoldo Rizzo, Blackshirt officer De Varda and Major Lucchetti) but also by civilians like [[Rosa Dainelli]]. She was a doctor who in August 1942 succeeded in entering the main ammunition depot of the British army in [[Addis Ababa]], and blowing it up, miraculously survived the huge explosion. Her sabotage destroyed the ammunition for the new British [[Sten submachine gun|Sten]] sub machine gun, delaying the use of this \"state of the art\" armament for many months.<ref>Rosselli, Alberto. ''Storie Segrete. Operazioni sconosciute o dimenticate della seconda guerra mondiale''. pag. 103</ref> Her true name was Danielli Rosa and the date of attack was September 15, 1941.<ref>Di Lalla, Fabrizio, \u201cSotto due bandiere. Lotta di liberazione etiopica e resistenza italiana in Africa Orientale\u201d. p. 235</ref>\n\n===After World War II===\n[[File:Ethiopian electric power corporation Addis Abeba.jpg|thumb|Italian-era electric power corporation building in Addis Ababa]]\nThe recognition by the United Kingdom of the full sovereignty of Ethiopia occurred with the signing on 19 December 1944 of the Anglo-Ethiopian agreement which acknowledged Ethiopia to be \"a free and independent state\"<ref>Henze, p. 235.</ref> although various regions remained under British occupation for some years.<ref name=\"Clapham\"/>\n\nIn the [[Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947|peace treaty of February 1947]], Italy renounced sovereignty over its African colonies of Libya, Eritrea and Somalia (art. 23) and recognised the independence of Ethiopia (art. 33), by then a sovereign member of the United Nations. \n\nItaly further agreed to:\n* Pay [[War reparation]] of US$25,000,000 to Ethiopia\n* Accept \"Annex XI of the Treaty\", upon the recommendation of the United Nations General Assembly in Resolution 390, that indicated that [[Eritrea]] was to be federated with Ethiopia.\n\nAfter the war, the [[Italian Ethiopians]] were given a full pardon by the newly returned Emperor Haile Selassie, as he saw the opportunity to continue the modernization efforts of the country.<ref name=\"Italoethiopians\">[https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/ Photos and articles of Italoethiopians who took refuge in Italy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211022551/https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/ |date=2017-02-11 }}</ref> He declared that no reprisals would be taken against the Italians, and many remained for decades, until the overthrow of the Emperor in the [[Ethiopian Civil War]] in 1974. Nearly 22,000 Italo-Ethiopians took refuge in Italy during the 1970s.<ref name=\"Italoethiopians\"/> Their main organization in Italy is the Associazione Italiana Profughi dall'Etiopia ed Eritrea (A.I.P.E.E.).<ref>[http://www.aipee.it/home.html Associazione Italiana Profughi dall'Etiopia ed Eritrea (AIPEE)]</ref>\n\nIn recent years, some Italian companies have returned to operate in Ethiopia, and a large number of Italian technicians and managers arrived with their families, residing mainly in the metropolitan area of the capital.<ref>https://dait.interno.gov.it/servizi-demografici</ref>\n\n==Contemporary relations==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right|direction=vertical|width=190\n|image1=2 giugno 2002-Axum.JPG\n|caption1=The [[Obelisk of Axum]] in [[Rome]] before its repatriation\n|image2=G7 Taormina Paolo Gentiloni Hailemariam Desalegn handshake 2017-05-27.jpg\n|caption2=[[Paolo Gentiloni]] and [[Hailemariam Desalegn]] at the [[43rd G7 summit]]\n}}\n\nIn the mid-1990s despite a previous arrangement with the Dergue regime under [[Mengistu Haile Mariam|Menghistu]] in the 1970s to cede the [[Obelisk of Axum]] to Italy in exchange for medical facilities and forgiving an accumulated debt to the Italian government, a populist movement made up of Italians and Ethiopians (both in country and expatriates around the world) began to petition the then current Italian government to return the obelisk,<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-03-10/news/0203100403_1_obelisk-ethiopian-people-ethiopian-embassy Chicago Tribune,March 10, 2002 \"Ethiopia Again Demands Italy Return Obelisk\"]</ref> an event which eventually culminated in its [[Obelisk of Axum#Repatriation|repatriation]] in 2008 to Axum, the city of its creation.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/apr/20/italy.ethiopian The Guardian, 20 April, 2005 \"Obelisk returned to Ethiopia after 68 years\"]</ref>\n\nThe Italian firm [[Salini Impregilo|Salini Costruttori]] was chosen by the Ethiopian government to design and build the Millennium or [[Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam#Construction|Renaissance Dam]] on the [[Blue Nile|Blue Nile river]], which when completed will be the largest dam and hydroelectric plant in Africa.<ref>[http://www.salini-impregilo.com/en/projects/in-progress/dams-hydroelectric-plants-hydraulic-works/grand-ethiopian-renaissance-dam-project.html Grand Renaissance Dam Project in Ethiopia]</ref> As the Italian engineers had helped to build the first railway from Addis to Djibouti in the past, the Ethiopian government has contracted them again to expand the railroad network along with India and China.<ref>[http://www.globalconreview.com/markets/ethiopia-steams-ahead-vision-modern-n8a8t8i8o8n8al/ Global Construction View - \"Ethiopia Steams Ahead\"]</ref> For the last 20 years, Italy has continued to be among the top 5 trading partners with Ethiopia and a major investor in the Ethiopian economy.<ref>[http://atlas.media.mit.edu/profile/country/eth/ MIT Country Profile - Ethiopia: Trading Partners]</ref>\n\nEthiopian languages such as Amharic and Tigrinya have many words borrowed from the Italian language, for example \"gettone\" (token), \"bigli\" from Italian \"biglie\" (glass marbles), \"borsa\" (bag), \"mach\u00ecna\" from Italian \"macchina\" (car), \"carburatore\" (carburetor) and others.<ref name=\"Yaqob\">{{cite web|url=https://totalitarismo.altervista.org/italianismi-nel-somalo-e-nell-amarico/|title=Italianismi nel somalo e nell\u2019amarico|first=Mister|last=Totalitarismo|date=2 December 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"altervista\">''I prestiti italiani in amarico e tigrino'', Yaqob Beyene</ref> Ethiopia has the largest concentration of Italian schools and cultural institutes in Africa (such as the [[Istituto Statale Italiano Omnicomprensivo di Addis Abeba|Scuola Statale Italiana]] of Addis Ababa), which foster and promote Italian and Ethiopian culture and are free to the public.<ref>[http://www.iicaddisabeba.esteri.it/IIC_AddisAbeba/Menu/Istituto/Come_raggiungerci/ Italian Cultural Institute of Addis Ababa]</ref>\n\n==Banknotes and postage stamps==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; border-bottom:2px solid gray;\" bgcolor=\"lightsteelblue\"\n! Frontal Image\n! Back Image\n! Amount\n! Color\n! Frontal Description\n! Back Description\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP1b-50Lire-1939 f-donated.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP1b-50Lire-1939 b-donated.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |'''50 Lire'''\n| align=\"left\" |Green\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CINQVANTA - BANCA D'ITALIA</small>\n| align=\"left\" |<small>50 LIRE - Lupa romana</small>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP2b-100Lire-1938-donatedms f.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |[[File:ItalianEastAfricaP2b-100Lire-1938-donatedms b.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"left\" |'''100 Lire'''\n| align=\"left\" |Green/gray\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CENTO - BANCA D'ITALIA - Dea Roma</small>\n| align=\"left\" |<small>LIRE CENTO - BANCA D'ITALIA - Aquila</small>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\nOn 5 May 1936 the capital Addis Ababa was captured by the Italians: on 22 May three new stamps showing the King of Italy were issued. Four further values inscribed \"ETIOPIA\" were issued on 5 December 1936. After that date, the stamps were issued with the name \"Africa Orientale Italiana\" on it.<ref>[http://www.italianstamps.co.uk/colonies/ethiopia/index.html Postage stamps of Italian Ethiopia]</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=September 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{C|Italian East Africa|Italian East Africa topics}}\n* [[Italians of Ethiopia]]\n* [[Italian Eritrea]]\n* [[Italian Somalia]]\n* [[Imperial Line|Linea dell'Impero]]\n* [[Prince Amedeo, Duke of Aosta]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://razzismocolonialevenezia.wordpress.com/2017/01/08/nasce-limpero-letiopia-italiana/|title=Nasce l\u2019Impero: l\u2019Etiopia italiana|last=Conte|first=Alessio|date=2017-01-08|website=Ascari e Schiavoni|language=it-IT|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Italy)]] |location=[[Rome]], Italy |url=http://www.esteri.it/mae/ministero/servizi/archiviostorico/2013/2asmai_vol.i_eritrea_etiopia_somalia.pdf |language=it |title={{lang-it|Inventario dell'Archivio Storico del Ministero Africa Italiana|translit=Index of the historical archive of the ministry of Italian Africa|link=no|nocat=true}} |volume=1: (1857-1939) |year= 1975 |access-date=2017-12-20}}\n* {{cite book |last=Bandini |first=Franco |title=Gli italiani in Africa: Storia delle guerre coloniali 1882-1943 |publisher=[[Longanesi]] |language=it |location=[[Milan]], Italy |date=1971 |oclc=1253348}}\n* {{cite book |last=Beltrami |first=Vanni |title=Italia d'Oltremare: Storie dei territori italiani dalla conquista alla caduta |language=it |publisher=Edizioni Nuova Cultura |location=[[Rome]] Italy |date=2013 |isbn=978-88-6134-702-1 |page=273 |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=TE2ldbz57eIC&lpg=PR1&hl=it&pg=PA273#v=onepage&q&f=false |access-date=2017-12-20}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Keith |title=World War II for Dummies |publisher=Wiley |location=[[Hoboken, New Jersey]], US |date=2001 |isbn=9780764553523 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/worldwariifordum00dick }}\n* {{cite book |last=Jowett |first=Philip S |title=The Italian Army 1940\u201345 2: Africa 1940\u201343  |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=[[Oxford]], UK |date=2001 |isbn=9781855328655}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Sbiacchi |first=Alberto |title=Hail\u00e9 Selassi\u00e9 and the Italians, 1941-43 |work=[[African Studies Review]] |volume=XXII |issue=1 |date=April 1979 |publisher=[[African Studies Association]]}}\n\n{{Italian Ethiopia}}\n{{Italian colonial empire}}\n{{WWII_history_by_nation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Italian East Africa|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Former Italian colonies|Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:History of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1930s in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1940s in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1930s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1940s in Italy]]\n[[Category:Ethiopia\u2013Italy relations]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1936]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1947]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_Ethiopia"}
{"title_page": "Beta Chi Theta", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox fraternity\n|letters=\u0392\u03a7\u0398\n\n| crest = Beta Chi Theta crest.png\n|image_size = 200px\n|colors= {{color box|#000000|Black|#FFFFFF}}  {{color box|#BCC6CC|Silver|#FFFFFF}}  {{color box|#FFFFFF|White|#000000}}\n|motto=\"Above All Else, Brotherhood\"\n|symbol= Rampant Lion\n|founded={{start date and years ago|1999|6|2}}\n|birthplace=[[UCLA]]\n|type=[[Fraternities and sororities|Social]]\n|scope=National\n|chapters=20 chapters, 8 [[Colony (fraternity)|Colonies]]\n|members=1700+\n|homepage= [http://www.betachitheta.com/ betachitheta.com]\n}}\n'''Beta Chi Theta''' ('''\u0392\u03a7\u0398''', also '''Beta Chi''') is a nationally recognized South Asian interest [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternity]] in the United States, established in 1999 at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA).  On June 2, 1999, Beta Chi Theta was acknowledged by the university and granted membership into the UCLA Inter-Fraternity Council (IFC). Beta Chi Theta was founded by eight young men and today has chapters and colonies located all over the United States. It is the largest South Asian Fraternity in the USA.\n\nThe founding principles which support and give purpose to Beta Chi Theta are creating and maintaining a strong, close-knit brotherhood; honoring tradition; pursuing service to humanity; increasing cultural awareness; promoting academic excellence; and building a unified nationwide network.\n\nMembership in Beta Chi Theta has become diverse, with brothers from all backgrounds, races, cultures, religions, and sexual orientations.\n\n==National Founding Fathers==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;\" width=\"400\"\n|+'''\u0392\u03a7\u0398 Founding Fathers'''\n|-\n| | Brother Abu Mathew Abraham\n| | Brother Hashu Datwani\n|-\n| | Brother Samir Khandhar\n| | Brother Ankur Kumar\n|-\n| | Brother Ashish Nagdev\n| | Brother Ankur Parikh\n|-\n| | Brother Roshan Patel\n| | Brother Ali Zhumkhawala\n|-\n|}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nBeta Chi Theta seeks to promote service to humanity through engagement within the local communities of its respective chapters and colonies. Service to humanity is one of the six pillars that defines the foundation of the organization. Brothers across the country participate in service both directly and indirectly through organizational activities. The fraternity encourages members to give back to the community in which they are fostered, help those in need, and mentor those who look up to them.\n\nNationally, regionally, and locally, Beta Chi Theta works with many non-profit organizations to support numerous causes that bind them together as a brotherhood. They believe that through outreach they can impact the lives of many around them and simultaneously become closer to one another.\n\nThe fraternity has two national philanthropy initiatives: Beating Heart Disease and Be the Change.\n\n; Beating Heart Disease\n\nIn 2009, it was voted that the fraternity's national philanthropy would be cardiac health awareness and research fundraising since it is the number one cause of death in not only the US, but the world, and it is also especially rampant amongst the South Asian population. Since then, they have partnered with American Heart Association to teach communities across the country on how to live a heart-healthy lifestyle and also to raise money for cardiac research and education. The Beating Heart Disease program is a string of week-long events thrown in the spring of every year by chapters and colonies in an effort to educate young students on cardiac health and also to raise money for American Heart Association. An additional aspect of this partnership involves the participation of brothers in Heart Walks, which are hosted annually across the nation by the American Heart Association.\n\n; Be The Change\n\nIn addition, the brothers of Beta Chi Theta have partnered annually with SAALT (South Asian Americans Leading Together) to host Be The Change Days of Service on university campuses across the nation. Be The Change is an annual occurrence in the fall of each year that pays tribute to the life of Mahatma Gandhi. Gandhi once said to \"be the change you wish to see in the world.\" This partnership with SAALT allows the members of the fraternity to recruit people for volunteer work in their circles and positively influence their communities.\n\n==Motto==\n\"Above all else,  Brotherhood\"\n\n== North American Interfraternity Conference ==\nOn April 23, 2006, Beta Chi Theta became the first nationally recognized South Asian-based fraternity through its acceptance of membership into the [[North American Interfraternity Conference]] (NIC). At seven years of age, it was the youngest fraternity ever to become a member of the NIC in its 100-year history.\n\n==Chapters==\n\n===Chapters===\n*'''Alpha chapter''' - [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n*'''Beta chapter''' - [[Baylor University]]\n*'''Gamma chapter''' - [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]]\n*'''Delta chapter''' - [[University of Oklahoma]]\n*'''Epsilon chapter''' - [[University of California, Riverside]]\n*'''\u0396eta chapter''' - [[University of California, San Diego]]\n*'''Eta chapter ''' - [[The University of Texas at Austin]]\n*'''Theta chapter''' - [[Vanderbilt University]]\n*'''Iota chapter''' - [[Purdue University]]\n*'''Lambda chapter''' - [[University of Minnesota]]\n*'''Mu chapter''' - [[University of Florida]]\n*'''Pi chapter''' - [[Texas A&M University]]\n*'''Rho chapter''' - [[The University of Tennessee, Knoxville]]\n*'''Sigma chapter''' - [[Rutgers University]]\n*'''Upsilon chapter''' - [[University of Texas at Dallas]]\n*'''Phi chapter''' - [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n*'''Omega chapter''' - [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]]\n*'''Alpha Alpha chapter''' - [[Northeastern University]]\n*'''Alpha Gamma chapter''' - [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]\n*'''Alpha Delta chapter''' - [[Indiana University Bloomington]]\n\n===Colonies===\n*'''\u039aappa Colony''' - [[Florida Atlantic University]]\n*'''\u039du Colony''' - [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n*'''Xi Colony''' - [[University of Houston]]\n*'''Omicron Colony''' - [[Emory University]]\n*'''Tau Colony''' - [[University of South Florida]]\n*'''Psi Colony''' - [[University of Connecticut]]\n*'''Alpha Beta Colony''' - [[Drexel University]]\n*'''Alpha Epsilon Colony''' - [[University of Georgia]]\n*'''Alpha Zeta Colony''' - [[Arizona State University]]\n*'''Alpha Eta Colony''' - [[Binghamton University]]\n\n===Chi chapter===\n*'''Chi chapter''' - This chapter is reserved for those brothers who have deceased.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of social fraternities and sororities]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.betachitheta.com/ Beta Chi Theta national site]\n\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n{{North American Interfraternity Conference}}\n{{National APIDA Panhellenic Association}}\n{{South-Asian Fraternities & Sororities}}\n\n[[Category:Asian-American culture in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:North American Interfraternity Conference]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Asian-American fraternities and sororities]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox fraternity\n|letters=\u0392\u03a7\u0398\n\n| crest = Beta Chi Theta crest.png\n|image_size = 200px\n|colors= {{color box|#000000|Black|#FFFFFF}}  {{color box|#BCC6CC|Silver|#FFFFFF}}  {{color box|#FFFFFF|White|#000000}}\n|motto=\"Above All Else, Brotherhood\"\n|symbol= Rampant Lion\n|founded={{start date and years ago|1999|6|2}}\n|birthplace=[[UCLA]]\n|type=[[Fraternities and sororities|Social]]\n|scope=National\n|chapters=20 chapters, 8 [[Colony (fraternity)|Colonies]]\n|members=1700+\n|homepage= [http://www.betachitheta.com/ betachitheta.com]\n}}\n'''Beta Chi Theta''' ('''\u0392\u03a7\u0398''', also '''Beta Chi''') is a nationally recognized South Asian interest [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternity]] in the United States, established in 1999 at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA).  On June 2, 1999, Beta Chi Theta was acknowledged by the university and granted membership into the UCLA Inter-Fraternity Council (IFC). Beta Chi Theta was founded by eight young men and today has chapters and colonies located all over the United States. It is the largest South Asian Fraternity in the USA. \n\nThe founding principles which support and give purpose to Beta Chi Theta are creating and maintaining a strong, close-knit brotherhood; honoring tradition; pursuing service to humanity; increasing cultural awareness; promoting academic excellence; and building a unified nationwide network.\n\nMembership in Beta Chi Theta has become diverse, with brothers from all backgrounds, races, cultures, religions, and sexual orientations.\n\n==National Founding Fathers==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;\" width=\"400\"\n|+'''\u0392\u03a7\u0398 Founding Fathers'''\n|-\n| | Brother Abu Mathew Abraham\n| | Brother Hashu Datwani\n|-\n| | Brother Samir Khandhar\n| | Brother Ankur Kumar\n|-\n| | Brother Ashish Nagdev\n| | Brother Ankur Parikh\n|-\n| | Brother Roshan Patel\n| | Brother Ali Zhumkhawala\n|-\n|}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nBeta Chi Theta seeks to promote service to humanity through engagement within the local communities of its respective chapters and colonies. Service to humanity is one of the six pillars that defines the foundation of the organization. Brothers across the country participate in service both directly and indirectly through organizational activities. The fraternity encourages members to give back to the community in which they are fostered, help those in need, and mentor those who look up to them.\n\nNationally, regionally, and locally, Beta Chi Theta works with many non-profit organizations to support numerous causes that bind them together as a brotherhood. They believe that through outreach they can impact the lives of many around them and simultaneously become closer to one another.\n\nThe fraternity has two national philanthropy initiatives: Beating Heart Disease and Be the Change.\n\n; Beating Heart Disease\n\nIn 2009, it was voted that the fraternity's national philanthropy would be cardiac health awareness and research fundraising since it is the number one cause of death in not only the US, but the world, and it is also especially rampant amongst the South Asian population. Since then, they have partnered with American Heart Association to teach communities across the country on how to live a heart-healthy lifestyle and also to raise money for cardiac research and education. The Beating Heart Disease program is a string of week-long events thrown in the spring of every year by chapters and colonies in an effort to educate young students on cardiac health and also to raise money for American Heart Association. An additional aspect of this partnership involves the participation of brothers in Heart Walks, which are hosted annually across the nation by the American Heart Association.\n\n; Be The Change\n\nIn addition, the brothers of Beta Chi Theta have partnered annually with SAALT (South Asian Americans Leading Together) to host Be The Change Days of Service on university campuses across the nation. Be The Change is an annual occurrence in the fall of each year that pays tribute to the life of Mahatma Gandhi. Gandhi once said to \"be the change you wish to see in the world.\" This partnership with SAALT allows the members of the fraternity to recruit people for volunteer work in their circles and positively influence their communities.\n\n==Motto==\n\"Above all else,  Brotherhood\"\n\n== North-American Interfraternity Conference ==\nOn April 23, 2006, Beta Chi Theta became the first nationally recognized South Asian-based fraternity through its acceptance of membership into the [[North-American Interfraternity Conference]] (NIC). At seven years of age, it was the youngest fraternity ever to become a member of the NIC in its 100-year history.\n\n==Chapters==\n\n===Chapters===\n*'''Alpha chapter''' - [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n*'''Beta chapter''' - [[Baylor University]]\n*'''Gamma chapter''' - [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]]\n*'''Delta chapter''' - [[University of Oklahoma]]\n*'''Epsilon chapter''' - [[University of California, Riverside]]\n*'''\u0396eta chapter''' - [[University of California, San Diego]]\n*'''Eta chapter ''' - [[The University of Texas at Austin]]\n*'''Theta chapter''' - [[Vanderbilt University]]\n*'''Iota chapter''' - [[Purdue University]]\n*'''Lambda chapter''' - [[University of Minnesota]]\n*'''Mu chapter''' - [[University of Florida]]\n*'''Pi chapter''' - [[Texas A&M University]]\n*'''Rho chapter''' - [[The University of Tennessee, Knoxville]]\n*'''Sigma chapter''' - [[Rutgers University]]\n*'''Upsilon chapter''' - [[University of Texas at Dallas]]\n*'''Phi chapter''' - [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n*'''Omega chapter''' - [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]]\n*'''Alpha Alpha chapter''' - [[Northeastern University]]\n*'''Alpha Gamma chapter''' - [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]\n*'''Alpha Delta chapter''' - [[Indiana University Bloomington]]\n\n===Colonies===\n*'''\u039aappa Colony''' - [[Florida Atlantic University]]\n*'''\u039du Colony''' - [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n*'''Xi Colony''' - [[University of Houston]]\n*'''Omicron Colony''' - [[Emory University]]\n*'''Tau Colony''' - [[University of South Florida]]\n*'''Psi Colony''' - [[University of Connecticut]]\n*'''Alpha Beta Colony''' - [[Drexel University]]\n*'''Alpha Epsilon Colony''' - [[University of Georgia]]\n*'''Alpha Zeta Colony''' - [[Arizona State University]]\n*'''Alpha Eta Colony''' - [[Binghamton University]]\n\n===Chi chapter===\n*'''Chi chapter''' - This chapter is reserved for those brothers who have deceased.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of social fraternities and sororities]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.betachitheta.com/ Beta Chi Theta national site]\n\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n{{North-American Interfraternity Conference}}\n{{National APIDA Panhellenic Association}}\n{{South-Asian Fraternities & Sororities}}\n\n[[Category:Asian-American culture in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1999]]\n[[Category:North-American Interfraternity Conference]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Asian-American fraternities and sororities]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "using AWB cleanup,, replaced: North-American Interfraternity Conference \u2192 North American Interfraternity Conference (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_Chi_Theta"}
{"title_page": "It's My Party (Lesley Gore song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1963 single by Lesley Gore}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = It's My Party\n| cover      = It's My Party single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original US single cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lesley Gore]]\n| album      = [[I'll Cry If I Want To]]\n| B-side     = Danny\n| released   = April 1963\n| format     = 7\" vinyl\n| recorded   = March 30, 1963\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[blue-eyed soul]]}}\n| length     = 2:19\n| label      = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Wally Gold|Walter Gold]]|John Gluck Jr.|Herb Weiner|Seymour Gottlieb}}\n| producer   = [[Quincy Jones]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Judy's Turn to Cry]]\n| next_year  = 1963\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  =\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Lesley Gore - It's My Party.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = EP cover\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''It's My Party'''\" is a pop song recorded by multiple artists since the 1960s. In 1963, American singer [[Lesley Gore]]'s version hit number one on the [[Pop music|pop]] and [[rhythm and blues]] charts in the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=803}}</ref> It was the first hit single for producer [[Quincy Jones]].\n\n==Theme==\nThe song lyrically portrays the discomfort of a [[Adolescence|teenage]] girl at her birthday party when her boyfriend Johnny disappears, only to return in the company of Judy, another girl, who is \"wearing his ring,\" to indicate he has replaced the birthday girl as his love interest.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=It's My Party|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/its-my-party-t2601611|author=Ankeny, J.|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=July 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe song's chorus, \"It's my party, and I'll cry if I want to... You would cry too if it happened to you!\" became a part of American pop cultural language as a phrase used to describe being utterly humiliated and miserable during an event that is supposed to be a happy occasion.\n\n\"It's My Party\" is in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[A major]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Musicological identities: essays in honor of Susan McClary|author=McClary, S., Knapp, R., Baur, S. & Warwick, J.C.|page=71|year=2008|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6302-7}}</ref>  The song's effectiveness is enhanced by several musical touches producer Quincy Jones incorporated, including Latin-sounding [[rhythm]]s, [[doubletracking|double tracked]] vocals and effective horn parts.<ref name=allmusic/> [[Allmusic]] critic Jason Ankeny wrote of the song, {{\"'}}It's My Party' remains one of the most vivid evocations of adolescent heartbreak ever waxed\u2014Quincy Jones produced the record, although you'd swear it was [[Aaron Spelling]] instead.\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\n==Background==\n\"It's My Party\" was credited to John Gluck, Wally Gold and Herb Weiner, staff writers at the [[Aaron Schroeder]] Music firm in 1962.  The lyrics were actually written by Seymour Gottlieb, a freelance songwriter.  He gave the lyrics to Herb Weiner, with whom he partnered in writing songs, to peddle.  It was based on actual events relating to Gottlieb's daughter Judy's \u2018Sweet 16\u2019 party, before which she cried over the prospect of her grandparents being invited.<ref name =Gottlieb>{{cite news |last=Tumposky |first= Ellen|date=February 18, 2015 |title= Brooklyn Woman recall origins of Gore's 'It's My Party'|url=http://m.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/brooklyn-woman-recalls-origins-gore-party-article-1.2119662|newspaper=Daily News |location=New York |access-date= February 18, 2015}}</ref>  The demo for the song was cut by Barbara Jean English, a girl group veteran (the Clickettes, the Fashions), who was then working as a receptionist at the firm.  She also worked with [[Jimmy Radcliffe]], serving as the firm's in-house demo singer.  Radcliffe produced the demo, and, according to English, \"tried to persuade Musicor [the label owned by Aaron Schroeder] to release it as a record, or to take me into a master studio and redo it, but they weren't interested.\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\">{{cite web|url-status=dead|url=http://www.chachacharming.com/article.php?id=16&pg=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612170838/http://www.chachacharming.com/article.php?id=16|archivedate=June 12, 2007|title=It's My Party|publisher=Cha Cha Charming Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe first recording of the song was in 1962 by [[The Chiffons]] for their ''One Fine Day'' album.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} It was also recorded by [[Helen Shapiro]] for her ''Helen in Nashville'' album in February 1963 with Shapiro's regular producer, [[Norrie Paramor]], and also [[Al Kasha]].  Shapiro would recall: \"Right from the first time we heard the song on the rough demo back in London, we thought we were going to sock them between the eyes with that one\";<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/>\nhowever, Shapiro's version was not one of the cuts chosen as an advance single from the album and by the time of the album's release that October the \"It's My Party\" track was perceived as a cover of Lesley Gore's hit.\n\nLesley Gore recalls that \"It's My Party\" was among some two hundred demos producer [[Quincy Jones]] brought to review with her in the den of her family home in February 1963.  On hearing \"It's My Party,\" Gore told Jones: \"That's not half bad.  I like it.  Good melody.  Let's put it on the maybe pile.\"  The song proved to be the only demo Gore and Jones found agreeable.  With Jones producing and [[Claus Ogerman]] handling arranging and conducting duties, Gore recorded 'It's My Party' at Bell Sound Studios in [[Manhattan]] on March 30, 1963.<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/><ref name=no1>{{cite book|title=The Billboard book of number 1 hits|author=Bronson, F.|page=130|edition=5|year=2003|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-0-8230-7677-2}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1963 [[Phil Spector]] heard the demo of \"It's My Party\" while visiting Aaron Schroeder's office. Wally Gold would recall: \"He [Spector] said, 'Great, I love it. I\u2019m gonna do it with the Crystals.'  We [the song's writers] were really excited, because that would ensure that the record was #1!\"<ref name=\"bobshannon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bobshannon.com/stories/Party.html |title=Behind The Hits: Stories: It's My Party |accessdate=September 17, 2011 |author=Shannon, Bob |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206100809/http://www.bobshannon.com/stories/Party.html |archivedate=February 6, 2008 }}</ref> Schroeder apparently only learned of the Lesley Gore recording of \"It's My Party\" when Quincy Jones invited him to hear the completed track, which Schroeder found formulaic; believing that Spector would be able to cut a much stronger version of the song with the Crystals and not wanting to lose Spector's good will, Schroeder attempted to convince Jones to suppress the track.  Schroeder did not mention Spector's version to Jones but Jones and Spector both happened to attend a concert with [[Charles Aznavour]] at [[Carnegie Hall]] on the evening of March 30, 1963 and when they met outside it came up in conversation that Spector had recorded a version of \"It's My Party\" with the Crystals.{{#tag:ref|As with \"[[He's a Rebel]]\", the Crystals' hit for which it was intended as the follow-up, \"It's My Party\" was actually recorded not by the Crystals but [[the Blossoms]], who cut the track at [[Gold Star Studios]]. [[Darlene Love]] says the Spector version was \"kinda slow with me and my sister [[Honey Cone|Edna [Wright]]] singing together on lead.  Much more [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] than Lesley Gore's version.\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/>|group=note}} Jones skipped the concert, instead spending that night\u2014a Saturday\u2014at Bell Sound Studios making a test pressing of the track comprising one hundred copies. \n\nOver the next two days Jones mailed these out to radio programmers in key markets across the US.  Gore heard her record played on the radio for the first time that Friday; the official release of \"It's My Party\" came later in the month, with the disc ascending to number one nationally in four weeks.<ref name=\"chachacharming2\" /><ref name=\"bobshannon\" />  Jones was abroad at the time of \"It's My Party\"'s release.  On his return he expressed dismay when Aaron Schroeder advised him that the rush release of \"It's My Party\" had precluded coining a more pleasant name for the singer than \"Lesley Gore,\" to which Schroeder replied: \"Didn't anybody tell you?...Quince, the record's number one.  Do you really give a damn what her last name is?\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/> {{failed verification|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn 1980, [[WCBN-FM]], the [[University of Michigan]] freeform student radio station, played \"It's My Party\" for 18 hours straight the day after [[Ronald Reagan]] was elected.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wcbn.org/history/wcbntime.html | title=CBN History | accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1963)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1681&Itemid=52|title=Australian Weekly Singles Charts(David Kent) from 1963|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qartistid=383#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 4 July 1963]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|9|date=19630717|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19630608.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles, June 8, 1963 |access-date=March 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313044215/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19630608.html |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1963)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"Musicoutfitters.com\">[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1963.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1963YESP.html |title=Cash Box Year-End Charts: Top 100 Pop Singles, December 28, 1963 |access-date=March 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713020757/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1963YESP.html |archive-date=July 13, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|30\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Dave Stewart and Barbara Gaskin version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = It's My Party\n| cover      = StewartGaskinItsMyParty.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dave Stewart (keyboardist)|Dave Stewart]] with [[Barbara Gaskin]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Waiting in the Wings\n| released   = August 1981<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/broken2|title=45cat - Dave Stewart With Barbara Gaskin - It's My Party / Waiting In The Wings - Stiff - UK - BROKEN 2|publisher=45cat.com|accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| format     = 7\" vinyl\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Synthpop]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]}}\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Stiff Records|Stiff]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Wally Gold|John Gluck Jr.|Herb Weiner}}\n| producer   = Dave Stewart\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Johnny Rocco\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n\nIn 1981, a remake by British artists [[Dave Stewart (keyboardist)|Dave Stewart]] and [[Barbara Gaskin]] was a [[List of number-one singles from the 1980s (UK)|UK number-one hit single]] for four weeks, becoming the first version of the song to reach number one in the UK.<ref name=no1/> The cover also reached number one in Ireland and New Zealand and reached the top 10 in Australia, Austria, Germany, South Africa, and Switzerland. The music video for the Stewart/Gaskin version contained a cameo by [[Thomas Dolby]] as Johnny, Judy being played by Gaskin in a blond wig.\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1981\u20131982)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2372&Itemid=52|title=Australia's (David Kent) Weekly Singles Charts for 1982|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|3|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|17|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|13|chartid=0480|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Denmark ([[Hitlisten]])<ref>https://www.ukmix.org/showthread.php?63915-Danish-Charts-Archive</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|3|songid=801|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=It's My Party|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|20|year=1981|week=48|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|26|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|1|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(H-I).html|title=SA Charts 1965 - 1989 Songs H-I|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|6|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|1|date=19811017|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018|refname=uk2}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|72|artist=Dave Stewart|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1982)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1982|title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|language=German|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand (Recorded Music NZ)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3871|title=End Of Year Charts 1982|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|47\n|}\n\n==Other cover versions==\n{{sources|section|date=February 2018}}\n\n*In 2017, American [[metalcore]] band [[Motionless In White]] parodied \"It's My Party\" for the chorus in \"Necessary Evil\", featuring [[Jonathan Davis]], with lyrics altered to \"It's my party and I'll die when I want to/Die when I want to/Die when I want to\".\n*[[Melanie Martinez (singer)|Melanie Martinez]] sampled the song on her 2015 single \"[[Pity Party (Melanie Martinez song)|Pity Party]].\"\n*The [[Paris Sisters]] recorded a version of \"It's My Party\" which was slower than Gore's version.\n*In 1963, a Swedish-language version of the song, \"Leva livet\", with lyrics by [[Stikkan Anderson]], reached number five in the Swedish hit parade ''[[Svensktoppen]]'' and became a [[signature song]] for the singer, [[Lill-Babs]]. \n*In 1963, [[Richard Anthony (singer)|Richard Anthony]] sang a French version of the song called \"C'est ma f\u00eate\" on [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Richard-Anthony-Cest-Ma-F%C3%AAte/release/9507985|title=Richard Anthony (2) - C'est Ma F\u00eate|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n*[[Donna Reed]] sang a cover version of the song on the 1966 series finale of ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]''.\n*[[Bryan Ferry]] covered the song for his 1973 album ''[[These Foolish Things (album)|These Foolish Things]]''.\n*In 1977, [[Carroll Baker (singer)|Carroll Baker]] had a number one [[country music|country]] hit in Canada with her version of \"It's My Party\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5281&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=fv38leg7c4m9ukfkm8adob1nh4|title=RPM Country Tracks for April 2, 1977|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=November 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610223633/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5281&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=fv38leg7c4m9ukfkm8adob1nh4|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The original version of the song appears in the 1990 film ''[[Problem Child (film)|Problem Child]]''.\n*In 2004, German pop group [[Preluders]] covered the song on their album ''[[Prelude to History]]''.\n*[[Amy Winehouse]] covered the song on Quincy Jones' 2010 album ''[[Q Soul Bossa Nostra]]''.\n*[[Icona Pop]] sampled the song on their 2014 song \"My Party\", featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]].\n\n==Sequel==\nBecause of the pop cultural obsession with the song and its tragic nature, Gore recorded a sequel, \"[[Judy's Turn to Cry]]\". In this song, the teenage girl narrator gets her revenge on Judy. In the lyrics the narrator explicitly finds \"foolish\" how much she cried when she saw Johnny and Judy together, and seems determined to start anew. But after she kisses another boy at another party, Johnny gets jealous, punches the other boy and returns to her.<ref name=allmusic/>  Following just two months on the heels of \"It's My Party,\" the sequel reached number five on the charts.\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1963)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1963)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"Musicoutfitters.com\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|83\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|lesley-gore|its-my-party}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Lesley Gore}}\n{{Carroll Baker (singer)}}\n\n[[Category:Songs about parties]]\n[[Category:1962 songs]]\n[[Category:1963 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Lesley Gore songs]]\n[[Category:Dave Stewart (keyboardist) songs]]\n[[Category:Carroll Baker songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Country Tracks number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Quincy Jones]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wally Gold]]\n[[Category:Helen Shapiro songs]]\n[[Category:Lill-Babs songs]]\n[[Category:Amy Winehouse songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1963 single by Lesley Gore}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = It's My Party\n| cover      = It's My Party single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original US single cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lesley Gore]]\n| album      = [[I'll Cry If I Want To]]\n| B-side     = Danny\n| released   = April 1963\n| format     = 7\" vinyl\n| recorded   = March 30, 1963\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[blue-eyed soul]]}}\n| length     = 2:19\n| label      = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Wally Gold|Walter Gold]]|John Gluck Jr.|Herb Weiner|Seymour Gottlieb}}\n| producer   = [[Quincy Jones]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Judy's Turn to Cry]]\n| next_year  = 1963\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  =\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Lesley Gore - It's My Party.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = EP cover\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''It's My Party'''\" is a pop song recorded by multiple artists since the 1960s. In 1963, American singer [[Lesley Gore]]'s version hit number one on the [[Pop music|pop]] and [[rhythm and blues]] charts in the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=803}}</ref> It was the first hit single for producer [[Quincy Jones]].\n\n==Theme==\nThe song lyrically portrays the discomfort of a [[Adolescence|teenage]] girl at her birthday party when her boyfriend Johnny disappears, only to return in the company of Judy, another girl, who is \"wearing his ring,\" to indicate he has replaced the birthday girl as his love interest.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|title=It's My Party|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/its-my-party-t2601611|author=Ankeny, J.|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=July 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe song's chorus, \"It's my party, and I'll cry if I want to... You would cry too if it happened to you!\" became a part of American pop cultural language as a phrase used to describe being utterly humiliated and miserable during an event that is supposed to be a happy occasion.\n\n\"It's My Party\" is in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[A major]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Musicological identities: essays in honor of Susan McClary|author=McClary, S., Knapp, R., Baur, S. & Warwick, J.C.|page=71|year=2008|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-0-7546-6302-7}}</ref>  The song's effectiveness is enhanced by several musical touches producer Quincy Jones incorporated, including Latin-sounding [[rhythm]]s, [[doubletracking|double tracked]] vocals and effective horn parts.<ref name=allmusic/> [[Allmusic]] critic Jason Ankeny wrote of the song, {{\"'}}It's My Party' remains one of the most vivid evocations of adolescent heartbreak ever waxed\u2014Quincy Jones produced the record, although you'd swear it was [[Aaron Spelling]] instead.\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\n==Background==\n\"It's My Party\" was credited to John Gluck, Wally Gold and Herb Weiner, staff writers at the [[Aaron Schroeder]] Music firm in 1962.  The lyrics were actually written by Seymour Gottlieb, a freelance songwriter.  He gave the lyrics to Herb Weiner, with whom he partnered in writing songs, to peddle.  It was based on actual events relating to Gottlieb's daughter Judy's \u2018Sweet 16\u2019 party, before which she cried over the prospect of her grandparents being invited.<ref name =Gottlieb>{{cite news |last=Tumposky |first= Ellen|date=February 18, 2015 |title= Brooklyn Woman recall origins of Gore's 'It's My Party'|url=http://m.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/brooklyn-woman-recalls-origins-gore-party-article-1.2119662|newspaper=Daily News |location=New York |access-date= February 18, 2015}}</ref>  The demo for the song was cut by Barbara Jean English, a girl group veteran (the Clickettes, the Fashions), who was then working as a receptionist at the firm.  She also worked with [[Jimmy Radcliffe]], serving as the firm's in-house demo singer.  Radcliffe produced the demo, and, according to English, \"tried to persuade Musicor [the label owned by Aaron Schroeder] to release it as a record, or to take me into a master studio and redo it, but they weren't interested.\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\">{{cite web|url-status=dead|url=http://www.chachacharming.com/article.php?id=16&pg=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612170838/http://www.chachacharming.com/article.php?id=16|archivedate=June 12, 2007|title=It's My Party|publisher=Cha Cha Charming Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe first recording of the song was in 1962 by [[The Chiffons]] for their ''One Fine Day'' album.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} It was also recorded by [[Helen Shapiro]] for her ''Helen in Nashville'' album in February 1963 with Shapiro's regular producer, [[Norrie Paramor]], and also [[Al Kasha]].  Shapiro would recall: \"Right from the first time we heard the song on the rough demo back in London, we thought we were going to sock them between the eyes with that one\";<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/>\nhowever, Shapiro's version was not one of the cuts chosen as an advance single from the album and by the time of the album's release that October the \"It's My Party\" track was perceived as a cover of Lesley Gore's hit.\n\nLesley Gore recalls that \"It's My Party\" was among some two hundred demos producer [[Quincy Jones]] brought to review with her in the den of her family home in February 1963.  On hearing \"It's My Party,\" Gore told Jones: \"That's not half bad.  I like it.  Good melody.  Let's put it on the maybe pile.\"  The song proved to be the only demo Gore and Jones found agreeable.  With Jones producing and [[Claus Ogerman]] handling arranging and conducting duties, Gore recorded 'It's My Party' at Bell Sound Studios in [[Manhattan]] on March 30, 1963.<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/><ref name=no1>{{cite book|title=The Billboard book of number 1 hits|author=Bronson, F.|page=130|edition=5|year=2003|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-0-8230-7677-2}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1963 [[Phil Spector]] heard the demo of \"It's My Party\" while visiting Aaron Schroeder's office. Wally Gold would recall: \"He [Spector] said, 'Great, I love it. I\u2019m gonna do it with the Crystals.'  We [the song's writers] were really excited, because that would ensure that the record was #1!\"<ref name=\"bobshannon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bobshannon.com/stories/Party.html |title=Behind The Hits: Stories: It's My Party |accessdate=September 17, 2011 |author=Shannon, Bob |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206100809/http://www.bobshannon.com/stories/Party.html |archivedate=February 6, 2008 }}</ref> Schroeder apparently only learned of the Lesley Gore recording of \"It's My Party\" when Quincy Jones invited him to hear the completed track, which Schroeder found formulaic; believing that Spector would be able to cut a much stronger version of the song with the Crystals and not wanting to lose Spector's good will, Schroeder attempted to convince Jones to suppress the track.  Schroeder did not mention Spector's version to Jones but Jones and Spector both happened to attend a concert with [[Charles Aznavour]] at [[Carnegie Hall]] on the evening of March 30, 1963 and when they met outside it came up in conversation that Spector had recorded a version of \"It's My Party\" with the Crystals.{{#tag:ref|As with \"[[He's a Rebel]]\", the Crystals' hit for which it was intended as the follow-up, \"It's My Party\" was actually recorded not by the Crystals but [[the Blossoms]], who cut the track at [[Gold Star Studios]]. [[Darlene Love]] says the Spector version was \"kinda slow with me and my sister [[Honey Cone|Edna [Wright]]] singing together on lead.  Much more [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] than Lesley Gore's version.\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/>|group=note}} Jones skipped the concert, instead spending that night\u2014a Saturday\u2014at Bell Sound Studios making a test pressing of the track comprising one hundred copies. \n\nOver the next two days Jones mailed these out to radio programmers in key markets across the US.  Gore heard her record played on the radio for the first time that Friday; the official release of \"It's My Party\" came later in the month, with the disc ascending to number one nationally in four weeks.<ref name=\"chachacharming2\" /><ref name=\"bobshannon\" />  Jones was abroad at the time of \"It's My Party\"'s release.  On his return he expressed dismay when Aaron Schroeder advised him that the rush release of \"It's My Party\" had precluded coining a more pleasant name for the singer than \"Lesley Gore,\" to which Schroeder replied: \"Didn't anybody tell you?...Quince, the record's number one.  Do you really give a damn what her last name is?\"<ref name=\"chachacharming2\"/> {{failed verification|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn 1980, [[WCBN-FM]], the [[University of Michigan]] freeform student radio station, played \"It's My Party\" for 18 hours straight the day after [[Ronald Reagan]] was elected.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wcbn.org/history/wcbntime.html | title=CBN History | accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1963)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1681&Itemid=52|title=Australian Weekly Singles Charts(David Kent) from 1963|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qartistid=383#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 4 July 1963]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|9|date=19630717|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19630608.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles, June 8, 1963 |access-date=March 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313044215/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19630608.html |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1963)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"Musicoutfitters.com\">[http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1963.htm Musicoutfitters.com]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1963YESP.html |title=Cash Box Year-End Charts: Top 100 Pop Singles, December 28, 1963 |access-date=March 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713020757/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/1963YESP.html |archive-date=July 13, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|30\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Dave Stewart and Barbara Gaskin version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = It's My Party\n| cover      = StewartGaskinItsMyParty.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dave Stewart (keyboardist)|Dave Stewart]] with [[Barbara Gaskin]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Waiting in the Wings\n| released   = August 1981<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/broken2|title=45cat - Dave Stewart With Barbara Gaskin - It's My Party / Waiting In The Wings - Stiff - UK - BROKEN 2|publisher=45cat.com|accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| format     = 7\" vinyl\n| recorded   = 1981\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Synthpop]]|[[New wave music|new wave]]}}\n| length     = 3:47\n| label      = [[Stiff Records|Stiff]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Wally Gold|John Gluck Jr.|Herb Weiner}}\n| producer   = Dave Stewart\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Johnny Rocco\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n\nIn 1981, a remake by British artists [[Dave Stewart (keyboardist)|Dave Stewart]] and [[Barbara Gaskin]] was a [[List of number-one singles from the 1980s (UK)|UK number-one hit single]] for four weeks, becoming the first version of the song to reach number one in the UK.<ref name=no1/> The cover also reached number one in Ireland and New Zealand and reached the top 10 in Australia, Austria, Germany, South Africa, and Switzerland. The music video for the Stewart/Gaskin version contained a cameo by [[Thomas Dolby]] as Johnny, Judy being played by Gaskin in a blond wig.\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1981\u20131982)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2372&Itemid=52|title=Australia's (David Kent) Weekly Singles Charts for 1982|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|3|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|17|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|13|chartid=0480|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Denmark ([[Hitlisten]])<ref>https://www.ukmix.org/showthread.php?63915-Danish-Charts-Archive</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|3|songid=801|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=It's My Party|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|20|year=1981|week=48|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|26|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|1|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(H-I).html|title=SA Charts 1965 - 1989 Songs H-I|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|6|song=It's My Party|artist=Dave Stewart with Barbara Gaskin|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|1|date=19811017|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018|refname=uk2}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|72|artist=Dave Stewart|rowheader=true|accessdate=17 May 2018}}\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1982)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1982|title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment]]|language=German|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand (Recorded Music NZ)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3871|title=End Of Year Charts 1982|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|47\n|}\n\n==Other cover versions==\n{{sources|section|date=February 2018}}\n\n*In 2017, American [[metalcore]] band [[Motionless In White]] parodied \"It's My Party\" for the chorus in \"Necessary Evil\", featuring [[Jonathan Davis]], with lyrics altered to \"It's my party and I'll die when I want to/Die when I want to/Die when I want to\".\n*[[Melanie Martinez (singer)|Melanie Martinez]] sampled the song on her 2015 single \"[[Pity Party (Melanie Martinez song)|Pity Party]].\"\n*The [[Paris Sisters]] recorded a version of \"It's My Party\" which was slower than Gore's version.\n*In 1963, a Swedish-language version of the song, \"Leva livet\", with lyrics by [[Stikkan Anderson]], reached number five in the Swedish hit parade ''[[Svensktoppen]]'' and became a [[signature song]] for the singer, [[Lill-Babs]]. \n*In 1963, [[Richard Anthony (singer)|Richard Anthony]] sang a French version of the song called \"C'est ma f\u00eate\" on [[Columbia Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Richard-Anthony-Cest-Ma-F%C3%AAte/release/9507985|title=Richard Anthony (2) - C'est Ma F\u00eate|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>.\n*[[Donna Reed]] sang a cover version of the song on the 1966 series finale of ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]''.\n*[[Bryan Ferry]] covered the song for his 1973 album ''[[These Foolish Things (album)|These Foolish Things]]''.\n*In 1977, [[Carroll Baker (singer)|Carroll Baker]] had a number one [[country music|country]] hit in Canada with her version of \"It's My Party\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5281&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=fv38leg7c4m9ukfkm8adob1nh4|title=RPM Country Tracks for April 2, 1977|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=November 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610223633/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.5281&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=fv38leg7c4m9ukfkm8adob1nh4|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The original version of the song appears in the 1990 film ''[[Problem Child (film)|Problem Child]]''.\n*In 2004, German pop group [[Preluders]] covered the song on their album ''[[Prelude to History]]''.\n*[[Amy Winehouse]] covered the song on Quincy Jones' 2010 album ''[[Q Soul Bossa Nostra]]''.\n*[[Icona Pop]] sampled the song on their 2014 song \"My Party\", featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]].\n\n==Sequel==\nBecause of the pop cultural obsession with the song and its tragic nature, Gore recorded a sequel, \"[[Judy's Turn to Cry]]\". In this song, the teenage girl narrator gets her revenge on Judy. In the lyrics the narrator explicitly finds \"foolish\" how much she cried when she saw Johnny and Judy together, and seems determined to start anew. But after she kisses another boy at another party, Johnny gets jealous, punches the other boy and returns to her.<ref name=allmusic/>  Following just two months on the heels of \"It's My Party,\" the sequel reached number five on the charts.\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Chart (1963)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1963)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"Musicoutfitters.com\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|83\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|lesley-gore|its-my-party}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Lesley Gore}}\n{{Carroll Baker (singer)}}\n\n[[Category:Songs about parties]]\n[[Category:1962 songs]]\n[[Category:1963 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Lesley Gore songs]]\n[[Category:Dave Stewart (keyboardist) songs]]\n[[Category:Carroll Baker songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Country Tracks number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Quincy Jones]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wally Gold]]\n[[Category:Helen Shapiro songs]]\n[[Category:Lill-Babs songs]]\n[[Category:Amy Winehouse songs]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It%27s_My_Party_(Lesley_Gore_song)"}
{"title_page": "Issaquah School District", "text_new": "{{other uses2|Issaquah}}\n[[File:Issaquah School District logo.png|frame|right|The Issaquah School District's logo]]\n\n'''Issaquah School District No. 411''' is a public [[school district]] in [[King County, Washington]], [[United States|USA]], serving the city of [[Issaquah, Washington|Issaquah]] as well as portions of [[Sammamish, Washington|Sammamish]], [[Renton, Washington|Renton]], [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]], and [[Newcastle, Washington|Newcastle]].\n\nAs of the 2018-19 school year, the district has an enrollment of 20,965<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/summary.aspx?groupLevel=District&schoolId=114&reportLevel=District&yrs=2015-16&year=2015-16|title=Washington State Report Card|website=reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> with 24 total schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.issaquah.wednet.edu/schools|title=Schools|last=|first=|date=|website=Issaquah School District|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Schools==\n\n===High schools (9-12th grades)===\n*[[Issaquah High School]], is located south of downtown [[Issaquah]], and is expectedly the district's oldest high school. IHS opened in 1905 and moved to its present location in 1962. School colors: Purple & Gold. Mascot: Eagles.\n*[[Liberty Senior High School]], opened in 1977 at the southwest region of the district. LHS was named the National Blue Ribbon school in 1999 and was recognized in [[Washington, D.C.]] School colors: Silver, Green, & Blue. Mascot: Patriots.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu/ |title=Liberty High School |publisher=Liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981205161512/http://www.liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu/ |archivedate=1998-12-05 }}</ref>\n*[[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline High School]] is the district's newest high school, opening its doors in 1997. Located in [[Sammamish, Washington|Sammamish]] on the northern boundary of the district, Skyline serves as a community center for the city of Sammamish. School colors: Green & Silver. Mascot: Spartans.\n*[[Gibson Ek High School]], opened in the fall of 2016 at the previous location of Issaquah Middle School. Gibson Ek is a choice high school that places emphasis on real world experience. Students are allowed to explore career options with the help of volunteer mentors and are required to go to internships on Tuesdays and Thursdays. Mascot: Griffins.\n\n=== Middle schools (6-8th grades) ===\n*[[Beaver Lake Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline]] Mascot: Bulldogs<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.issaquahreporter.com/news/beloved-mascot-of-sammamish-school-to-live-on-in-bronze-statue-after-retirement/|title=Beloved mascot of Sammamish school to live on in bronze statue after retirement {{!}} Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|date=2018-01-31|work=Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.issaquahreporter.com/news/beaver-lake-middle-school-honors-beloved-bulldogs-legacy/|title=Beaver Lake Middle School honors beloved bulldog\u2019s legacy {{!}} Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|date=2018-01-29|work=Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}<</ref>\n*[[Issaquah Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Issaquah High School|Issaquah]] & [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. Mascot: Panther\n*[[Maywood Middle School (Issaquah, Washington)|Maywood Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. Mascot: Chargers\n*[[Pine Lake Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline]]. Mascot: Wolverine\n*[[Pacific Cascade Middle School]] - formerly [[Pacific Cascade Freshman Campus]], feeder school for [[Issaquah High School]]. Mascot: Lynx\n\n=== Elementary schools (K-5) ===\n*Apollo Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. It is also a host site for the district's Mind Education \u2013 Right and Left (brain) Integration (MERLIN) program.\n*Briarwood Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]] (New school opening in fall 2012)\n*Cascade Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline\n*Challenger Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline\n*Clark Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Cougar Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah & Maywood Middle Schools, and Liberty & Issaquah High Schools\n*Creekside Elementary School - feeder school for Pine Lake and Skyline\n*Discovery Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pine Lake, Beaver Lake, and Skyline\n*Endeavour Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline. It is also a host site for the district's Mind Education \u2013 Right and Left (brain) Integration (MERLIN) program.\n*Grand Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pacific Cascade Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Issaquah Valley Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Maple Hills Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]\n*Newcastle Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]\n*Sunny Hills Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pine Lake Middle, Pacific Cascade Middle, Skyline High and Issaquah High School\n*Sunset Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pacific Cascade Middle and Issaquah High School\n\n=== Closed schools ===\n*[[Tiger Mountain Community High School]] was a high school serving students throughout the district who seek an alternative to the traditional high school environment. Each student is given personalized lessons and support by the staff which adds to the alternative style of education. Tiger Mountain is also the site for a regional high tech learning center serving students throughout the region. This school closed after the 2015-16 school year.\n\n==In the news==\n\n===2002 District strike===\nThe Issaquah School District teachers' union voted to strike which in turn left Issaquah schools to be closed from the opening day of school, September 4, until September 26 \u2013 closing the school for a total of three weeks; fifteen total school days. An agreement was made on September 25 ratified by a 740-45 majority vote cast by the teachers at [[Issaquah High School]], relieving the teachers of the threats of fines that would be put in place because the teachers voted to defy a [[King County Superior Court]] injunction calling for the teachers to return to work.<ref name=\"seattlepi.nwsource.com\">{{cite news \n  | last = Roberts\n  | first = Gregory\n  | title = All sides -- including kids -- voice relief at Issaquah strike's resolution\n  | pages = \n  | publisher = The Seattle Post Intelligencer\n  | date = 2002-09-26\n  | url = http://www.seattlepi.com/local/88661_schools26.shtml\n  | accessdate = 2008-09-18 }}\n</ref> Resulting from the strike was a 3.8 percent pay increase over two years; ninety-five percent being covered by state aid. An additional $250 \"return to work incentive\" was offered to all teachers as well as a $500 bonus the following year. Because of the increased incentive to return to work, more staff was gained in that year than during any previous year.<ref name=\"seattlepi.nwsource.com\"/>\n\n===2006 Bus driver termination===\nAn Issaquah School District bus driver now identified as Staci LaManna was fired in September 2006 when she allegedly \"flipped off\" former [[United States]] [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in June 2006 while she was transporting a group of students back from a field trip to the [[Woodland Park Zoo]].<ref>[http://www.local6.com/education/10222137/detail.html School Fires Driver For Giving Bush The Finger - Education News Story - WKMG Orlando] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301093514/http://www.local6.com/education/10222137/detail.html |date=March 1, 2007 }}</ref> The 43-year-old driver has filed a union grievance for wrongful termination.<ref>\n{{cite news \n  | last = Tuinstra\n  | first = Rachel\n  | title = She flipped off president, wants old job\n  | pages = \n  | publisher = The Seattle Times\n  | date = 2006-12-29\n  | url = https://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003500087_endbusdriver29m.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}\n</ref>\nThe Issaquah School District stated that the termination was a result of a \"pattern of behavior\" and not for any political reasons.<ref>\n{{cite news\n |last        = Postman\n |first       = David\n |title       = District says driver did more than flip the bird to Bush\n |publisher   = The Seattle Times\n |date        = 2006-11-01\n |url         = http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/davidpostman/archives/2006/11/district_says_driver_did_more_than_flip_the_bird_to_bush.html\n |accessdate  = 2008-02-10\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110520114240/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/davidpostman/archives/2006/11/district_says_driver_did_more_than_flip_the_bird_to_bush.html\n |archivedate = 2011-05-20\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===2014 Rape and subsequent victim harassment campaign===\nIn 2014 a 16-year-old girl was raped by two members of the [[Skyline High School (Washington)|Skyline]] football team. She reported it, they were convicted and a protective order forced the rapists off the team and out of the school. The community and coaches responded by starting a targeted harassment campaign of the victim and her younger sister that included online bullying, personal confrontations, firebombing the victims house, planting drugs on her, and prominently featuring the rapists during her graduation ceremony attempting to force her to move to another school so the rapists could come back and play for Skyline. After her graduation the harassment continued against her younger sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mynorthwest.com/1160574/suing-issaquah-school-bullying-lawsuit/|title=2 women suing Issaquah School District for bullying, retaliation|accessdate=26 October 2018|publisher=Bonneville International}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/rape-victim-files-suit-against-issaquah-school-district-for-refusing-to-investigate-abuse|title=Rape victim's suit against Issaquah School District claims they didn't investigate abuse|accessdate=26 October 2018|publisher=Sinclair Broadcast Group}}</ref>\n\n===2015 District Walkout===\nAll schools in the Issaquah School District were closed on May 19, 2015 when the Issaquah School District Teacher's Union voted to go on strike to earn more funding from the state for Washington's schools. Thousands of teachers of the Issaquah School District, [[Mercer Island School District]], and [[Seattle School District]] filled the streets of [[Downtown Seattle]] and traveled from the [[Seattle Center]] to [[Westlake Park (Seattle)|Westlake Park]]. The commotion caused by this walkout caused some senators in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]] to propose a bill to decrease teacher's pay while on strike, but this proposal was not accepted by many senators.<ref>[http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/no-school-for-thousands-of-kids-as-teachers-hold-1-day-walkout/ Thousands of teachers hit streets in Seattle \u2014 and Dems walk out, too]</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Enrollment by Ethnicity<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Ethnicity\n!'''2014-15'''\n!2015-16\n!2016-17\n!2017-18\n!2018-19\n|-\n|White\n|11,499 (59.2%)\n|11,380 (57.2%)\n|11,317 (55.1%)\n|11,129 (53%)\n|10,772 (51.4%)\n|-\n|Asian\n|4,751 (24.5%)\n|5,126 (25.8%)\n|5,581 (27.2%)\n|6,042 (28.8%)\n|6,260 (29.9%)\n|-\n|Hispanic/Latino\n|1,505 (7.7%)\n|1,579 (7.9%)\n|1,712 (8.3%)\n|1,765 (8.4%)\n|1,793 (8.6%)\n|-\n|Two or More Races\n|1,227 (6.3%)\n|1,366 (6.9%)\n|1,474 (7.2%)\n|1,591 (7.6%)\n|1,661 (7.9%)\n|-\n|Black/African American\n|341 (1.8%)\n|335 (1.7%)\n|359 (1.7%)\n|391 (1.9%)\n|405 (1.9%)\n|-\n|American Indian/Alaskan Native\n|40 (0.2%)\n|39 (0.2%)\n|45 (0.2%)\n|32 (0.2%)\n|31 (0.1%)\n|-\n|'''Total Enrollment'''\n|'''19,425'''\n|'''19,883'''\n|'''20,540'''\n|'''21,000'''\n|'''20,965'''\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Enrollment by Gender<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Gender\n!'''2014-15'''\n!2015-16\n!2016-17\n!2017-18\n!2018-19\n|-\n|Male\n|9,883 (50.9%)\n|10,140 (51%)\n|10,475 (51.0%)\n|10,808 (51.5%)\n|10,802 (51.5%)\n|-\n|Female\n|9,542 (49.1%)\n|9,743 (49%)\n|10,065 (49%)\n|10,192 (48.5%)\n|10,163 (48.5%)\n|-\n|'''Total Enrollment'''\n|'''19,425'''\n|'''19,883'''\n|'''20,540'''\n|'''21,000'''\n|'''20,965'''\n|}\nAs of May 2016, 7.9% of students are on free or reduced-price meal programs.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Staff ==\nIn the district, as of 2016, there are 1029 classroom teachers. Of these, 696 (67.7%) have at least a master's degree. Teachers have an average of 10.6 years of experience in the district.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.issaquah.wednet.edu/ Issaquah School District No. 411]\n*[http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/?schoolId=114 Issaquah School District Report Card]\n{{Bellevue, Washington}}\n\n[[Category:School districts in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Issaquah, Washington]]\n[[Category:Education in King County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Education in Sammamish, Washington]]\n[[Category:Education in Renton, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|Issaquah}}\n[[File:Issaquah School District logo.png|frame|right|The Issaquah School District's logo]]\n\n'''Issaquah School District No. 411''' is a public [[school district]] in [[King County, Washington]], [[United States|USA]], serving the city of [[Issaquah, Washington|Issaquah]] as well as portions of [[Sammamish, Washington|Sammamish]], [[Renton, Washington|Renton]], [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]], and [[Newcastle, Washington|Newcastle]].\n\nAs of the 2018-19 school year, the district has an enrollment of 20,965<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us/summary.aspx?groupLevel=District&schoolId=114&reportLevel=District&yrs=2015-16&year=2015-16|title=Washington State Report Card|website=reportcard.ospi.k12.wa.us|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> with 24 total schools<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.issaquah.wednet.edu/schools|title=Schools|last=|first=|date=|website=Issaquah School District|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Schools==\n\n===High schools (9-12th grades)===\n*[[Issaquah High School]], is located south of downtown [[Issaquah]], and is expectedly the district's oldest high school. IHS opened in 1905 and moved to its present location in 1962. School colors: Purple & Gold. Mascot: Eagles.\n*[[Liberty Senior High School]], opened in 1977 at the southwest region of the district. LHS was named the National Blue Ribbon school in 1999 and was recognized in [[Washington, D.C.]] School colors: Silver, Green, & Blue. Mascot: Patriots.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu/ |title=Liberty High School |publisher=Liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981205161512/http://www.liberty.issaquah.wednet.edu/ |archivedate=1998-12-05 }}</ref>\n*[[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline High School]] is the district's newest high school, opening its doors in 1997. Located in [[Sammamish, Washington|Sammamish]] on the northern boundary of the district, Skyline serves as a community center for the city of Sammamish. School colors: Green & Silver. Mascot: Spartans.\n*[[Gibson Ek High School]], opened in the fall of 2016 at the previous location of Issaquah Middle School. Gibson Ek is a choice high school that places emphasis on real world experience. Students are allowed to explore career options with the help of volunteer mentors and are required to go to internships on Tuesdays and Thursdays. Mascot: Griffins.\n\n=== Middle schools (6-8th grades) ===\n*[[Beaver Lake Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline]] Mascot: Bulldogs<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.issaquahreporter.com/news/beloved-mascot-of-sammamish-school-to-live-on-in-bronze-statue-after-retirement/|title=Beloved mascot of Sammamish school to live on in bronze statue after retirement {{!}} Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|date=2018-01-31|work=Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.issaquahreporter.com/news/beaver-lake-middle-school-honors-beloved-bulldogs-legacy/|title=Beaver Lake Middle School honors beloved bulldog\u2019s legacy {{!}} Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|date=2018-01-29|work=Issaquah-Sammamish Reporter|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}<</ref>\n*[[Issaquah Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Issaquah High School|Issaquah]] & [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. Mascot: Panther\n*[[Maywood Middle School (Issaquah, Washington)|Maywood Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. Mascot: Chargers\n*[[Pine Lake Middle School]] \u2013 feeder school for [[Skyline High School (Sammamish, Washington)|Skyline]]. Mascot: Wolverine\n*[[Pacific Cascade Middle School]] - formerly [[Pacific Cascade Freshman Campus]], feeder school for [[Issaquah High School]]. Mascot: Lynx\n\n=== Elementary schools (K-5) ===\n*Apollo Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]. It is also a host site for the district's Mind Education \u2013 Right and Left (brain) Integration (MERLIN) program.\n*Briarwood Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]] (New school opening in fall 2012)\n*Cascade Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline\n*Challenger Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline\n*Clark Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Cougar Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah & Maywood Middle Schools, and Liberty & Issaquah High Schools\n*Creekside Elementary School - feeder school for Pine Lake and Skyline\n*Discovery Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pine Lake, Beaver Lake, and Skyline\n*Endeavour Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Beaver Lake and Skyline. It is also a host site for the district's Mind Education \u2013 Right and Left (brain) Integration (MERLIN) program.\n*Grand Ridge Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pacific Cascade Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Issaquah Valley Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Issaquah Middle and Issaquah High School\n*Maple Hills Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]\n*Newcastle Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Maywood and [[Liberty Senior High School|Liberty]]\n*Sunny Hills Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pine Lake Middle, Pacific Cascade Middle, Skyline High and Issaquah High School\n*Sunset Elementary School \u2013 feeder school for Pacific Cascade Middle and Issaquah High School\n\n=== Closed schools ===\n*[[Tiger Mountain Community High School]] was a high school serving students throughout the district who seek an alternative to the traditional high school environment. Each student is given personalized lessons and support by the staff which adds to the alternative style of education. Tiger Mountain is also the site for a regional high tech learning center serving students throughout the region. This school closed after the 2015-16 school year.\n\n==In the news==\n\n===2002 District strike===\nThe Issaquah School District teachers' union voted to strike which in turn left Issaquah schools to be closed from the opening day of school, September 4, until September 26 \u2013 closing the school for a total of three weeks; fifteen total school days. An agreement was made on September 25 ratified by a 740-45 majority vote cast by the teachers at [[Issaquah High School]], relieving the teachers of the threats of fines that would be put in place because the teachers voted to defy a [[King County Superior Court]] injunction calling for the teachers to return to work.<ref name=\"seattlepi.nwsource.com\">{{cite news \n  | last = Roberts\n  | first = Gregory\n  | title = All sides -- including kids -- voice relief at Issaquah strike's resolution\n  | pages = \n  | publisher = The Seattle Post Intelligencer\n  | date = 2002-09-26\n  | url = http://www.seattlepi.com/local/88661_schools26.shtml\n  | accessdate = 2008-09-18 }}\n</ref> Resulting from the strike was a 3.8 percent pay increase over two years; ninety-five percent being covered by state aid. An additional $250 \"return to work incentive\" was offered to all teachers as well as a $500 bonus the following year. Because of the increased incentive to return to work, more staff was gained in that year than during any previous year.<ref name=\"seattlepi.nwsource.com\"/>\n\n===2006 Bus driver termination===\nAn Issaquah School District bus driver now identified as Staci LaManna was fired in September 2006 when she allegedly \"flipped off\" former [[United States]] [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] in June 2006 while she was transporting a group of students back from a field trip to the [[Woodland Park Zoo]].<ref>[http://www.local6.com/education/10222137/detail.html School Fires Driver For Giving Bush The Finger - Education News Story - WKMG Orlando] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301093514/http://www.local6.com/education/10222137/detail.html |date=March 1, 2007 }}</ref> The 43-year-old driver has filed a union grievance for wrongful termination.<ref>\n{{cite news \n  | last = Tuinstra\n  | first = Rachel\n  | title = She flipped off president, wants old job\n  | pages = \n  | publisher = The Seattle Times\n  | date = 2006-12-29\n  | url = https://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003500087_endbusdriver29m.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}\n</ref>\nThe Issaquah School District stated that the termination was a result of a \"pattern of behavior\" and not for any political reasons.<ref>\n{{cite news\n |last        = Postman\n |first       = David\n |title       = District says driver did more than flip the bird to Bush\n |publisher   = The Seattle Times\n |date        = 2006-11-01\n |url         = http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/davidpostman/archives/2006/11/district_says_driver_did_more_than_flip_the_bird_to_bush.html\n |accessdate  = 2008-02-10\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110520114240/http://blog.seattletimes.nwsource.com/davidpostman/archives/2006/11/district_says_driver_did_more_than_flip_the_bird_to_bush.html\n |archivedate = 2011-05-20\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===2014 Rape and subsequent victim harassment campaign===\nIn 2014 a 16-year-old girl was raped by two members of the [[Skyline High School (Washington)|Skyline]] football team. She reported it, they were convicted and a protective order forced the rapists off the team and out of the school. The community and coaches responded by starting a targeted harassment campaign of the victim and her younger sister that included online bullying, personal confrontations, firebombing the victims house, planting drugs on her, and prominently featuring the rapists during her graduation ceremony attempting to force her to move to another school so the rapists could come back and play for Skyline. After her graduation the harassment continued against her younger sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mynorthwest.com/1160574/suing-issaquah-school-bullying-lawsuit/|title=2 women suing Issaquah School District for bullying, retaliation|accessdate=26 October 2018|publisher=Bonneville International}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://komonews.com/news/local/rape-victim-files-suit-against-issaquah-school-district-for-refusing-to-investigate-abuse|title=Rape victim's suit against Issaquah School District claims they didn't investigate abuse|accessdate=26 October 2018|publisher=Sinclair Broadcast Group}}</ref>\n\n===2015 District Walkout===\nAll schools in the Issaquah School District were closed on May 19, 2015 when the Issaquah School District Teacher's Union voted to go on strike to earn more funding from the state for Washington's schools. Thousands of teachers of the Issaquah School District, [[Mercer Island School District]], and [[Seattle School District]] filled the streets of [[Downtown Seattle]] and traveled from the [[Seattle Center]] to [[Westlake Park (Seattle)|Westlake Park]]. The commotion caused by this walkout caused some senators in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]] to propose a bill to decrease teacher's pay while on strike, but this proposal was not accepted by many senators.<ref>[http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/no-school-for-thousands-of-kids-as-teachers-hold-1-day-walkout/ Thousands of teachers hit streets in Seattle \u2014 and Dems walk out, too]</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Enrollment by Ethnicity<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Ethnicity\n!'''2014-15'''\n!2015-16\n!2016-17\n!2017-18\n!2018-19\n|-\n|White\n|11,499 (59.2%)\n|11,380 (57.2%)\n|11,317 (55.1%)\n|11,129 (53%)\n|10,772 (51.4%)\n|-\n|Asian\n|4,751 (24.5%)\n|5,126 (25.8%)\n|5,581 (27.2%)\n|6,042 (28.8%)\n|6,260 (29.9%)\n|-\n|Hispanic/Latino\n|1,505 (7.7%)\n|1,579 (7.9%)\n|1,712 (8.3%)\n|1,765 (8.4%)\n|1,793 (8.6%)\n|-\n|Two or More Races\n|1,227 (6.3%)\n|1,366 (6.9%)\n|1,474 (7.2%)\n|1,5